<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Inflation     07-10 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Inflation,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Inflation Lowest In a Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico has recorded its lowest inflation rate
in a decade, and June's 1.2 percent increase in consumer prices put
the 12-month inflation rate at 17.6 percent, the Bank of Mexico
reports.
   Inflation hit an all-time high of 159.2 percent in 1987, then
dropped to 51.7 percent in 1988.
   June's was the lowest increase in the consumer price index since
July 1979 and brought inflation for the six months ending June 30 to
9.3 percent.
   It was also the lowest for a first semester since 1978, when
prices rose by an average of 8.4 percent, the bank said Sunday in
its monthly report.
   Economists tie the sharp drop in inflation to a government
agreement with labor and management instituted in late 1987 that
freezes wages and prices for an average of six months at a time and
keeps increases at a minimum.
   During the last round of talks, all three sides agreed July 1 to
raise the minimum wage by an average of 6.5 percent nationwide and
continue the program until next March, with another round of
negotiations in December.
</TEXT>
