<FIRST>r i PM-Baker-Reporter'sNotebook     07-10 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Reporter's Notebook,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, a Critic of Authoritarian Rulers, Rubs Elbows With Them on
Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA_ ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has welcomed the
global trend away from authoritarian rule, but at least two stops on
Secretary of State James A. Baker III's swing through Asia and
Europe seem immune to such democratic changes.
   Baker has spent much of the past four days in Brunei and Oman,
both sultanates that are virtually devoid of the democratic
trappings normally advocated by the United States.
   In this Arabian Peninsula nation, there are no political parties,
no legislature and no elections. All power rests with Sultan Qaboos,
the latest in a line of monarchs who have ruled this Kansas-sized
land since the 1740s.
   Baker decided to stop off in Oman mainly to rest before joining
President Bush in Poland, the first stop on a four-nation European
tour.
   Oman was chosen in part because few Arab nations, if any, are
friendlier to the United States. Oman was one of the first Arab
nations that endorsed the 1978 Camp David peace agreement between
Egypt and Israel.
   As authoritarian rulers go, Qaboos appears to be more benign than
most. When he deposed his father in 1970, Oman was a land plagued by
poverty, disease and illiteracy.
   In 19 years, Qaboos has been able to forge what is for the most
part a modern, prosperous nation, overcoming such obstacles as a
forbidding climate that often sends temperatures above 130 degrees.
   According to State Department figures, there were only three
schools in Oman in 1970. In 1986, there were 697. The number of
hospital beds rose from 12 to 2,800 in the same time period.
   Oil helped finance the boom, much as it did in Baker's previous
stop, Brunei.
   Unlike Oman, Brunei has a constitution, but it provides Sultan
Hassanal Bolkiah with supreme executive authority.
   The occasion for Baker's visit to Brunei was the annual meeting
of the six-member Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   Like Oman, Brunei has a system with a social conscience,
providing subsidized food, fuel, housing, free education and medical
care.
   Brunei's 250,000 citizens enjoy an unusually high standard of
living, which permits them to over look the opulent lifestyle of
their ruler and his two wives.
   The main attraction in Brunei, about the size of Delaware, is the
sultan's palace, a 1,788-room extravaganza with a dining room
capable of accommodating 6,000 for a sit-down meal. Need a bathroom?
The palace has more than 200.
   Amid such abundance, the sultan is somewhat wary about
inquisitive reporters. Before the start of the ASEAN conference,
reporters were told to write about the conference, not about Brunei.
   Still, the sultan has been unable to conceal his role as perhaps
the world's richest man, with an estimated wealth of $28 billion,
almost four times the gross national product of Oman.
   He is one of a handful of men who has claim to a fortune that
dwarfs the estimated $3 billion to $5 billion of Zaire's autocratic
president, Mobutu Sese Seko, the last foreign leader whom Baker
entertained before departing on his tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
