<FIRST>r a PM-SweatLodge     07-10 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweat Lodge,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Inmates Hold First Sweat Lodge Ceremony in Utah Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT OF THE MOUNTAIN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian inmate pounded a
drum outside a canvas dome, while inside a purification ceremony
capped a two-year legal battle over the religious rite.
   With Saturday's ceremony at the State Prison, Utah became the
19th state to allow Indian sweat lodges on prison grounds.
Corrections officials had resisted the rituals, arguing they posed a
security risk.
   ``This shows you can make anything work as long as you put your
heart in it. We pray for positiveness and unity,'' said Arvol
Looking Horse, Keeper of the Pipe for the Sioux Nation.
   A group of prisoners in 1987 sued to get the sweat lodges, and
U.S. District Court Judge J. Thomas Greene ruled in March that the
prohibition was unreasonable because it meant that ``the Native
American religion was not being accommodated to the extent other
religions are.''
   ``It was fun to win this thing,'' said Danny Quintana, who
represented the inmates in the court battle. ``I was very happy with
the way it turned out.''
   The sweat lodge is a small dome built of willow branch poles
covered with blankets and canvas.
   On Saturday, worshipers entered the sweat lodge, poured water
over a bed of heated rocks and recited prayers.
   Outside the dome, inmates played a water drum and gourd and
chanted and sang as part of the traditional ceremony.
   Nine Indian inmates from the Blackfoot, Shoshone, Sioux and
Navajo tribes participated in the two-hour ceremony.
   ``It's something big for them today. Something they can look
forward to,'' said Robert Eagleman, of the Navajo Nation Corrections
Project.
   Darrell Gardner, a medicine man who built the lodge and will run
the rituals on Saturdays, said the religious experience will have a
definite impact on the practicing inmates.
   ``They're gonna be different people. It changes them and we'll
all benefit from it,'' Gardner said.
   Tribal officials say the sweat lodge is central to purification
and ceremonial rites that date back thousands of years.
   Prison officials claimed the rituals threatened security because
the lodge must be dark and enclosed. Greene's ruling stipulated that
prison guards could dismantle the lodge after each weekly ceremony.
The assembly of the lodge takes only a few hours.
</TEXT>
