<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina-Malvinas     07-10 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina-Malvinas,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Argentina, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly inaugurated President Carlos
Menem has suggested Argentina and Britain temporarily set aside
their claims to the Falkland Islands, and meet to discuss the
resumption of diplomatic relations.
   ``If Mrs. Thatcher doesn't insist on the issue of sovereignty, we
won't, either,'' Menem told a news conference Sunday. ``Meanwhile,
we could advance in the dialogue toward re-establishing relations.''
   The two countries went to war in 1982 over the windswept,
sparsely populated islands that are 350 miles east of southern
Argentina. Britain won and diplomatic relations were never resumed.
   The government of President Raul Alfonsin, which left office
Saturday, always insisted that sovereignty over the islands claimed
by both countries _ but ruled by Britain since 1833 _ be an issue in
bilateral negotiations.
   Menem's position on the ownership of the islands that Argentines
call the Malvinas is clear: ``We are convinced that the Malvinas are
Argentina's.''
</TEXT>
