<DOCNO> AP890710-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HouseRaces     07-10 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Races,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Elections Will Fill Pepper, Wright, Coelho Seats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans have high hopes of claiming Claude
Pepper's old House seat in one of three Sunbelt special elections
this summer, but face tougher odds in races to replace Democrats who
left because of ethical problems.
   Republican prospects appear dimmest in Texas, where former
Speaker Jim Wright quit after a GOP-sponsored ethics investigation.
Democrats expect a former aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen to hold the
seat for them.
   California shapes up as the most competitive of the three races
in a district that regularly elected Democrat Tony Coelho but where
his party owns only a narrow margin in voter registration. Coelho
quit unexpectedly last month rather than face an ethics probe into
his finances.
   The results in the three races will have scant impact on the
balance of power in the House, where Democrats hold a 257-175
majority and have held power for more than three decades.
   But the contests represent the first congressional balloting
since Democrats became ensnared in the ethics difficulties _ and
since Republicans were criticized for a memo that compared Speaker
Thomas Foley's voting record to that of Rep. Barney Frank of
Massachusetts, an openly homosexual lawmaker.
   Democrats see a battle for the Florida seat held by Pepper, who
died May 30.
   ``This is going to be a tough seat for us, no question about
that,'' said Howard Schloss, spokesman for the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee. ``The demographics have switched
in the years since Claude Pepper and we're going to have a tough
battle on our hands to hold on.''
   Cuban-Americans are now 40 percent of the Miami district's
voters. Wrathful toward the Havana government, they are
overwhelmingly Republican.
   ``The votes are going to go to the one who hates (Fidel) Castro
the most and loves Ollie (North) the most,'' says California-based
lobbyist Arnoldo Torres.
   Two Cuban-Americans _ state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen and
millionaire businessman Carlos Perez, a prominent fund-raiser for
North _ are dueling for the GOP nomination in the Aug. 1 primary.
Former North Miami Mayor John Stembridge and insurance broker David
M. Fleischer also are on the GOP ballot.
   Among Democrats, Miami City Commissioner Rosario Kennedy has
strong labor support while Joanne Pepper, the late congressman's
niece, is running a law-and-order, anti-drug campaign that includes
prowling the streets with a police SWAT team.
   Six other Democrats are in the field. But party officials
nationally are glum about the district, and Republicans are taking
care not to appear overconfident.
   Both parties say Democratic chances are better in Coelho's old
California district, which extends through the heavily agricultural
Central Valley, and Wright's bastion around Fort Worth.
   ``We know the Republicans will put up a strong battle in
California, but we're confident that we can hold both seats,''
Democratic spokesman Schloss said.
   In California, a battle is shaping up between conservative state
Rep. Gary Condit, D-Modesto, and former state Food and Agriculture
Director Clare Berryhill, a Republican, in what could turn out to be
a 10-candidate open primary.
   Republican, Democratic and minor party candidates will face off
on the same ballot Sept. 12. Any contender gaining a majority gets a
ticket to Washington. Otherwise, the top Republican and top Democrat
meet in a runoff.
   Berryhill, 64, has strong conservative credentials and another
advantage in the crop-rich valley. ``He is known as a supporter of
the interests of the agricultural community,'' says agricultural
consultant William Lesher.
   With a slight Democratic edge in registration district-wide,
Condit hopes to win the seat outright in September. Berryhill says
his strategy will be to hold Condit to 50 percent or less, and then
face him one-on-one in the November runoff.
   In Texas, Bentsen's backing for 37-year-old attorney Pete Geren
may have discouraged other Democrats.
   Austin political consultant George Christian says the senator's
support represents ``a sort of Good Housekeeping seal of approval''
among Democrats.
   ``I think in a special election where you've got a man who gets
in the race with obvious support and obvious money, then another
fella who wants to get in the race certainly has a big mountain to
climb,'' he said.
   All the candidates clash on one ballot Aug. 12, with a runoff
later in the month between the top two vote-getters, regardless of
party, if no one gets a majority.
   Among Republicans, Dr. Bob Lanier, host of a television health
show, has been boasting of high name recognition.
   Larraine Bethke, a Republican former congressional staffer, is
also running along with Democrat-turned-Republican Jim Hunter, who
lost in an earlier bid for sheriff.
</TEXT>
