<FIRST>u a AM-JailRiot 1stLd-Writethru a0445 07-10 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jail Riot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0445,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot At California Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details, quotes from witnesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANNING, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A riot erupted in a prison late Sunday,
with a barracks engulfed in flames and as many as 12 people injured,
a fire dispatcher said.
   The riot broke out at 10 p.m. at the Banning Road Camp
Rehabilitation Center, and one barrack was destroyed by fire, said
Bonnie Underwood, a Riverside County Fire Department dispatcher.
   Fire Department paramedics had not been able to confirm the exact
number of injuries because they were not immediately allowed inside
the minimum- and maxmimum-security camp, which holds between 300 and
400 inmates, said Underwood.
   She said no deaths were reported.
   Tim Lewis, who lives across the street from the center, said that
at about 10:15 p.m. he heard a ``large explosion, like a sonic
blast.''
   ``The whole place is in flames,'' he said. ``There are flames
leaping up 50, 60, 70 feet high. And there must be 150 squad cars,
police, fire trucks, paramedics.''
   About 15 minutes later, a power pole exploded and plunged the
camp into darkness.
   ``I'm looking out my kitchen door and I see black clouds, fire
billowing very high, police running around in riot gear,'' Lewis
said. ``I sure hope I don't lose my house. Sparks and embers are
flying everywhere.''
   Debbie Gates, a dispatcher for the county sheriff's department,
said hundreds of deputies and police surrounded the prison late
Sunday.
   ``All of our available on-duty personnel is out there,'' said
Gates.
   Banning is 90 miles east of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
