<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0430 07-10 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0430,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Decline</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar.
Picks up 4th pvs, `Dealers said ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined
slightly.
   The dollar closed at 139.28 yen, down 0.37 yen from Friday's
139.65-yen finish. It opened at 139.25 yen and ranged between 139.00
yen and 139.35 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 27.95
points, or 0.08 percent, ending the day at 33,676.02. It shed 74.96
points during the morning session.
   Dealers said the index fell as a result of selling by foreign
investors in arbitrage deals to buy cheaper futures issues.
   Nomura Securities analyst Masahiro Umemori said Japanese
investors were reluctant to buy issues mainly because of concerns
over the election for the upper house of the parliament, scheduled
for July 23.
   Analysts predict the governing Liberal Democratic Party (LDP)
will lose badly in the election, hurt by the Recruit
influence-peddling scandal, an unpopular sales tax imposed in April
and reports that Prime Minister Sousuke Uno has kept several paid
mistresses, Umemori said.
   ``On top of it, the agriculture minister's remarks degrading
women last Friday triggered investors' worries that it might have
further damaged LDP popularty,'' he said.
   In a speech on behalf of LDP candidates, Agriculture Minisater
Hisao Horinouchi said ``women are useless in the world of politics.''
   ``Although macro-economic factors, including lower interest rates
in the United States, seem good for stock investment, the problem
here is the election,'' Umemori added.
   In currency dealing, trading was quiet ahead of release of
several U.S. economic indicators this week, including the producer
price index Friday.
   But the dollar is likely to become more bullish as the yen comes
under stronger pressure out of fear the LDP is losing its grip on
Japanese politics, said a dealer with a commercial bank in Tokyo.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar's ``direction is
unclear'' following the market's reaction Friday to a report that
the U.S. jobless rate edged up to 5.3 percent in June from May's 5.2
percent.
   The dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said most
investors were awaiting the U.S. wholesale price index for May, to
be released Friday.
</TEXT>
