<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     07-10 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Shares Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against the Japanese yen today,
and share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange also inched down.
   The dollar closed at 139.28 yen, down 0.37 yen from Friday's
139.65-yen close. It opened at 139.25 yen and moved narrowly between
139.00 yen and 139.35 yen.
   Kimio Kobori, a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, said that most
market players ``remained on the sidelines, being unable to
determine whether they should sell or buy.
   ``In the absence of fresh market-affecting news, Japanese
investors already have turned their concern to the U.S. wholesale
price index this coming Friday,'' he added.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues lost 27.95 points, or 0.08 percent, ending the day at
33,676.02. It shed 74.96 points during the morning session.
   Yutaka Yoshino, a dealer with Nikko Securities, attributed the
Nikkei's fall to technical adjustments after gains for three
consecutive trading days last week.
   ``Some market analysts say the market is not doing well due to
investors' concerns over the elections, but that is no longer a
fresh market-affecting incentive, although some concern remains,''
he said.
   Nomura Securities analyst Masahiro Umemori said Japanese
investors were reluctant to buy shares, mainly because of
uncertainty over elections on July 23 for half the seats in
Parliament's upper house.
   Analysts predict the ruling Liberal Democratic Party will suffer
major losses because of the Recruit influence-peddling scandal, an
unpopular sales tax imposed in April, and reports that Prime
Minister Sousuke Uno has kept paid mistresses.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 500
million shares. Shipbuilding, electrical and chemical shares were
all lower, while some oil issues sold well.
</TEXT>
