<FIRST>r a PM-HighwayKillings     07-10 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Highway Killings,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serial Murder Probe Enters Second Year With no Clear Leads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skeletons of nine women began showing up a year
ago along southeastern Massachusetts highways, but no charges have
been brought and authorities are frustrated by false leads in the
serial killings.
   ``It's not getting any easier,'' said James Martin, a spokesman
for the district attorney. ``Time is going on and the trail's
getting colder.''
   The nine women, as well as two others missing and believed dead,
were drug addicts and many supported their habit through
prostitution in the New Bedford area.
   But aside from the similar backgrounds, few links have been made
in the slayings. Since last July, the bodies have turned up
one-by-one, uncovered by highways workers, passersby and police dogs
sniffing 40 miles of roads.
   ``We started with a lukewarm trail to begin with because the
bodies were decomposed and little evidence was left at the scene,''
Martin said.
   Authorities have been tight-lipped about their investigation.
   Troopers have worked 3,500-plus overtime hours, a forensic
specialist was brought from Washington, D.C., and a special grand
jury was convened several times last spring to hear testimony.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald A. Pina also has
recruited the FBI's special serial-murder investigation unit, which
has been working up a profile of a killer.
   But still, no arrests.
   James A. Fox, a professor of criminal justice at Northeastern
University, said leads were particularly hard to find because the
killer had obscured clues to the scene of the crime.
   ``This is the kind of serial murder where the victims' bodies are
dumped some other place than where they were killed, cutting out a
major form of police investigation: the forensics evidence,'' Fox
said.
   He said serial killers also were difficult to trace because they
generally prey on strangers. ``There's no clear motive,'' said Fox,
co-author of ``Mass Murder: America's Growing Menace.''
   Martin said the investigation has also been hindered by a ``hall
of mirrors.''
   Investigators spend much time at Weld Square, New Bedford's
rundown redlight district. They take to the streets after dark and
by dawn have often questioned scores of prostitutes and drug dealers.
   But the stories told by street people often are contradictory and
frequently fabricated under the influence of alcohol, cocaine or
heroin.
   ``We're in a situation right now where we're frustrated because a
couple of weeks ago the DA received information from a witness that,
if corroborated, could very quickly lead to an indictment,'' Martin
said last week.
   ``We've been out searching for that information and evidence over
the last couple of weeks and haven't found it.''
   Martin declined to give details on the lead, but said the tip now
seems to have fizzled. This is not an unfamiliar pattern.
   Through the last nine months four suspects have emerged. Although
the district attorney has never named names, the men all have been
questioned and their links to the Weld Square community detailed
extensively in media reports.
   Two men were held on unrelated assault charges; a third appeared
before a special grand jury; and Pina has said he'd like to question
the fourth, a lawyer who moved to Florida last fall.
   But Fox was skeptical. ``If any of these people were the killer,
my guess is that he'd be arrested already,'' he said.
   Fox also said the odds for finding the killer or killers weren't
improving.
   ``The longer it takes, the less likely there is to be an
arrest,'' Fox said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-RenegadePriest     07-10 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Renegade Priest,1st Ld-Writethru,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended Priest Leads African-American Catholic Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Adds 2 grafs after 18th pvs with Brooklyn support; Picks up,
Stallings has</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE RUMSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspended black priest who defied church
authorities for the second week by conducting his own brand of
services incorporating African religious rites says he will try to
reconcile with the Roman Catholic Church.
   The Rev. George A. Stallings Jr., who accuses the church of
racism and failing its black parishioners, told a local television
station Sunday that he planned to begin seeking reconciliation by
the end of the week ``so that we are not separated and divided, but
we are all working toward the same goal.''
   Stallings declined to discuss terms of a proposed reconciliation,
but told WRC-TV, ``I think that this could happen within the next 30
days.''
   The Rev. William Lori, personal secretary to Washington
Archbishop Cardinal James A. Hickey, said the church would welcome
reconciliation.
   ``Our hope and our prayer through all of this is
reconciliation,'' Lori said. ``Obviously, we'll have to see what the
proposal contains. But remember that the cardinal has always left
the door open.''
   A woman who plans to join Stallings' new African-American
Catholic Congregation said the Catholic church must find a way to
address the needs of its black parishioners.
   ``I feel the Catholic Church is going to have to confront this
issue in some way and now is as good a time as any,'' said Christine
Kearney, a former worshipper at the Catholic parish led until
recently by Stallings. She said she plans to join his new Imani
Temple.
   ``I don't want to leave the Roman Catholic Church, but I do want
some input into the way I worship. That's all he is trying to do,''
Kearney said.
   Stallings led services Sunday, shouting above the din of African
drums, exhorting a packed auditorium to spread the word about the
new Catholic congregation that blends African religious rites,
gospel music and traditional Catholic liturgy.
   The swaying, clapping congregation shouted back as the choir
swung into ``Praise Him,'' a rollicking favorite in many black
churches.
   Stallings's back-to-back revival-style services at Imani Temple
marked the second straight week he has said mass in defiance of
church authorities.
   ``We are not simply making a joyful noise, we are not just
talking about our African-American cultural and spiritual heritage,
we are helping you to know the Lord in a way you have never known
him before,'' Stallings told parishioners.
   ``We've got to tell people about it ... There's plenty of lapsed
Catholics, plenty of what I call pagan Catholics you only see on
Christmas,'' Stallings said.
   Stallings said mass and served communion to more than 2,000
parishioners in the Suitland High School auditorium in suburban
Washington, summer home of the new church. He also asked for
donations to build a new church.
   The 41-year-old priest wore a robe trimmed with African printed
fabric and called on worshipers to ``invoke the spirits'' of African
and black American ancestors.
   He poured libations made of earth taken from the grounds of six
black institutions in Philadelphia, including a prominent black
Catholic parish.
   The service was a repeat of an inaugural service last Sunday that
drew an estimated 3,000 people to a larger church _ and which
resulted in Stallings' suspension by the Roman Catholic archdiocese
of Washington.
   Stallings spokesman Paul Dillard said more than 400 people agreed
to join the church Sunday.
   In New York, worshippers of Our Lady of Charity Church in
Brooklyn held their own mass rich in black cultural expression to
show support for Stallings, according to today's editions of the New
York Times. Members of the congregation, facing an altar that
featured the figure of a black Jesus, spent most of the service on
their feet, swaying and clapping to Gospel melodies.
   ``What we did today wasn't all that different from what Father
Stallings did last Sunday,'' said parishioner Jaime Cobham. ``We
just want to worship in our own idiom. You'll find he has a lot of
support here.''
   Stallings has said he wants to see formation of an
African-American Catholic rite that would still recognize the
authority of the pope but give individual priests more control over
Catholic liturgy and other matters.
   Stallings' suspension means he is not sanctioned by the church to
lead mass or perform sacraments. It is the strongest step Hickey can
take without moving for excommunication.
   ``He is a suspended priest ... The church is not going to stand
behind anything he does sacramentally,'' Hickey's assistant Lori
said in an interview Saturday. Lori said the church is not
contemplating any further discipline for now.
   Several churchgoers said they attended Stallings' parish during
the 12 years Stallings was pastor of a predominantly black parish in
Washington.
   One woman, who declined to give her name, said she isn't sure
she'll join. ``I just don't know at this point. I'll know when the
spirit moves me,'' she said.
   But she and Kearney said they will not stop attending church if
Stallings is excommunicated.
   ``Those who are following out of curiosity will probably go
someplace else,'' Kearney said. ``Those who are true believers will
continue.''
</TEXT>
