<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CaliforniaQuake     07-10 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--California Quake,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mild Earthquake Shakes San Jose Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake centered just northeast
of San Jose shook the southern San Francisco Bay area.
   There were no reports of damage, according to the Santa Clara
County Communications Center.
   The earthquake, which hit just after 6:30 a.m. Sunday, measured
3.9 on the Richter scale and was centered in the Alum Rock area
seven miles northeast of San Jose, according to the Seismographic
Stations of the University of California at Berkeley.
   The tremor was centered on the Calaveras Fault, roughly in the
area as the June 12, 1988, earthquake that had a magnitude of 5.5.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage.
</TEXT>
