<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Glance     07-10 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Glance,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here at a glance is background on the
Polish People's Republic:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GEOGRAPHY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Located in Central Europe, the 120,727-square-mile Soviet bloc
country is bordered by the Baltic Sea to the north, the Soviet Union
to the east, Czechoslovakia to the south and East Germany to the
West. Its largest cities are Warsaw, the capital, with a population
of 1.67 million; Lodz, population 845,000; Krakow, population
744,000. Gdansk has 467,000 residents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE PEOPLE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's 38 million people are 94 percent Roman Catholic. The
life expectancy for males is 66.8 years, for females 75.2 years. The
literacy rate is 98 percent. Thirty-nine percent of the people live
in the country, 61 percent in the city.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HISTORY:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Poland was a great power controlling large sections of central
Europe from the 14th to the 17th centuries. Three partitions from
1772 to 1795 divided the country among Prussia, Russia and Austria.
   The post-World War I Treaty of Versailles recognized Poland's
independence in 1919. Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union invaded
Poland in 1939. The Communists consolidated power in fraud-tainted
1947 elections.
   Amid labor turmoil, the independent trade union Solidarity was
legalized in 1980. In December 1981, the government of Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski declared martial law and thousands of Solidarity
activists were jailed.
   After negotiations between the Jaruzelski's government and the
opposition, Solidarity's legal status was restored on April 17, 1989.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GOVERNMENT:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party continues to rule, but Jaruzelski has
promised to allow opposition candidates to run for all seats in
parliament in four years.
   Largely democratic elections were held June 4 and June 18.
Solidarity-backed candidates won 99 seats in the newly restored
100-member Senate and they won the maximum they were allowed, 161,
in the National Assembly's more powerful lower house, the 460-member
Sejm.
   The Assembly is expected to soon choose a new president, with
expanded powers and primacy in military and foreign affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-Poland 3rdLd-Writethru a0474 07-10 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Poland, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0474,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Lays Wreaths, Meets With Polish Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS pvs 3rd graf bgng, Jaruzelski shook, to CORRECT spelling
of Belvedere; fixes spelling of wreaths in overline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, cheered by flag-waving
crowds shouting ``long live, long live,'' honored Polish war dead
and Jewish martyrs today and sat down for talks with Polish leader
Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   Bush also planned to address the Polish National Assembly, the
only parliament in the Communist world with a freely elected
opposition party, as he began a 10-day European tour.
   Jaruzelski shook hands with Bush at the entrance to the 18th
century Belvedere Palace, and they went inside for two hours of
talks.
   About 2,000 people, including Poles and American tourists, turned
out on a warm, sunny morning to greet Bush at a wreath-laying
ceremony at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier.
   Poles shouted ``long live, long live'' and ``100 years, 100
years'' as Bush stepped out of his armored limousine, flown here
from Washington and still bearing District of Columbia license
plates.
   One man carried a banner of the independent Solidarity labor
movement that was topped with a paper cutout of the Statue of
Liberty.
   Jadwiga Staklewska, a secretary at the medical academy in Lodz,
rode a train for two hours to see Bush and began to cry when he
arrived at the memorial.
   ``I came out of sympathy for Bush,'' she said. ``He wants to help
Poland, so that convinced me to come. Only in Bush do I see hope for
our tragic situation.''
   At the military monument, Bush and his wife, Barbara, watched as
two members of an honor guard placed a wreath at the triple
colonnade memorial.
   The president also participated in a wreath-laying ceremony at
Umschlagplatz, an almost unmarked memorial of marble walls
identifying a spot in the Warsaw ghetto where Jews were rounded up
for trains bound for Nazi death camps.
   About 2,000 people showed up at the Jewish monument, where Bush
was accompanied by the only rabbi in Poland, Menachem Jaskowitz, and
Marek Edelman, the last surviving commander of the Jewish ghetto
uprising in April 1943.
   The walls are inscribed with the family names of some of the more
than 300,000 Warsaw Jews who were sent to the camps in 1942-43.
   Bush's two hours of scheduled talks with Jaruzelski, Poland's
Communist Party chief, preceded a speech before a newly constituted
parliament where nearly half the members are members of the
once-banned Solidarity movement.
   The Polish legislators awaited the first details of Bush's new
but limited aid proposal for Poland's battered economy.
   White House officials said Bush's proposals would go ``somewhat
further'' than a package of trade concessions and other incentives
he announced in April. The Los Angeles Times reported today that
Bush was expected to propose the creation of a $100 million fund to
aid the Polish economy, and said he will urge other nations to offer
similar contributions.
   Sensitive to government fears that his visit might spark huge
demonstrations and upset the delicate political situation here, Bush
told reporters Sunday, ``I'm not going to try to put (Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev) in a box by throwing strains on the
Warsaw Pact.''
   Bush said he was in ``a little delicate'' position amid high
expectations among Poles for desperately needed economic aid. ``I
don't want to over-promise, do too little or do too much,'' he said.
   Upon his arrival Sunday night, Bush said ``a new and brighter
future'' is on the horizon for Poland.
   ``Poland has started along an ascending path of change,
democratic change,'' the president said. ``And this climb is
exhilarating, but not always be easy and will require further
sacrifices. But if followed, it will lead to a renaissance for this
remarkable nation.''
   The White House says Poles should be prepared to accept austerity
measures, likely bringing increased unemployment and higher prices
in a country already suffering from 100 percent inflation and a $39
billion foreign debt.
   Bush's visit to Poland is the first stop on a 10-day trip that
will include a meeting with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa in Gdansk
and the first-ever visit by an American president to Hungary.
   He also will travel to Paris for a seven-nation economic summit
and stop briefly in the Netherlands.
   Despite the lateness of his arrival Sunday, thousands of cheering
Poles lined Bush's motorcade route at 11 p.m., waving Americans
flags and raising the two-finger victory salute of Solidarity, which
trounced the Communists in parliamentary elections.
   Jaruzelski, who in 1981 imposed martial law to crush the
Solidarity movement, was praised by Bush for embracing the
democratic reforms that led to Solidarity's election victory.
   Jaruzelski welcomed Bush as ``an eminent politician and
statesman.''
   He told Bush, ``You are arriving in a country in which a process
of basic change is at work. You are going to see a Poland that is
following with determination the path of profound socio-political
and economic reforms.''
   Solidarity representatives were among 80 guests invited today to
an outdoor lunch with Bush under a huge tent at the U.S.
ambassador's residence.
   Other guests included Jaruzelski, government leaders, academics
and businessmen.
   Bush was to be Jaruzelski's guest tonight at a formal state
dinner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
