<FIRST>r a PM-CentralPark-Rats     07-10 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central Park-Rats,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rats Infest Central Park's `Strawberry Fields'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strawberry Fields, a corner of Central Park
dedicated to the memory of John Lennon, has attracted a lot of rats,
a newspaper reported today.
   ``I saw a whole family of six or eight. One practically ran right
over my foot,'' longtime upper West Side resident Joyce Searles told
the New York Post.
   Mrs. Searles said she has visited the plot for 30 years _ long
before it was a memorial to the slain Beatle _ but had never seen a
rat there before.
   ``Now, whenever I see a squirrel, I jump,'' she said.
   ``I think it's shocking and I think it gives a bad impression to
all the tourists who come here. People come here with their children
all the time,'' Mrs. Searles said.
   Parks Department spokeswoman Ivy Morrison confirmed that rats
``have made their presence known,'' in Strawberry Fields.
   The park hasn't been using rat poison at Strawberry Fields
because of public concern about the environment, Morrison said.
   The poison affects benign park animals and pets as well as rats,
she said.
   ``We are looking into other alternatives. We prefer to handle it
in some natural way,'' Morrison said.
   One non-polluting way to attack rats is to put up houses for owls
in hopes that the predatory birds move in and start feeding on the
rodents, according to Morrison.
   A $1 million donation from Lennon's widow, Yoko Ono, created
Strawberry Fields in an area of Central Park where the couple used
to stroll.
   Lennon was assassinated at his nearby apartment in December 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
