<FIRST>r a PM-Fires-Nebraska     07-10 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires-Nebraska,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Threatens a Historic Fort, And People's Livelihood</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT ROBINSON STATE PARK, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The couple stood on a
hillside and watched the raging flames, waiting helplessly to see
whether the blaze sweeping this corner of northwest Nebraska would
consume their ranch.
   Rousted from their home of 44 years by firefighters, Anna and
Gayle Oldaker sat with a few belongings crammed into their pickup
truck as fire danced along ridges and through a canyon at Fort
Robinson State Park.
   Thick columns of acrid smoke towered overhead, part of the
20-mile front of the 50,000-acre fire roaring through northwestern
Nebraska.
   Fire trucks were trying to protect the house and other buildings
on the Oldakers' 1,900-acre ranch, adjacent to the state park.
Cattle had been herded away.
   ``We're just hoping the wind don't change,'' the 68-year-old Mrs.
Oldaker said Sunday. ``If the wind changes, I don't know what's
going to happen.''
   The couple earlier had met with Gov. Kay Orr, who declared a
disaster area after viewing the fire and talking to residents.
   Nearly half of the 22,000-acre park was believed to have burned
by Sunday, along with 40,000 acres of private land and other
parkland.
   ``Those pine trees are like kerosene-drenched torches,'' said
state Sen. Sandy Scofield, who lives near the area. Firefighters
were stymied by ``the terrain, the drought, just the nature of a
pine forest ablaze.''
   Except for one firefighter suffering smoke inhalation, and minor
injuries such as cut hands, there have been no injuries in the fire,
officials said.
   By early today, the fire had burned to within one-half mile of
Fort Robinson, the fort established in 1874 that now serves as a
park lodge.
   Sioux Chief Crazy Horse was killed by guards in 1877 at the
former cavalry post. The fort also witnessed a Cheyenne skirmish in
1876 in which William F. ``Buffalo Bill'' Cody fought.
   Fort Robinson Superintendent Vince Rotherham said more than 600
people were evacuated from the park because of the dense smoke. Most
were campers and had gone their way, said Don McRoberts, deputy
state fire marshal.
   Orr made state disaster funds available and called in the
National Guard to help fight the lightning-sparked fire, which began
Saturday afternoon as three small fires but became what one official
called a ``roaring inferno.''
   Smoke from the fire, raging out of control Sunday night with its
major front nine miles from the Sioux County town of Harrison, could
be seen at Scottsbluff, about 90 miles away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
