<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-Welcome     07-10 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Welcome,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Poles See Hope in Bush's Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Poles gave a shouting,
flag-waving welcome to President Bush today and expressed hope that
his visit will give their homeland an economic and emotional boost
at a time of turbulent change.
   About 4,000 spectators greeted Bush and his wife, Barbara, when
they arrived for wreath-laying ceremonies at two monuments honoring
Polish war dead and Jewish victims of the Nazi Holocaust before the
president's meeting with Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   The ceremonies took place at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier on
Victory Square in central Warsaw and about a mile away at
Umschlagplatz, the German word for a square on the edge of the
former Warsaw Ghetto where more than 300,000 Jews were loaded onto
trains bound for the Treblinka death camp in 1942-43.
   ``Long live, long live,'' shouted people at Victory Square when
Bush's black armored limousine pulled up in front of the marble
tomb, which was flanked by a military band and honor guard.
   Some American tourists began singing ``The Star-Spangled
Banner,'' and a few Poles gamely but haltingly joined in.
   To shelter themselves from the bright sun, some spectators made
paper hats out of the Communist daily newspaper, Trybuna Ludu. The
crowd held up one large Solidarity banner, topped with a cutout of
the Statue of Liberty.
   People at both sites spoke of their high expectations for Bush's
visit.
   ``Only in Bush do I see hope for our tragic situation,'' said
Jadwiga Staklewska, a medical academy secretary who rode the train
for two hours from Lodz to see the American president.
   ``He wants to help Poland, so that persuaded me to come,'' she
said, describing how ``my heart soared'' when she heard Bush's
speech on Polish television when he arrived in Warsaw Sunday night.
   ``The Communists are falling and the only thing that will help
this country is assistance,'' said construction worker Ryszard
Bobrek. ``America is a power and President Bush will be able to
convince Europe to do something to help Poland.''
   Maria Czerwinska, a 58-year-old retiree at the Jewish memorial,
carried a shopping bag emblazoned with the name of the independent
Solidarity trade movement, which was legalized again in April.
   ``Like everybody, I hope that due to the visit we will receive
some aid and get some help, including morally and psychologically,
through his presence,'' she said.
   Indicating her bag, she added: ``This would not have been
possible before. I was a member of underground Solidarity and now I
am a member of legal Solidarity.''
   ``All the time I had the feeling that changes were not real,''
she said. ``This lack of faith is very widespread. ... But (now)
there is some hope. For instance, the Senate is our Senate, our
hope.''
   She was referring to Poland's new, freely elected Senate, in
which Solidarity won all but one of the 100 seats.
   Although the Poles said they looked to America for support, many
said their country needs to buckle down and help itself.
   ``I hope things will be better, but to a large extent it is up to
Poles themselves to work properly,'' said Urszula Kozik, a
17-year-old aspiring artist.
   ``It would be good if people saw a motive for good work, so that
working would bring better profits,'' she said.
   At Umschlagplatz, Bush was accompanied by Marek Edelman, a key
Solidarity figure who is the last surviving commander of the Jewish
ghetto uprising in April 1943.
   After the wreath-laying ceremony there, Edelman said he told Bush
that the United States would have to make economic contributions to
help make sure that nothing like the Holocaust occurs again.
   ``Any dictatorship can lead to such a situation,'' Edelman said.
``Rich America must sometimes give a chunk, so that the world can
become free, so that these things do not happen again.''
</TEXT>
