<FIRST>r i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-10 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Stable in Light European Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was stable in light trading late this
morning in Europe as investors stayed on the sidelines, uncertain
whether to buy or to sell the U.S. currency.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Traders said the dollar had inched back up in early European
trading after Asian sales had taken it lower earlier today. But the
dollar still was well below its levels of late Friday.
   ``People are afraid to sell because they see the dollar still has
some strength in it,'' one Rome trader said. ``But they're afraid to
buy because there's still concern interest rates might come down in
the U.S. We're in a very ambivalent situation.''
   Traders predicted an uneventful day for the dollar as the market
awaited signs of the Federal Reserve's interest rate policy.
   ``The market has already discounted a rate decrease. Now we're
just waiting for something official to happen,'' another Rome trader
said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.37 yen to a closing 139.28 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a lower rate of 139.25 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _1.8700 West German marks, down from 1.8840
   _1.6133 Swiss francs, down from 1.6200
   _6.3438 French francs, down from 6.3915
   _2.1077 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1272
   _1,358.50 Italian lire, down from 1,368.00
   _1.1895 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1907
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6237 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6245 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $383 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $385.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $382.45.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $382.65 compared with $384.60 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 29 cents to close at a bid
$383.27.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.24 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $5.37.
</TEXT>
