<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Poland Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Polish Papers Hail Bush Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's visit was heralded today
by state and opposition newspapers alike, with one proclaiming that
U.S.-Polish relations strained after martial law are now completely
healed.
   New to newsstands since Bush's 1987 visit as vice president is
Gazeta Wyborcza, the first independent daily in the East bloc. It is
edited by supporters of the Solidarity movement.
   Atop its front page was a drawing of the American eagle joined
with the eagle from the Polish national emblem, followed by a story
with highlights from Bush's arrival speech.
   The daily has been published with official permission since the
April restoration of legal status to Solidarity following talks with
the communist government.
   ``The visit definitely undoes the remnants of the period of deep
deterioration of the Washington-Warsaw relations after 1981,'' said
a front-page commentary in the Warsaw daily Zycie Warszawy.
   The United States imposed economic sanctions after the 1981
military crackdown to crush Solidarity. But as Polish authorities
have carried out reforms in recent years, relations have warmed step
by step.
   Reporters from Solidarity, and television crews with the
movement's logo pasted to their cameras, now join the crowds of
journalists from foreign news agencies and the government-backed
press covering each stop of Bush's itinerary.
   The communist party daily Trybuna Ludu reprinted the airport
remarks by Bush and Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, and said
their talks were expected to ``begin a new stage in Polish-American
cooperation ... that would foster overcoming Poland's difficulties
and serve building the new Europe based on reciprocal confidence and
understanding.''
