<HEAD>First Lady Unconcerned About White House Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush says she is confident about
security precautions for the first family despite reports of
late-night tours of the White House that reportedly included two
male prostitutes.
   Asked Sunday if she was concerned about security, she brushed off
the suggestion, saying ``Not at all.''
   ``There haven't been a lot of stories in our house about it,''
she said during a brief interview with reporters on Air Force One
during the flight to the Polish capital from Washington.
   Responding to further questions about a Secret Service
investigation of possible late-night White House tours, Mrs. Bush
replied, ``I'm not into all of this.''
   Accompanying her husband on his second trip to Poland in 20
months and his first as president, the first lady predicted her
husband would receive a warm reception.
   Poland is the first stop on a 10-day trip that includes visits to
Hungary, a seven-nation economic summit in Paris and a one-day stay
in the Netherlands.
   ``I think the whole trip is going to be thrilling,'' Mrs. Bush
said.
   Mindful of the hot weather here, she said, ``I wish it was
October-November. The weather is kinder, gentler.''
   Mrs. Bush said she regretted leaving behind her dog, Millie.
   ``She (Millie) cried real tears and did not come out to say
goodbye,'' Mrs. Bush said. ``She did not leave her chair, and when I
went over to say goodbye, there were tears.''
