<HEAD>Clashes Near Israel's Security Zone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to UPDATE with Israelis withdrawing, attacking
with helicopter; No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian and leftist Lebanese fighters
attacked a joint patrol of Israeli troops and allied militiamen in
south Lebanon today, and three guerrillas were killed in a
counterattack, police said.
   The assault was mounted by guerrillas of the Marxist Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, the Popular Struggle Front
and the Syrian Social Nationalist Party, a pro-Syrian leftist
Lebanese faction, a police spokesman said.
   The raiders opened fire with automatic weapons on the patrol of
the Israeli army and the allied South Lebanon Army militia at the
northern edge of Israel's self-designated ``security zone'' in south
Lebanon at 8 a.m., said the spokesman, who cannot be named under
standing regulations.
   There were no reports of casualties among the Israelis and their
militia allies.
   Shortly afterward, another joint Israeli-SLA force of 70 fighters
in 13 armored personnel carriers raided suspected guerrilla hideouts
around the village of Dellaya, the spokesman said.
   ``They have punched 3 miles north of the security zone and are
shooting into the bush,'' he said. ``We have a report that three
guerrillas have been killed.''
   He said the joint Israeli-Lebanese force withdrew to the buffer
zone at midday. But Israeli helicopter gunships staged repeated
strafing runs in the area afterwards.
