<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--DamagedAirliner     07-10 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Damaged Airliner,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airliner Lands Safely After Hitting Bird, Turbulence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wayward bird cracked the windshield of a United
Airlines 737 and heavy turbulence shook rivets loose on its wings,
but the jet's pilot managed to land safely at Miami International
Airport, officials said.
   Flight 1295 from Providence, R.I., encountered the hazards near
the Florida-Georgia border, Federal Aviation Administration
spokesman Jack Barker said in Atlanta.
   Passengers were prepared for an emergency landing during the
approach to Miami, but the plan landed safely at 5:10 p.m. Sunday
and none of the 108 passengers was injured.
   ``It was disconcerting to see that the windshield had totally
cracked, and ... not knowing whether it was going to give way,''
said passenger Helen Furgang. ``It was an interesting fight. Not one
that I'd want to repeat.''
