<FIRST>r a PM-FamilySlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0514 07-10 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Slayings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Authorities Say Killed Entire Family Scheduled to be Arraigned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Edits throughout to include suspect's denial he is List; no
pickup. ^By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Sunday school teacher who
authorities say was on the run for 18 years after slaying his
children, wife and mother, spent the day before his arraignment
reading the Bible in his cell, an officer said.
   The man identified as John E. List, 63, who allegedly shot his
oldest son 10 times, and shot his wife, mother and two other
children once each in the back, was kept in jail Sunday for his own
safety, said a corrections officer who declined to give his name.
   ``We wouldn't let him go to church,'' the officer said. ``It's
too risky. We don't want to have to answer how he got hurt by
another prisoner.''
   The man, who goes by the name of Robert P. Clark, was arrested
last month in Richmond, Va., and charged with the Nov. 9, 1971,
killings. He has denied he is List, but authorities say fingerprints
and a scar prove List and Clark are the same man.
   He was to be arraigned this afternoon before Superior Court Judge
William Wertheimer.
   The bodies of List's wife and children were not found until a
month after the killings, neatly laid side-by-side in the ballroom
of their 19-room mansion in nearby Westfield. The body of his
85-year-old mother was discovered in an upstairs bedroom.
   A worldwide manhunt ensued, but all leads hit dead ends until
June 1, when the suspect was arrested at the Richmond accounting
firm where he had worked for 18 months. FBI agents had been tipped
off by a viewer of the national television program, ``America's Most
Wanted,'' which 11 days earlier had run a segment focusing on List.
   Authorities say List fled to Colorado, then Virginia and built a
new life as Robert Clark without changing his appearance, profession
or reputation as a quiet churchgoing Lutheran.
   He had remarried and his new wife said she knew nothing of his
alleged past, but that she would stand by him.
   The officer at the Union County Jail said List's wife has not
visited him.
</TEXT>
