<DOCNO> AP890710-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     07-10 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians, Christians Stage Artillery Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners duelled with
howitzer shells and rockets across Beirut today and street gun
battles between rival Shiite factions ebbed into sporadic sniping.
   In south Lebanon, Palestinian and leftist Lebanese guerrillas
attacked a patrol of Israeli troops and allied militiamen, prompting
a massive counterattack that left three guerillas dead, police said.
   Police said Syrian artillery emplacements in west Beirut and
north Lebanon shelled Christian residential districts and the coast
north of Beirut at dawn, maintaining a four-month blockade of the
310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   Gunners of the mostly Christian troops of army commander Gen.
Michel Aoun retaliated by shelling the seaside districts of Ein
Mreisseh and Maramel, said a police spokesman. He cannot be named
under standing regulations.
   He said two people were killed and five wounded in the overnight
bombardment, raising the overall toll to 405 killed and 1,581
wounded since the Syrian-Christian confrontation broke out March 8.
   Police said Syrian troops in charge of west Beirut's security
deployed in the coastal residential districts of Jnah and Ouzai,
restoring traffic between Beirut and south Lebanon and disengaging
warring militiamen of the pro-Syrian Amal movement and the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Syrian officers on the scene said they do not plan to go into the
narrow alleyways of both Shiite slums while the two warring factions
were staging funerals for their dead.
   Occasional sniper fire marred the truce called at midnight after
daylong clashes with mortars, rocket-propelled grenades and machine
guns that trapped thousands of sunbathers on nearby beaches.
   They were evacuated at sundown, when the Syrian command arranged
a one-hour ``mercy cease-fire'' and sent in armored personnel
carriers that brought out the trapped sunbathers.
   Police said 10 people were killed and 23 wounded in Sunday's
hostilities. That raised the overall toll to 18 killed and 51
wounded since the current Amal-Hezbollah confrontation erupted 10
days ago.
   The two factions have been vying for dominance of Lebanon's 1.2
million Shiites, the country's largest Moslem sect.
   The spiraling hostilities made it clear that Arab League
troubleshooter Lakhdar Ibrahimi failed to make a headway during four
days of talks with Christian and Moslem leaders in Beirut.
   Ibrahimi represented an Arab League committee seeking a solution
to the 14-year-old civil war.
   The independent Beirut newspaper An-Nahar said Aoun rejected
Syria's conditions for lifting the enclave's siege.
   These conditions, An-Nahar said, included the formation of a
security committee made up of Lebanese and Arab League
representatives to oversee the cease-fire, search ships heading to
Christian ports and remove surface-to-surface missiles from the
enclave.
   Syria contends Aoun has recently acquired the missiles from Iraq,
Syria's main Arab foe. The missiles, which have a range of 43 miles,
can hit the Syrian capital of Damascus from Lebanon's central
mountains.
   Also today, Druse parliamentary deputy Bashir Awar, 76, died of a
heart attack, reducing the number of surviving members of Lebanon's
99-seat Parliament to 74.
   The current unicameral house was elected for a four-year term in
1972. The civil war prevented new elections and Parliament had been
extending its term once every two years.
   The parliament, however, has been unable to convene for the last
11 months to elect a successor to former President Amin Gemayel,
whose term expired Sept. 22.
   That created a political crisis that split the government along
sectarian lines and generated the fighting between Christians and
Syria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RacistsRetreat     07-10 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racists Retreat,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>White Supremacist Demonstration Broken Up By Anti-Racist Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERRY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten white supremacists gave up their protest
of a market that sells kosher foods after they found themselves
outnumbered by about 200 anti-racism demonstrators.
   Sunday's Ku Klux Klan rally, staged at the Taylor County
Courthouse, was intended to protest Tom's Foods, which prepares some
of its food according to Jewish law. KKK members say they think U.S.
food companies are being ``infiltrated'' through the certification
of kosher foods.
   The protest ended after about an hour and a half when the seven
white-robed Klansmen, one skinhead and his girlfriend, and a Klan
member in plain clothes grew tired of the counter-demonstrators, who
sang peace songs and carried anti-racist signs.
   ``I'm a little bit disappointed,'' said John Baumgardner, the
Grand Dragon of the Invisible Empire Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.
``We wanted to go over there and try to educate those people, but
the police wouldn't let us.''
   Tony Bastanzio, the leader of a Klan group called the Dixie
Knights, which scheduled the demonstration, said he canceled the
kosher rally because he didn't want to challenge the anti-racist
group.
   The 30 police officers patrolling the area would not allow any
interaction between the two groups, which were separated by a police
line. Police officers frisked everyone who entered the demonstration
site.
   Taylor County Sheriff John Walker said one counter-demonstrator,
from Gainesville, was arrested for carrying two concealed weapons.
No injuries were reported.
   ``I'm delighted this is over,'' Walker said, ``and we're very
pleased that both sides were cooperative.''
   Stephanie Gray, who helped organize a Tallahassee coalition of
counter-demonstrators, said the demonstration was a success.
   ``I think there's a lot of real positive emotions here,'' Ms.
Gray said. ``We've got plenty of support here. We've definitely got
them outnumbered.''
   But the white supremacists say they weren't impressed.
   ``I've always been a racist,'' said John DeFreeuw, a 21-year-old
skinhead. ``There's no such thing as racial harmony _ just look
around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
