<FIRST>r a PM-UrbanDolphin     07-10 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Urban Dolphin,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biologists Study Dolphin Found Dead in Hudson River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine biologists today studied the body of a
bottlenosed dolphin for clues to why it strayed into the East River
and then swam 50 miles up the Hudson River, where it died.
   A preliminary look at the dead dolphin shows it had ``severe and
significant skin lesions and skin sloughing because of the fresh
water,'' said Dr. Samuel Sadove of the Okeanos Ocean Research
Foundation.
   ``There are also a number of old healed wounds that are quite
large,'' he said.
   The dolphin, which Sadove said was an adult female weighing
between 500 and 600 pounds, was found floating Sunday afternoon in
the Hudson River off the town of Garrison, about 50 miles north of
New York City.
   The mammal's death ``was not totally unexpected,'' Sadove said,
adding that it was last seen alive on Saturday.
   The dolphin was first noticed on June 20 in the East River off
Manhattan. It stayed there for about 11 days, attracting a steady
stream of curious onlookers.
   The gray, 5-foot-long animal resisted the efforts of biologists
who tried to drive it out to open seas by banging on pipes in the
water.
   Two weeks ago, the dolphin headed north up the Hudson, forcing
scientists to scuttle plans to scare it toward the ocean by playing
recorded killer-whale sounds underwater.
   Sadove declined to speculate on what caused the animal's death.
</TEXT>
