<FIRST>r a PM-IowaProbe     07-10 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iowa Probe,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says He's Satisfied With Navy's Handling of Iowa Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARTERVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman asked to investigate
information leaks during the probe of the gun turret explosion
aboard the battleship Iowa says he found no evidence that Navy
officials acted improperly.
   ``I have found nothing to indicate in my inquiry that the Navy,
at least officially, has acted irresponsibly,'' said Rep. Glenn
Poshard, D-Ill.
   Poshard was asked to investigate by the father of Gunner's Mate
3rd Class Kendall Truitt, a sailor who reportedly has been the focus
of the Navy's investigation. Truitt's father lives in Poshard's
district.
   The April 19 explosion killed 47 men, including Gunner's Mate
Clayton Hartwig, who had named Truitt as the sole beneficiary of a
$50,000 life insurance policy.
   News reports have cited unidentified sources as saying the Navy
was investigating the possibility of a homosexual relationship
between the two men. There also was speculation that Hartwig may
have caused the blast to commit suicide or that Truitt had
orchestrated it to kill Hartwig.
   Poshard said Saturday that he is satisfied with the Navy's
handling of the probe, although he added that he felt sorry for
Truitt.
   ``Kendall Truitt is a young man caught up in the most unfortunate
of circumstances,'' Poshard said. ``I feel a great deal of sympathy
for Truitt, because he and his family have had to endure more than
most people endure in ten lifetimes, and perhaps all of it
unjustly.''
   He said the Navy is still investigating the leaks.
   ``What we have here is a bureaucratic investigation too large to
control every comment from every source,'' Poshard said. ``I can't
point my finger at the Navy, and I can't at the media. I don't know
who's to blame.''
   Truitt last week criticized the Navy's investigation and
complained of harassment by the Navy and the news media. He also
said drug use was rampant on the Iowa, and that he and Hartwig were
among the few in the turret crew who did not use drugs.
   A Navy spokeswoman in Norfolk, Va., declined comment on the case.
</TEXT>
