<DOCNO> AP890710-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Bush     07-10 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Bush,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Daily Accuses Bush of Interference In East European Affairs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania today accused President Bush of
seeking to destabilize East European countries, in an official
editorial coinciding with his visit to reform-oriented Poland and
Hungary.
   ``It is quite obvious that President Bush urges ...
destabilization in socialist countries,'' said an editorial in the
government daily Romania Libera.
   Bush's positions on the reform ``flagrantly run counter to the
principles and norms of international laws,'' said an English
translation of the editorial carried by the official Agerpres news
agency and monitored in Vienna.
   Bush arrived in Warsaw Sunday and travels on to Budapest Tuesday
for the first visit to Hungary by a U.S. president.
   Communist Party chief Nicolae Ceausescu is one of the most
adamant opponents within the East bloc of political and economic
reforms like those under way in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary.
   The editorial came just two days after leaders of the seven
Warsaw Pact countries issued a communique in which they declared
they would not interfere in each other's affairs.
   However, the official Romanian editorial applied the agreement to
East-West relations, alleging ``attempts to interfere in the
domestic affairs of the socialist (communist) countries.'' It
referred to the West in general and the United States in particular.
   Romania in the 1960s and 1970s drew praise in the West for
Ceausescu's maverick foreign policy and Presidents Richard Nixon and
Gerald Ford visited Bucharest in 1969 and 1975 respectively. At that
time Romania was criticized by its Warsaw Pact allies for hosting
the two presidents.
   Bush visited Romania as Vice President in September 1983.
   However, Romania has in recent years increasingly come under fire
both from Western nations and from neighboring Hungary and
Yugoslavia for alleged human rights violations.
   Last year, the United States suspended Romania's most-favored
nation trading status.
   Bush has pledged U.S. support for reforms in Poland and Hungary,
but in an interview last week with Hungarian journalists he
emphasized that Washington should not meddle in the domestic affairs
of Warsaw Pact nations or prescribe what kind of reform to undertake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt     07-10 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>57 Moslem Extremists Arrested; Terror School Alleged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of extremist Moslem fundamentalists
were arrested today for allegedly turning a religious summer school
into a terrorist training camp for boys, a security source said.
   The source said police arrested 57 people early today to break up
the school for children as young as 7 years old at Zagazig, capital
of the Nile Delta province of Sharkiya. The city is about 50 miles
northeast of Cairo.
   About 40 boys ages 7 to 15 were recruited by extremists who
``trained them in the use of violence and incited them with lectures
to hate the present system of government,'' said the source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He gave no specifics on that but said the extremists exploited
the boys' summer school holidays, which began last month, for
lessons in terrorism. He said the lessons occurred in the courtyard
of a religious institute but refused to identify the institute.
   Moslem fundamentalists advocate implementation of Sharia, the
ethical and legal code enshrined in Islam's holy book the Koran and
the teachings of the prophet Mohammed. The government maintains that
more than 90 percent of its laws already conform to Sharia and that
the rest will be brought in line gradually.
   President Hosni Mubarak's government systematically cracks down
on violence-prone fundamentalists, invoking an emergency law in
force since Moslem extremists assassinated Mubarak's predecessor
Anwar Sadat in Cairo in 1981. The law gives police wide powers,
including detention without trial.
   Interior Minister Zaki Badr, whose ministry is responsible for
internal security, said in April that more than 1,000 Moslem
extremists were in custody. There has been no official update since.
</TEXT>
