<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-SingingParliament     07-10 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Singing Parliament,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Assembly Welcomes Bush with a Song</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's new National Assembly made its
warm welcome of President Bush evident today in unorthodox fashion
for a legislative body.
   It serenaded him.
   As Bush and Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski took their
seats at the front of the combined meeting of the Senate and Sejm, a
low stirring rose up in the rear of the chamber.
   Soon the hall was filled with the melody of ``Sto Lat,'' a
traditional Polish song that is the local variant of ``For He's A
Jolly Good Fellow.''
   The strains grew louder as the song drew to a close, with even
Jaruzelski appearing to join in for the last refrain.
   The song goes:
   ``A hundred years, a hundred years,
   ``Let him live, live for us.
   ``Once again, once again
   ``Let him live for us.''
   Bush nodded in acknowledgement of the melody before delivering a
speech promising Poland a $100 million aid package.
</TEXT>
