<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Maps     07-10 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Maps,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Produces First Accurate Maps of Moscow in Half Century</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in 50 years the government is
producing accurate maps of the capital, the official Tass news
agency said today.
   In the past, maps of the city were deliberately distorted and
among ``the manifestations of the policy of secrecy which quite
often covered up lawlessness and arbitrariness,'' Tass said.
   As a result, Tass said, maps failed to be adequate guides both
for tourists and Muscovites.
   A familiar saying among Soviets that is often passed on to
foreigners is: ``If you don't know where you are, you don't belong
there.''
   But the new map of Moscow, ``prepared by the main board of
Geodesy and Cartography on the strength of a topographic survey of
the city, represents Moscow as it is in actual fact for the first
time in half a century,'' Tass said.
   The news agency said there are more than 3,100 avenues, squares,
streets and lanes in Moscow. ``Every street of the city is shown on
the new map and its name is listed in a supplement which is
published as a separate booklet,'' Tass said.
   It did not say where or when the map would be made available to
the public.
</TEXT>
