<FIRST>r w PM-Panama-Bullet     07-10 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Bullet,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Tightened at Panama Base Folowing Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security was tightened over the weekend at Fort
Amador, in Panama, after a bullet from an AK-47 rifle struck the
bedroom of the child of a U.S. Army colonel, the Pentagon said today.
   No one was injured in the incident Saturday, in which the bullet
entered the home of Col. Jorge Torres, the commander of the U.S.
Army Southern Command's signal brigade, the Pentagon said.
   Military police investigators on the scene said the bullet
``apparently came from the vicinity of the PDF (Panama Defense
Forces) compound'' in nearby Chorillo, according to a statement
issued by the Southern Command and relayed by Pentagon officials.
   The colonel and his wife ``were visibly shaken'' by the early
morning shot, which landed in the center of their son's room, the
statement said.
   The bullet came through a second-story window, penetrated an
interior wooden door and dropped to the floor less than a foot from
the child's bed, the statement said.
   U.S. authorities protested the incident to senior Panamanian
Defense officials, the statement said.
   Fort Amador, a facility jointly used by U.S. and Panamanian
military forces, is located near Balboa in the Panama Canal area.
</TEXT>
