<SECOND>PM-Bush-Polish Names, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Jaruzelski Right, Stelmachowski Wrong</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs. ADDS 1 graf with additional pronouncers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush faced today what be the
biggest hurdle on his trip to Poland: trying to get through those
multi-syllabic Polish names without stumbling.
   He didn't quite make it, but he made a good try.
   At the beginning of his speech to parliament, Bush paid greetings
to Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski, Sejm speaker Mikolaj
Kozakiewicz, Senate speaker Andrzej Stelmachowski and Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski.
   He did a passable job on Jaruzelski and Kozakiewicz, but the
others were a muddle.
   What should have been pronounced Stel-ma-HOV-ski came out
``Stal-ma-CHOW-ski'' and Ra-KOFF-ski came out ``Ra-KOW-ski.''
   If he felt self-conscious about the task, Bush could take comfort
from the fact that Poles have trouble saying his name, too.
   It usually comes out ``Boosh.''
   Jaruzelski, by the way, is pronounced Yah-ruh-ZEL-ski, and
Kozakiewicz is Ko-za-KIEH-vich.
