<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NewsroomMinorities     07-10 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newsroom Minorities,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor Sees Slippage in Desegregating News Staffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``A resurgence of apathy'' risks reducing the
percentage of minorities on the staffs of the country's newspapers,
the president of the American Society for Newspaper Editors said
today.
   ``Employment freezes, layoffs and last-hired, first-fired
policies threaten to undermine years of minority recruiting,'' said
Loren Ghiglione, who is editor of a small New England newspaper.
   ``Talk of racial diversity has given way to talk of marketing,
competition and circulation. Editors that have established
internship programs for minority students ask whether, given the
tone of recent U.S. Supreme Court decisions, they face
reverse-discrimination suits,'' he said.
   To counter indifference to the ASNE's goal of making newsroom
staffs equivalent to the racial diversity of the general population
by the year 2000, Ghiglione said he has set out on a three-week
cross-country trip. He will meet with about 100 newspaper editors
and publishers to try to persuade them to step up minority
recruitment.
   He told a news conference that indifference, rather than
hostility, has been the chief problem. He said he found only one
daily among the seven published in Maine employed any blacks,
Hispanics, Asian-Americans or Native Americans on their staffs
despite a sharp increase in Maine's Native American population.
   ``I don't think it's an exaggeration to say that the industry
faces a crisis,'' Ghiglione said. ``Several factors _ a so-so
economy, recent Supreme Court decisions (on affirmative action
programs), a resurgence of apathy on the part of the press and
politicians _ suggest that further progress will not come easily.
   ``Indeed, it may not come at all unless each one of us in the
newspaper industry puts more effort into overcoming indffence and
desegregating an industry where 54 percent of the newsrooms still
are all white.''
   On his own paper, the News of Southbridge, Mass., Ghiglione said,
the newsroom staff of 10 includes three minorities. He said that
puts the lie to the excuse offered by many editors, especially on
small papers, that they cannot find qualified minorities.
   ``They can't tell me a tiny newspaper can't recruit,'' he said,
citing his paper's use of job fairs and contacts with black
colleges. ``I'm telling them they can.''
   In April, an ASNE survey, reflecting responses from 64 percent of
the nation's dailies, found minority staffers account for 7.54
percent of the nation's newsroom workforce of 56,200 _ an increase
from 7.02 percent a year earlier. But 54 percent of surveyed papers
reported they did not have one minority staffer.
   If every paper in the country added one minority person to its
staff, Ghiglione said, the rate of increase would jump fivefold
overnight. ``You need to educate newspapers that haven't even
thought about the problem,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
