<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-10 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident's Trial Suspended in Uproar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a dissident clergyman
accused of traveling to North Korea was postponed Monday after 150
relatives and friends jeered the judge.
   Also Monday, police stepped up their manhunt for three student
leaders who encouraged travel to the communist nation, offering
rewards of $7,500 for each one's capture.
   A thousand police ringed the Seoul District Criminal Courthouse
when the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan arrived for the second day of his trial.
   More than 150 family members and friends cheered Moon's arrival.
When Judge Chung Sang-hak ordered silence, they protested loudly.
Some shouted anti-government slogans.
   Moon's son, Sung-kun, 36, and Shin Sung-myo, 69, mother of a
political prisoner, were taken away by police.
   The judge postponed the trial until July 24.
   Moon is charged with violating the national security law for a
nine-day trip to Pyongyang in March, when he met President Kim Il
Sung on unifying the peninsula. He faces penalties ranging from
seven years in jail to death.
   South Korea forbids trips to North Korea without approval, saying
talks on reunification must be left to the government.
   Song Han-ho, a vice minister for unification, said Monday he has
told Pyongyang that South Korea was postponing a third round of
talks to arrange a conference to ease tensions.
   Song accused Pyongyang of hypocrisy and trying to subvert the
Seoul government by inviting dissidents to visit while also seeking
dialogue with South Korean authorities.
   Moon, a 71-year-old Presbyterian minister, and his traveling
companion, Yoo Won-ho, 59, were arrested April 13 when they returned
from Pyongyang.
   Yoo testified he did not consider North Korea ``an anti-state
group'' because of President Roh Tae-woo's announced intention to
ease tensions with Pyongyang.
   Meanwhile, the Agency for National Security Planning announced it
will free Lee Chul-yong, an opposition lawmaker arrested for
questioning about whether he had prior knowledge of an illegal visit
to North Korea by a colleague in his Party for Peace and Democracy.
Under South Korean law, detained people must be charged or released
after 48 hours.
   Ten people have been arrested in the visit by legislator Suh
Kyung-won, who was taken into custody June 28. But Lee's detention
proved controversial after intelligence agents first tried
unsuccessfully to detain him by force Thursday.
   Korea was divided at the end of World War II. In 1946, North
Korea invaded South Korea, starting a bloody three-year war.
</TEXT>
