<HEAD>Precede: HAMBURG</HEAD>
<HEAD>East German Leader Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Honecker released from hospital.
Pickup 7th graf `Honecker, who...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker was released from
a hospital today after treatment for a gallstone and began his
annual vacation on schedule, the government-run news agency ADN said.
   The brief agency report gave no other details.
   The 76-year-old Communist Party leader was forced to return home
early from a Warsaw Pact summit in Romania on Saturday.
   At the time, ADN said he was suffering from an ``acute
gallbladder ailment,'' but made no other mention of Honecker's
condition until today's report.
   Earlier today, a West German newspaper said doctors were fighting
to save Honecker's life. The report by the mass-circulation
newspaper Bild, which quoted no sources, said Honecker was in the
intensive care unit of an East Berlin hospital.
   Honecker, who became East Germany's Communist Party leader in
1971 and assumed the additional post of head of state in 1976,
appeared to be in robust health and alert during recent public
appearances.
   But some West German newspapers, including Bild, have reported in
recent months that Honecker's concentration appeared to be failing
and that he had speech problems.
