<FIRST>r a AM-FBI-Cohn 1stLd-Writethru a0598 07-10 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Cohn, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0598,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: FBI Investigated Roy Cohn for Communist Links</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD year of correspondent's letter; PICKS
UP 4th graf pvs, `The investigation ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Cohn, who as an aide to Sen. Joseph McCarthy
in the 1950s made his reputation as an anti-communist crusader, was
himself investigated by the FBI for communist links, a newspaper
reported Monday.
   New York Newsday said it had obtained files under the Freedom of
Information Act that showed that an anonymous correspondent in 1950
wrote to the FBI alleging that Cohn was an active supporter of a
leftist congressman and ``affiliated with several Commie outfits.''
   A federal loyalty review board exonerated Cohn a year later after
an FBI investigation failed to uncover any such evidence, Newsday
said.
   The investigation was contained in 2,000 pages of FBI files
covering 1948 until just before Cohn's death at 59 in 1986.
   Newsday said the files also showed that Hoover and other top
Justice Department officials distrusted Cohn in the early 1950s and
sought to keep information from him, sometimes because Cohn had a
propensity for passing off FBI information as his own.
   At the same time, Newsday said, the files are replete with kudos
from Hoover for Cohn's anti-communist stance. Cohn and Hoover
developed a close relationship.
   As early as 1954 there were allegations that Cohn was homosexual,
but the files contained no evidence that the FBI investigated that
aspect of Cohn's life.
   Cohn always denied the charges. A biography after his death from
AIDS included accounts of alleged sexual encounters with men.
   Cohn was chief counsel to McCarthy, whose Senate hearings helped
create the anti-communist hysteria of the 1950s that cost many
people their jobs and reputations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
