<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NewsroomMinorities     07-10 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newsroom Minorities,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor Calls for `Desegregating' His Profession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors said Monday that the U.S. press may become a
bastion unless publishers insist on ``desegregating an industry
where 54 percent of the newsrooms still are all white.''
   Loren Ghiglione, who runs the Southbridge (Mass.) News, said he
set out on a three-week cross-country trip last week to visit two
dozen newspapers and meet about 100 editors, publishers and owners
in an effort to increase the industry's minority recruting and
hiring.
   Speaking at a news conference Monday, he sounded pessimistic.
   Slight increases in recent years in employment of blacks,
Hispanics, Asians and American Indians stand to be reversed by a
wave of indifference unless newspaper owners, especially at small
papers, demand that editors recruit minority beginners, Ghiglione
said.
   ``They can't tell me a tiny newspaper can't recruit,'' he said,
citing his own 7,000-circulation paper's use of job fairs and
contacts with black colleges. ``I'm telling them they can.''
   Ghiglione, who is white, said three of the 10 people in his
newsrooms are members of minorities. The paper, he said, is stronger
because of the diversity of views they bring.
   On the first leg of the trip, through Maine, he said he found
only one of seven daily papers had any minorities. He said he has
found no hostility to his goal, but widespread indifference.
   ``You need to educate newspapers that haven't even thought about
the problem,'' he said.
   ``I don't think it's an exaggeration to say that the industry
faces a crisis. Several factors _ a so-so economy, recent Supreme
Court decisions (on affirmative action programs), a resurgence of
apathy on the part of the press and politicians _ suggest that
further progress will not come easily.
   ``Indeed, it may not come at all unless each one of us in the
newspaper industry puts more effort into overcoming indifference and
desegregating an industry where 54 percent of the newsrooms still
are all white.''
   In April, an ASNE survey reflecting responses from 64 percent of
the nation's dailies found minority staffers account for 7.54
percent of the nation's newsroom work force of 56,200 _ an increase
from 7.02 percent a year earlier.
   But 54 percent of surveyed papers reported they did not have one
minority staffer.
   Ghiglione cited Census projections that say minorities will
become a majority of the U.S. population in the next century. To
serve such an audience and market, ``the newspaper industry has to
become more than a 92.5 percent white symbol of the status quo,'' he
said.
   He said he doesn't worry when larger papers hire the minority
staff he has recruited and trained.
   ``We lose all our good people,'' he said. ``We'll always be a
graduate school.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
