<FIRST>r i AM-Honecker     07-10 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Leader Treated For Gallstone Ailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German Communist Party leader Erich Honecker
was released from a hospital Monday after treatment for a gallstone,
the state-run news agency ADN said.
   The brief dispatch followed a report in a West German newspaper
that Honecker, 76, was fighting for his life.
   ADN said he was released after being treated for a gallstone and
began his summer vacation on schedule, but the news agency gave no
other details.
   Honecker was forced to return home early from a Warsaw Pact
summit in Romania on Saturday. At the time, ADN said he was
suffering from an ``acute gallbladder ailment,'' but made no other
mention of Honecker's condition until Monday's report.
   The report came shortly after Karl-Heinz Hiersmann, a leader of
the West Germany's opposition Social Democratic party in Bavaria,
said Honecker's ailment was ``nothing serious.''
   Hiersmann said in East Berlin that his information came from
Hermann Axen, a member of East Germany's policy-making party
Politburo.
   The West German newspaper Bild reported earlier today that
doctors were fighting to save Honecker's life. The Bild report,
which quoted no sources, said Honecker was in the intensive care
unit of an East Berlin hospital.
   Honecker, who became party chief in 1971 and head of state in
1976, appeared to be in robust health and alert during recent public
appearances.
   But Bild and some other West German newspapers have reported that
Honecker's concentration appeared to be failing in recent months and
that he had speech problems.
</TEXT>
