<FIRST>r i AM-Ochoa     07-10 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ochoa,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentences Confirmed For Cuban Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba's top government council, led by
President Fidel Castro, turned down an army hero's appeal and
affirmed his death sentence by firing squad for drug trafficking,
the official Cuban news agency said Monday.
   The 29-member Council of State unanimously upheld the death
sentences against former Maj. Gen. Arnaldo Ochoa and three other
officers, according to the Prensa Latina report, which was monitored
in Mexico.
   The decision apparently exhausted the last appeal for Ochoa, who
was convicted of helping smuggle tons of cocaine and shiploads of
marijuana into the United States.
   The council made its decision Sunday night, Prensa Latina said.
   The news agency did not say when the death sentences would be
carried out or whether Castro could or would consider executive
clemency. The Council of State is made up of senior government
officials and is chaired by Castro.
   The military division of the supreme court already had refused to
overturn the death sentences given Ochoa and Col. Antonio de la
Guardia, Maj. Armando Padron and Capt. Jorge Martinez.
   The highly publicized case has been an embarrassment to Castro
and the Communist Party. Castro spent years denying U.S. accusations
that Cuba was being used to smuggle drugs, saying the accusations
were part of a U.S. plot to discredit the revolution.
   Ochoa and three other officers were sentenced to death for their
parts in helping smuggle Colombian cocaine and Jamaican marijuana
into the United States across Cuban seas and airspace.
   The court-martial prosecutor said that the men had committed
crimes against foreign nations, among them the United States.
   Ten other officers were convicted in the case, which also
involved smuggling of diamonds, ivory and dollars, and sentenced to
terms ranging from 10 to 30 years in prison.
   All 14 of the convicted men were officers of the Cuban armed
forces or held high positions in the security staff of the Interior
Ministry.
   A military court of honor stripped Ochoa and the other 13
defendants of all rank and decorations and gave them dishonorable
discharges before the court-martial began last week.
   On Friday, the court-martial convicted them on charges of drug
trafficking, corruption and treason.
   The arrests and trial constituted the biggest scandal to rock
Cuba since Castro came to power Jan. 1, 1959.
   Ochoa, 57, had fought alongside Castro in Cuba's rugged mountains
during the revolution that overthrew dictator Fulgencio Batista,
became a trusted aide and carried out confidential missions for
Castro.
   Ochoa had been named a Hero of the Republic, the nation's highest
military honor, for leading Cuban military expeditions to Angola and
Ethiopia and heading a military advisory team to Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
