<FIRST>u a PM-Aguilar     07-10 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aguilar,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Arraigned On Conspiracy, Racketeering Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Robert Aguilar pleaded
innocent today to charges of using his office to do favors for
convicted felons, crimes punishable by up to 55 years in prison.
   Aguilar, the fourth federal judge in the nation to be indicted in
the last decade and the first ever for racketeering, was arraigned
before a visiting federal judge, Howard Bratton of New Mexico, and
released without bail. His trial has also been assigned to an
outside judge, Louis Bechtle of Philadelphia.
   The 58-year-old judge stood with his lawyers for less than three
minutes before the bench and spoke only a few words _ identifying
himself, giving his age, and saying ``the plea is not guilty'' _
before Bratton said further reading of the charges was not necessary.
   Bratton denied a request by Justice Department prosecutor Ralph
Martin to prohibit Aguilar from contacting potential witnesses.
Defense lawyer Patrick Hallinan told reporters the request would
have barred Aguilar from speaking to ``half of his family'' and
described it as part of the government's campaign to portray Aguilar
as a corrupt judge.
   Aguilar left through a rear exit and did not speak with
reporters. Before the hearing, he sat talking and laughing with
defense lawyers and did not look at codefendants Rudy Tham, an
imprisoned former labor leader, and Abe Chapman, a self-styled
former mobster related to Aguilar by marriage.
   Aguilar, a 1980 appointee of President Jimmy Carter, was indicted
by a federal grand jury last month on eight felony charges. He has
relinquished most of his duties while the case is pending.
   He is accused of approaching two other federal judges to seek
favorable treatment for Tham and another man, Ronald Cloud, a former
law client of Aguilar's who was convicted of bank fraud; of trying
to help Tham get a new trial while Tham arranged a job for Aguilar's
brother; and of tipping Chapman that his phone was being tapped.
   Aguilar is also accused of helping his former secretary, Vera
Hoff, remain a fugitive in Mexico, where she fled after being
convicted of tax evasion. The judge is additionally charged with
lying to the FBI and advising one of Tham's lawyers to lie to the
grand jury.
   The racketeering charge alleges Aguilar used his office as a
racketeering ``enterprise'' to obstruct justice.
   Hallinan, speaking to reporters after the hearing, said he had
investigated the case ``assiduously'' and ``can find no substance to
any of the allegations.''
   He said Aguilar's mood was ``one of great optimism ... a
conviction that the final result will be a happy one.''
   Tham and Chapman also pleaded innocent to the charges. No trial
date has been set.
</TEXT>
