<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FamilySlayings     07-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Slayings,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent to Murdering Family 18 Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A churchgoing accountant arrested on a TV
viewer's tip in June pleaded innocent Monday to murdering five
family members 18 years ago.
   The man authorities say is John E. List, 63, but who calls
himself Robert P. Clark did not speak at the hearing, entering his
plea through his lawyer.
   Superior Court Judge William Wertheimer agreed to the
prosecutor's request for $5 million bail and set trial for Dec. 4.
   FBI agents said List assumed a new identity after shooting to
death his three children, wife and mother at their home in Westfield
in 1971.
   Clark, arrested in Richmond, Va., denies he is List, but FBI
agents said they identified him through fingerprints and a scar from
a mastoid operation.
   The bodies of List's wife and children were found a month after
the killings, neatly laid side-by-side in the ballroom of their
19-room mansion. The body of his 85-year-old mother was in a bedroom.
   A worldwide manhunt ensued, but all leads hit dead ends until
June 1, when Clark was arrested at the Richmond accounting firm
where he had worked for 18 months.
   FBI agents had been tipped off by a viewer of the TV program
``America's Most Wanted,'' which 11 days earlier had run a segment
on List and shown a bust depicting how the former Sunday school
teacher might look today.
   Authorities say List fled to Colorado, then Virginia, remarried
and built a new life without changing his appearance, profession or
reputation as a quiet churchgoing Lutheran.
   His new wife said she knew nothing of his alleged past but that
she would stand by him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
