<FIRST>r i AM-US-MiddleEast 410   07-10 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Middle East, 410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker to Probe Israel's Intentions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Monday that he will send an emissary to the Middle East to test
Israel's commitment to holding elections among Palestinian Arabs on
the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Baker, who is traveling with President Bush, said at a news
conference that the adoption of a hard-line stance by Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir at a Likud party convention last week raised
questions about the government position.
   The emissary, Baker said, will ``determine the extent to which
the Israeli government is still committed to their elections
proposals in the aftermath of the Likud party convention.''
   In Jerusalem on Monday, Labor Party leaders recommended that
their party quit the governing coalition to protest the Likud bloc's
tougher conditions for peace talks.
   The move could bring down the government and, eight months after
the last national elections, force a new vote.
   Baker said four points approved by Shamir ``give rise, at least
in our minds, to questions about the seriousness of purpose.''
   The Likud leadership opposes establishment of a Palestinian state
and yielding territory on the West Bank or in Gaza, as well as
barring Palestinians in East Jerusalem from voting and requiring an
end to violence in the territories before balloting could begin.
   Shamir's plan would provide local self-rule to Palestinians for
five years after which Israel, Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinians
would negotiate a settlement.
   None of the points marked a change in Shamir's position, but
their reaffirmation while the administration is failing to persuade
the Arabs to agree to elections is considered a setback to U.S.
diplomacy.
   Baker doesn't support a Mideast peace conference, a proposal that
has widespread Arab and West European support.
   ``The time is not right now,'' he said.
   Shamir is opposed to such a conference because it might give the
Soviets a prominent role in support of Arab positions.
   A senior U.S. official traveling with Baker said no parallel
talks were planned with the Palestine Liberation Organization. PLO
support for elections is considered essential, but it has denounced
them as a ploy to prevent a Palestinian state.
   Baker didn't say whom he would send to Israel next week, but
added that reports that it would be Deputy Secretary of State
Lawrence Eagleburger could be mistaken.
</TEXT>
