<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: ``Licence'' is cq.</UNK>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez's acting abilities are
up for review in the latest James Bond movie, ``Licence to Kill.''
   ``My name is Martinez, Bob Martinez,'' the governor said in his
best Bond imitation as he welcomed 300 guests Sunday for the
Tallahassee premiere of the movie, which stars Timothy Dalton as
Bond. The film opens this week across the state.
   Martinez's non-speaking cameo as a Customs agent in an airport
scene drew applause from the audience. That scene and much of the
rest of the film were shot in Key West.
   The governor got the spot as a result of a 1987 trip to
California to drum up movie business for Florida.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The role of Jack Nicholson's girlfriend in
``Batman'' was practically Jerry Hall's for the asking.
   ``I was making a commercial in the studio where the movie was
being shot,'' the actress and model says in the August issue of
Glamour magazine. ``Some man had his door open and hollered:
`Beauty! Where did you come from?'''
   ``I saw that his door said `Batman,' so I said, `Do you have a
job for me?' He said, `Are you kidding? Of course we do!'''
   The man, who was not identified in the article, introduced her to
the director, according to Glamour. Hall later auditioned and won
the part.
   Nicholson plays the arch-villain Joker in the hit movie starring
Michael Keaton as Batman.
   Glamour says the only thing Hall hasn't talked her way into is a
walk down the aisle with long-time boyfriend Mick Jagger. ``I always
wanted to get married. But when I wanted to, he didn't and when he
wanted to, I didn't,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Diana's younger brother, Viscount Althorp,
said Monday he is marrying former model Victoria Lockwood after a
six-week whirlwind courtship.
   Althorp, 25, said he met his 24-year-old fiancee at the home of
mutual friends, and they plan to marry in the fall.
   ``We have told each other's families and they all seem
delighted,'' he said.
   Althorp, who works for NBC, said the romance developed ``quite
quickly.''
   He said his bride-to-be had worked as a model in New York for two
years and then in Paris.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Barry Goldwater, plagued for years
with an arthritic knee and hip, was reported in good condition
Monday after corrective surgery.
   The 80-year-old Arizona Republican is doing ``very, very well''
and probably will be discharged in in four to seven days, said Mary
Starmann-Harrison, chief executive officer of St. Luke's Medical
Center.
   The surgery was Wednesday.
   Goldwater underwent knee surgery at St. Luke's in 1987 to relieve
pain from a college football injury. He underwent hip operations in
1976, 1981 and 1986.
   He also underwent triple-bypass heart surgery in 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eileen Brennan broke her left leg, which
had been severely injured in a 1982 auto accident, and bumped her
head when she fell from a stage into an orchestra pit during a
rehearsal of ``Annie.''
   Ms. Brennan was in fair condition Monday at Research Hospital &amp;
Medical Center after the accident Sunday, said Julie Millard,
hospital spokeswoman.
   The actress was to play the role of the orphanage's head mistress
when the musical opened at the Starlight Theatre Monday night. She
will be replaced by a member of the Starlight company.
   Ms. Brennan, 54, played Capt. Doreen Lewis in the movie and TV
series ``Private Benjamin.''
   In 1982, she was nearly killed when a car struck her as she was
crossing a street in Venice, Calif. She had a skull fracture, and
facial bones and both her legs were broken.
   Pins were inserted in her left leg to help the bones heal, and
she underwent plastic surgery to repair facial injuries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Munchkin Dale Paullin's role as a
Lollipop Boy in the 50-year-old ``The Wizard of Oz'' is finally
paying off.
   Paullin, one of the few cast members still alive, has been hired
to help promote the release of the movie's uncut version on video
next month.
   ``I haven't seen it myself, and I can't wait,'' said Paullin, who
at 4 feet, 6 inches is more than a foot taller than he was as a
16-year-old Munchkin.
   It's the first time the movie starring Judy Garland has opened
any doors for him, he said.
   ``It hasn't been until the last six, eight years when the adults
took over and the memorabilia came out. Now is when the Wizard of Oz
is really popular,'' he said. ``Before now it was just a kiddie
show.''
   Paullin is one of three Lollipop Boys who present Dorothy with a
lollipop and welcome her to the Land of Oz.
   Only a few Munchkins are left to tell the tale of sweltering
shooting conditions and the excitement of building one of the first
color movies.
</TEXT>
