<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola     07-10 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Still Concerned About Angola, IMF</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States still has serious
reservations about admitting Marxist-led Angola to the International
Monetary Fund, a State Department spokesman said Monday.
   Richard Boucher appeared to rebut published reports that the Bush
administration would switch its vote and favor Angola's admittance
to the IMF as a gesture of appreciation for the recent decision by
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos to open negotiations with
rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.
   Boucher called dos Santos' decision to meet with Savimbi a
``significant step toward national reconciliation,'' but said the
United States would not reward the government before the process is
complete.
   ``The United States continues to have serious reservations about
admitting Angola to the IMF,'' Boucher said. ``We have no intention
of establishing diplomatic relations with Angola before national
reconciliation is achieved.''
   The Angolan government had hoped that opening negotiations with
Savimbi together with the withdrawal of Cuban forces would lead to
full diplomatic relations with the United States.
   The IMF executive board has voted to admit Angola, a step the
United States alone could not block.
</TEXT>
