<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia-US     07-10 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-US,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says Namibian Independence on Track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senior U.S. official for African
affairs said Monday that Namibia's independence plan is on track but
that Pretoria and the South-West Africa People's Organization should
ease tension in the territory.
   Herman Cohen, U.S. assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, spoke after talks with Namibia's South African
administrator, Louis Pienaar, and the U.N. representative to the
territory, Martti Ahtisaari.
   Cohen said Namibia's yearlong independence process has passed an
``irreversible threshold.'' He siad he is pleased with the ongoing
repatriation of Namibian refugees and registration of voters for
November elections.
   However, he warned South Africa and the South-West Africa
People's Organization that they are not doing enough to reduce the
suspicion that developed during their 23-year bush war.
   The guerrilla organization accuses the territory's South
African-controlled police force of intimidating its supporters in
northern towns and villages where it draws most support.
   ``We took very seriously the complaint of the U.N.
secretary-general (Javier Perez de Cuellar) about the excessive use
of force in northern Namibia and the abuses by the police force,''
Cohen told a news conference.
   He called on South African officials to work on ``defusing the
rather tense situation'' in northern Namibia.
   He also noted South Africa is uneasy because many guerrillas have
remained at camps in Angola rather than return to Namibia as
civilians.
   ``I would urge SWAPO to repatriate former members as soon as
possible so they can be here as civilians and voters rather than in
Angola as sequestered fighters,'' he said.
   South Africa agreed to end its 74-year rule of Namibia under a
regional peace agreement in exchange for the repatriation of 50,000
Cuban troops in Angola.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization is expected to win
the elections. No date for independence has been set, but it is
expected early next year. More than 5,000 U.N. monitors are
overseeing the process in Namibia.
</TEXT>
