<DOCNO> AP890710-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissidents     07-10 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Dissidents Say Crackdown Was Crueler than Cultural Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China,Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two leading Chinese dissidents who escaped to the
West told a newspaper the June 4 crackdown was a massacre ``100
times crueler'' than the Cultural Revolution.
   ``The cruelty of Deng Xiaoping goes way beyond that of Mao
(Tse-tung) and Chiang Kai-shek,'' university professor Yan Jiaqi was
quoted as telling Le Monde newspaper.
   ``The massacre of June 4 was 10, 20, 100 times crueler than the
Cultural Revolution.'' During the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution,
``people were suppressed with clubs, whereas today, they use tanks
and rifles to gun down the crowd,'' Yan said. He is former director
of the Beijing Institute of Political Studies.
   Student leader Wu'er Kaixi was quoted as saying 2,000 dead was
the ``most prudent figure'' for the number of demonstrators killed
when troops marched on Tiananmen Square on June 3-4.
   Yan and Wu'er are wanted by the Chinese government for
``counterrevolutionary crimes.'' They have been in hiding in France,
where the press has published unconfirmed reports they are awaiting
papers to go to the United States.
   China formally protested to France on Friday, calling the two
``criminals.'' It said their activities on French soil aim at
overthrowing the Beijing government and therefore granting them
asylum is ``a gross interference'' in China's internal affairs.
France froze relations with Beijing after the June 4 crackdown.
   Wu'er described to Le Monde the June 4 scene:
   ``I saw the army arrive with rifles in the northern sector of the
square and, row by row, decimate the students. About a dozen fell at
a time.'' In one section alone, he said, there were 200 victims.
   Yan was quoted as saying Deng, China's senior leader, ``behaves
like an emperor.''
   In another interview, published by Der Spiegel newsmagazine in
West Germany on Monday, Yan said thousands of executions could
follow. Twenty-seven people have been executed in China since June
4, some student leaders and others common criminals.
   ``Deng now will, so I believe, have thousands of people killed,
first the students, then the intellectuals,'' Der Spiegel quoted Yan
as saying.
   ``The persecution will now be directed against all progressive
people who stand up for freedom and democracy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PresidentialVisit`MakesItEasterToPersist'     07-10 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>Presidential Visit `Makes It Easter To Persist'</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Solidarity signs along Warsaw's streets
show that much has changed since George Bush visited two years ago;
the long lines outside poorly stocked stores show that much has not.
   The once-banned flags of the independent labor organization now
are commonplace. But Polish citizens still must wait, often for
hours, to buy essential goods.
   Amid the contrasts, Bush halted his motorcade on Monday to shake
the hands of people lining the city's streets.
   ``In these hardships, there is someone we can count on,'' said
Elzbieta Laskowska. As Bush worked the crowd _ only 4,000 or so
strong _ she clutched paper U.S. and Polish flags in one hand and
shook Bush's hand with the other.
   ``We have real friends in America. ... Friends are found when one
needs them,'' she said, quoting a Polish saying.
   ``It makes it easier to persist and go on,'' Barbara Araszawska
said after seeing the president.
   But even as they applauded Bush _ ``We hope he makes Poland the
51st state,'' joked one man _ the Polish people acknowledged that
the United States will not alone lift their country from the
economic slide that forces them to wait hours to get into stores
with little stock. They face more belt tightening as the standard of
living falls further and further behind the rest of Europe.
   A retired shoe factory worker who identified herself only as
Helena commented:
   ``What's going on here is very good. ... We won't be able to get
over our crisis without others' help. But if we don't get to work,
no one is going to help us overcome our problems.''
   Even as economic hardships persist, however, Polish society is
becoming more open.
   Solidarity now has 260 members in the 560-seat parliament. One of
the songs with which the crowds serenaded Bush was the union's
anthem, ``Solidarity. Solidarity.''
   In the crowds that turned out to greet Bush were Poles wearing
Solidarity T-shirts or carrying shopping bags emblazoned with the
logo of the independent trade union banned for seven years until
historic reform accords reached by the communist government and the
opposition in April.
   ``As a Solidarity activist, only half a year ago I was not
allowed into an enterprise where I had business to do and now I am
employed there and I am a deputy to the Polish parliament,'' Zbignie
Kaminski, an economist, remarked as he awaited Bush's speech to the
only freely elected national legislative body in Eastern Europe.
   Janusz Onyszkiewicz, another member of parliament and a
Solidarity spokesman, sat near Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, the
Communist Party leader, at a luncheon Bush gave at the U.S.
ambassador's residence and commented on the union's dramatic change
in fortunes, which were strongly supported by the United States.
   ``This is rather strange when you think a year ago I was in
prison,'' Onyszkiewicz said after dining on minted cantaloupe soup
and roast tenderloin of beef.
   Earlier in the day, about 4,000 people gathered as Bush and his
wife, Barbara, laid a wreath of flowers at the Tomb of the Unknown
Soldier.
   At Umschlagplatz, the square on the edge of the one-time Warsaw
ghetto where more than 300,000 Jews were loaded onto trains bound
for the Treblinka gas chambers in 1942 and 1943, the Bushes were met
by Poland's lone rabbi, Menachem Jaskowitz, and by Marek Edelman,
the last surviving commander of the Jewish ghetto uprising of April
1943.
   Edelman said later he had told the president that ``rich America
must sometimes give a chunk so that the world can become free, so
that these things do not happen again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-StealthTest     07-10 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Test,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radar-Evading Stealth Bomber Whistles Down Runway for Ground Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $500 million B-2 stealth bomber
revved its engines and taxied across a desert runway at up to 100
mph Monday, operating under its own power for the first time.
   The Air Force pronounced the tests of the sinister-looking,
black-and-gray flying wing a success and said high-speed tests of
the radar-evading nuclear bomber would be conducted later this week
with a view toward its first flight soon afterward.
   ``You've got a lot of firsts here today,'' said Maj. Pat
Mullaney. ``You have the first time under its own power, you have it
turning. All this has only been done before on computer
simulations.''
   The sleek, boomerang-shaped strategic bomber rolled from its
super-secret research hangar and taxied back and forth on an
11,000-foot runway at Air Force Plant 42, the crucible through which
virtually all Air Force aircraft pass.
   ``I love it,'' said Air Force spokeswoman Capt. Tess Taft, waving
an American flag.
   Three taxi tests at different speeds stopped traffic on Sierra
Highway next to the plant and offered the first unobstructed view of
the craft since it was unveiled for the news media on Nov. 22.
   At approximately $500 million each, the plane is the nation's
most expensive and controversial, joining the nation's arsenal
during a period of increasing Pentagon budget cuts.
   The stealth is designed to drop nuclear bombs and fire cruise
missiles and evade radar and infrared detection.
   Despite delays that have plagued the B-2, Brig. Gen. Richard
Scofield, B-2 program director, said, ``Everybody in the Air Force
is convinced that we are working the schedule the right way. We are
making sure the plane works right for when we do the hazardous
testing, and flight test is hazardous.''
   Tests on the B-2 took place in the Antelope Valley of the Mojave
Desert where the space shuttle was built and where test pilot Chuck
Yeager first broke the sound barrier in 1947.
   For weeks, people fascinated with the eerie manta-like aircraft
have parked nearby, hoping for a glimpse. On Monday, the dozen or so
regulars got an eyeful.
   The plane rolled out of its hangar shortly after sunrise and
stayed in view of highway onlookers for three hours. Periodically,
its engines ran at various pitches and decibels, sometimes blowing a
lonesome whistle across the desert, sometimes accelerating up to a
dull roar.
</TEXT>
