<HEAD>Protesters Shout `Down with Communism'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government Polish demonstrators
shouting ``down with Communism'' greeted President Bush Monday as he
arrived for a formal state dinner hosted by the Communist Party
chief, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   The demonstrators, who also chanted ``Jaruzelski Must Go,'' could
be heard among the 1,000 people outside Radziwill Palace when the
Bushes arrived.
   It was the first protest of Bush's visit to Eastern Europe, which
began Sunday night, and appeared to have been staged by splinter
opposition groups.
   The Bush motorcade pulled straight into the palace driveway and
there was no indication if he heard the chants or saw a sign
reading, ``Poland, like the United States, has a right to be
independent.''
   The dinner was held in a green marble ballroom on the second
floor of the reconstructed 17th century palace used most recently
for the ``round-table'' reform talks between the Solidarity-led
opposition and the communist government.
   Among the 100 guests were political leaders and members of the
opposition, including three top Solidarity trade union advisers.
