<SECOND>AM-Israel-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0629,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed; Two Others Die Of Wounds, Reports Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 1 graf to UPDATE with 10 wounded.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinian teen-agers were shot and killed
by Israeli troops Monday in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
and two others died of wounds suffered in earlier clashes, the army
and Arab reports said.
   The army also said an armed Arab guerrilla was killed over the
weekend near the West Bank city of Hebron but gave no details.
   Ten other Palestinians were shot and wounded Monday in clashes
with troops in the occupied lands, Arab hospital officials said.
   The latest deaths raised to 557 the number of Palestinians killed
in the 19-month uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip. Thirty-five Israelis, including 12 killed in a bus
attack Thursday, also have died in the violence.
   The army said its army tanks and infantry carried out a raid
north of Israel's security zone in Lebanon near the village of
Zillaya in an area controlled by the Hezbollah, or Party of God, a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem militia.
   The announcement said the area was used to stage attacks on
Israeli forces. It said the army ``detained suspects and brought
them for investigation'' to the security zone.
   The village is about 11 miles northwest of the border, outside
the six- to 10-mile zone Israel set up in Lebanon in 1985 to protect
its northern border.
   In another action outside the security zone, the army said, the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia killed three Palestinian
guerrillas near Hasbaya, about six miles northwest of the border. It
said there were no militia casualties.
   The Palestinians killed in the occupied territories Monday
included Rami Mustafa El-Tarisi, 15, who was fatally shot in the
chest in a stone-throwing clash in the Bureij refugee camp in the
Gaza Strip, Arab reports said. The army said it was checking.
   In the West Bank town of Ramallah, 17-year-old Yasser Abu Ghosh
was fatally shot in the head and back by Israeli security men who
arrived in a civilian vehicle, Palestinian reports said.
   An army spokesman, who cannot be identified under military
regulations, said security forces tried to arrest the youth and
opened fire when he refused orders to halt.
   The spokesman described him as a member of the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, a Marxist faction of the PLO, and said
he was wanted for ``attacks on collaborators and as a senior
coordinator of violent actions in the area.''
   Two youths died of wounds suffered earlier:
   _ Iman Awadallah, 13, was hospitalized three days earlier with a
bullet wound in the stomach sustained in a clash in his hometown of
Rafah in the Gaza Strip. He died in Barzilai Hospital near the
Israeli town of Ashkelon, Arab reports said.
   _ Mahyub Musa Khalil, 14, was shot in the head with a rubber
bullet during a raid on the Palestinian village of Tormos Aya near
the West Bank town of Ramallah late Sunday night, the army said. He
died in Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital.
   The so-called rubber bullets, actually rubber-coated steel balls,
were introduced by the army as less lethal than standard ammunition,
but they can kill when fired at close range.
   Israeli authorities on Monday identified the final two victims of
the crash on the Jerusalem-Tel Aviv highway caused by a Palestinian
man who grabbed the bus's steering wheel and plunged the vehicle
into a 200-foot ravine.
   Both victims were Israel: Emil Gruzman, 54, an immigrant from the
Soviet Union, and Menachem Ezrahi, 63 a retired Tel Aviv policeman.
   Two Canadians died in the crash, and 27 other people were
injured. The Palestinian, a passenger, was arrested and was
hospitalized in an Israeli prison.
</TEXT>
