<FIRST>u w AM-Foley     07-10 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Says Congress Won't Vote Federal Pay Hike Without a Share</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley said Monday that
President Bush's proposals to raise pay for judges and top
executive-branch officials cannot win approval without a link to
higher pay for members of Congress.
   Foley said he prefers there to be no connection, but he suggested
his view is not widely shared on Capitol Hill.
   ``There will be ... no disconnection between judges and the
executive branch and Congress,'' he said. ``The underlying reality
of that, in my judgment, is that the votes do not exist to do it.''
   The House speaker, D-Wash., commented at a luncheon with
executives and reporters of The Associated Press
   Any congressional increase would have to meet a
``reasonableness'' test _ unlike the failed 51 percent pay hike
sought early this year _ and would have to be supported by both the
House and Senate, both Democrats and Republicans, and by party
political operatives as well as leaders such as Bush, he said.
   Foley said that even though the previous pay raise idea was
supported by two Republican presidents, the Democratic-controlled
Congress was politically mauled by Republican campaign operatives.
   ``I don't want to get into something where the president says
yes, and the congressional campaign committee says no,'' Foley said.
``That's unacceptable, that sort of good-cop, bad-cop routine.''
   And Foley repeated past criticism of media coverage of the
pay-raise issue, saying the public was not well informed about the
last raise attempt and was whipped into opposition.
   If there is a similar atmosphere the next time, ``if it's a `here
they go again' sort of thing ... beating up on the Congress, I'm not
going to put (lawmakers) through that,'' he said.
   Bush has so far proposed pay increases for judges and for senior
executive branch officials. He has said he will work with Congress
toward a pay raise but has not submitted a plan for boosting
lawmakers' pay.
   The matter of top federal pay scales remains far down the agenda
as Congress returns this week from its Fourth of July recess. Foley
said much of this month will be spent in passing ``all or close to
all'' of the 13 appropriations bills, the annual money measures that
provide the funding for most government programs.
   As for other priorities for the rest of the year, Foley listed
savings and loan bailout legislation, a military spending bill,
budget trims to meet deficit targets, child care and clean air
measures, and family leave and minimum wage bills.
   On other topics, Foley said:
   _ He still plans to resist any immediate attempt to amend the
Constitution to bar flag desecration, preferring to try first
putting the protective language into law. ``It would be wise to
start with a statute. It is unwise to rush into a constitutional
amendment, especially in the heat of this issue. ... I'm not going
to change my mind about that, obviously.''
   _ Bush gets relatively high marks so far in his conduct of
foreign affairs, having reasserted U.S. leadership in NATO, having
struck a proper balance in the U.S. response to China's crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators and having increased consultation with
Congress. Bush's challenge now is keeping alive political and
economic change in Eastern Europe without causing destabilization,
he said.
   _ The bitter partisan mood that surrounded his predecessor, Jim
Wright of Texas, has largely been left behind with Wright's
departure. ``The mood ... is to have a more conciliatory and
mutually respecting environment,'' he said. ``I don't think Jim
broke the rules (in his treatment of Republicans) but I think we
pushed the rules to the edge of the envelope, and that helped to
break down the sense of comity'' in the House.
</TEXT>
