<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Election     07-10 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Election,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Former Governor Leads Presidential Polls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll released Monday said
Fernando Collor de Mello, a 39-year-old former state governor who
leads a new party, holds a 3-1 lead over his nearest rival four
months before the presidential election.
   The former governor of Alagoas state, in the poor northeast, was
preferred by 39 percent of those interviewed, said the Brazilian
Institute of Public Opinion and Statistics.
   Leonel Brizola, former governor of Rio de Janeiro state, was
second with 13 percent, followed by socialist labor leader Luis
Inacio Lula da Silva with 7 percent.
   Brazilians are to vote Nov. 15 for a successor to President Jose
Sarney, who cannot succeed himself. The term is five years.
   It will be the first direct presidential election since 1960,
when Janio Quadros won. The military seized power in 1964 and
relinquished it in 1985.
   Collor de Mello's small National Reconstruction Party was founded
only this year. He rose in the polls from 7 percent in March to 20
percent in April and has led since.
   His rating of 39 percent was slightly below the 43 percent of a
month earlier, but Carlos Augusto Montenegr, director of the polling
institute, said the change was not significant because no other
candidate's performance rose substantially.
   The latest sampling was of 3,753 people in 255 cities questioned
between June 29 and July 5, the institute said, and the margin of
error was 2 percent.
   Brizola's rating was 13 percent, up from 11 percent. The former
leftist firebrand, who represents the Democratic Labor Party and now
projects a more moderate image, is widely considered Collor de
Mello's main competition.
   In 1982, Brizola came from a similar distance back in the polls
to win the Rio governorship.
   Da Silva's position began to erode early this year because of
strikes led by labor groups linked to his radical Workers Party.
   Other candidates include Rep. Ulysses Guimaraes, former speaker
of the House of Represenatives, from the centrist Brazilian
Democratic Movement Party; Sen. Mario Covas of the center-left
Brazilian Social Democracy Party, and wealthy businessman Paulo
Maluf, the 1985 presidential candidate of the military's Democratic
Social Party. Each got 5 percent in the polls.
   Responses to other questions in the survey indicated Brazilians
worry most about unemployment, inflation, health care and education
in that order.
   The popularity of Collor de Mello, a businessman, is considered a
sign of dissatisfaction with Sarney, whom he often criticizes. The
59-year-old president has been unable to curb 1,000 percent annual
inflation, and allegations of corruption in his government arise
frequently.
   As governor of Alagoas, Collor de Mello caught the nation's
attention by refusing to pay state workers known as ``maharajahs''
who had attained high salaries through corruption. The campaign
against such employees spread to other states and has been the core
of his presidential campaign.
   Opponents claim Collor de Mello appointed thousands of civil
servants in his home state and was overly generous in settling a tax
dispute with Alagoas sugar barons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
