<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonRiot     07-10 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Riot,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calm Follows Riot at Jail Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANNING, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police restored order at a jail camp
rife with racial tension Monday after a three-hour uprising left
nine people injured and several buildings in ashes, authorities said.
   The uprising at the county-run, minimum- and medium-security
Banning Rehabilitation Center began late Sunday when officers were
inspecting a mostly black, 55-man barracks, said Riverside County
sheriff's Capt. Jake Bowser.
   The inmates were standing outside the building when Hispanic
inmates from a neighboring barracks ``started pummeling them with
rocks and other debris,'' said Bowser.
   ``When the corrections officers tried to intervene they were
pummeled, too,'' he said.
   Tim Lewis, who lives across the street, said he heard a ``large
explosion, like a sonic blast.'' Flames leaped high into the sky
over the camp and about 15 minutes later a power pole exploded and
plunged the camp into darkness, he said.
   The inmates gave up the battle when officers in riot gear
entered. No shots were fired. ``I think when we opened the gates
with our gear on it got their attention and they complied with our
orders,'' said Bowser.
   Seven inmates were injured in the melee, including two with stab
wounds, and two prison officers suffered minor injuries.
   The kitchen, commissary, work-release center and an operations
building housing corrections officers' lockers were burned, as were
three smaller buildings, three trucks, a county car and a sheriff's
patrol car, Bowser said.
   Bowser had no estimate of damage Monday but said workers were
setting up temporary kitchens to feed inmates. The camp, with a
784-inmate capacity, held 766 inmates, including 113 women, when the
riot erupted.
   ``There were definitely racial overtones,'' Bowser said.
   Inmate Diane Mason, interviewed as she was receiving oxygen in an
ambulance, said she was talking to her boyfriend through a fence
when she heard people yell that there was a fight in the
minimum-security area.
   She said people came running out of the commissary throwing
things. ``All of a sudden a big old fire blazed up out of nowhere,''
Mason said.
   Earlier Monday, helicopters using search lights illuminated the
surrounding land as law officers looked for any escapees. A head
count revealed no inmates were missing, said Bowser.
   About 300 inmates were sent to other jails in Riverside and San
Bernardino counties, Bowser said. Those who remained were locked in
their barracks.
   ``They are real subdued now and I'm sure they aren't happy, but
we had to do this to control the situation,'' Bowser said.
   The jail camp is 90 miles east of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Fires-Glance     07-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires-Glance,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Forest Fires At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state glance at details on fires in the West:
   _Arizona: Fires had burned more than 40,000 acres of forest and
range land through the weekend. The largest fire, along the New
Mexico state line, had burned 14,500 acres but was 98 percent
contained.
   _California: A fire in rugged, roadless terrain in the Big Sur
had blackened 2,140 acres and was 50 percent contained. One man was
killed by a falling tree. In Lassen County, in northeastern
California, a 4,600-acre brush fire that destroyed seven buildings
and burned four firefighters was 60 percent contained. In Southern
California, about 100 campers evacuated because of a 3,600-acre fire
in the Cleveland National Forest 60 miles east of San Diego.
   _Colorado: Crews battled more than two dozen fires covering
several thousand acres of dry timber and brush in central and
western Colorado. A 1,760-acre fire believed to be arson destroyed
at least 49 homes and other structures in Boulder Canyon west of
Denver and forced the evacuation of more than 200 people near
Sugarloaf Mountain.
   _Idaho: Eight smokejumpers and two 20-member ground crews battled
a 150-acre fire in the Payette National Forest.
   _Nebraska: A fire near Crawford burned 50,000 acres of pine and
brush in an area 22 miles long by 8 miles wide. It threatened to
burn westward into a rugged, remote area where firefighting would be
more difficult.
   _New Mexico: A fire that has charred 10,025 acres since it
started June 30 in the Gila National Forest was about 95 percent
contained.
   _Oregon: Crews completed fire breaks Monday around three fires
that burned more than 2,000 acres of pine and fir on the Malheur and
Fremont national forests.
   _Texas: A lightning-sparked fire that started Saturday in the
center of Big Bend National Park was 95 percent contained after
charring about 150 acres.
   _Utah: Crews were close to containing a 15,500-acre fire despite
rough, remote terrain near the Colorado line. Near Roosevelt,
firefighters were unable to contain a week-old, 4,800-acre fire in
the Ashley National Forest.
   _Wyoming: Light rain late Sunday helped cool off a 3,447-acre
fire in the Bridger-Teton National Forest, in western Wyoming, and
firefighters said they were close to completing a containment line
around it.
