<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     07-10 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Release 3 Mayors, Say They Will Spare Norwegian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas on Monday freed three
kidnapped mayors of northwestern towns and reportedly promised to
spare a Norwegian anthropologist who they earlier said would be shot.
   A helicopter pilot abducted in October also was released,
according to a source.
   Mayors Jesus Vasquez of Cocorna, Nevardo Ramirez of San Carlos
and Francisco Javier Castano of San Francisco were released Monday
morning in their northwestern state of Antioquia, said a news
release by the Cocorna City Hall.
   The mayors were kidnapped on Friday by the National Liberation
Army guerrilla movement, which has abducted 53 people this year,
including mayors, reporters and coal and oil industry workers.
   The Concorna statement said the three had been released so they
could deliver a message to Antioquia state about the government's
oil policies.
   Guerrillas want Colombia to nationalize foreign oil operations in
the country.
   The guerrilla group kidnapped the Norwegian anthropologist, Bruce
Olson, in October while he was working with tribes in eastern
Colombia, along the border with Venezuela.
   The guerrillas said last week in a statement sent to newspapers
and radio stations that Olson had been tried and found guilty of
exploiting Indians.
   The respected Bogota daily El Tiempo said Monday the guerrillas
also had accused Olson of killing hundreds of Indians. The newspaper
did not give a source for its report.
   The Spanish news agency EFE said it had talked with the
second-in-command of the National Liberation Army, Nicolas
Rodriguez, in a remote part of the northwest state of Antioquia.
   Rodriguez promised that Olson would be turned over to the
International Red Cross as soon as details could be worked out, EFE
said.
   The guerrillas said they would release Olson because of the many
requests to spare his life, EFE said.
   Olson's mother, in a statement from her home in San Diego,
Calif., appealed last week for the guerrillas to not kill her son.
El Tiempo published the appeal.
   Indian leaders, representatives of the Roman Catholic Church and
government spokesmen have asked the guerrillas not to kill Olson.
   A helicopter pilot who had been flying for foreign oil companies
also was released Monday, a source with a foreign oil company told
The Associated Press. The source identified the pilot as Cornelio
Gonzalez.
   The National Liberation Army has bombed the country's main oil
pipeline 24 times this year, resulting in hundreds of thousands of
gallons of oil being spilled and the loss of millions of dollars of
export revenue.
   The minister of mines and energy, Oscar Mejia, has rejected all
suggestions of negotiation with the rebels and has said the army
should deal with the rebels.
   Representatives of oil companies met in the town of Tibu along
the Venezuelan border over the weekend and issued a statement asking
the guerrillas to stop attacks on the oil industry while attempts
are made to arrange negotiations.
   Sen. Felix Salcedo, who attended the meeting, told a news
conference Monday in Bogota that the guerrillas said they would
consider the request.
</TEXT>
