<FIRST>r i AM-SultanBurglarized     07-10 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sultan Burglarized,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burglars Loot London Home of Sultan's Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burglars stole $6.5 million worth of jewelry and
cash from the London home of Prince Jefri Bolkiah, whose brother is
a sultan considered to be the world's richest man, police said
Monday.
   The intruders entered through a first-floor window of the red
brick house in the north London district of East Finchley late in
the afternoon Thursday or in the evening, said Detective
Superintendent David Staff of Scotland Yard.
   Police said details were being kept confidential at the sultan's
request.
   Prince Jefri is the youngest brother of the 42-year-old sultan of
Brunei, who has 37 words in his name and title but is generally
called Sir Hassanal Bolkiah. The sultan is worth an estimated $30
billion and is listed in the Guinness Book of World Records as the
world's richest man.
   Staff, the detective superintendent, said the prince's wife,
Princess Norhayti, was not at home when the robbery occurred.
   ``No physical violence'' was involved, he said, and the thieves
had ``no contact'' with any of the household staff or security
guards. He would not elaborate. He also would not say whether the
house had been ransacked or if selected items were taken.
   Fred McColl, the family's lawyer, said additional security
measures had been taken but he would not give details. Asked whether
former employees were being questioned, he replied: ``We are
questioning a number of people.''
   Newspaper reports said the gang must have had intimate knowledge
of the complex security systems and alarms in the house.
   Brunei, on the northwest coast of Borneo, is rich in oil and
natural gas and the revenues go to the sultan, who also is prime
minister and defense minister. It is a former British protectorate
and became fully independent on Dec. 31, 1983.
   Britain's record robbery was of an estimated $48 million from a
safe deposit center in London's Knightsbridge district in 1987. The
center's owner, Parvez Latiff, and three other men were convicted of
the crime last January.
</TEXT>
