<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     07-10 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Moves 20 Armored Personnel Carriers Near Noriega Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT AMADOR, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. forces said Monday they deployed
armored cars and helicopter gunships at a base near one of Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega's offices to bolster security after a bullet
hit a U.S. colonel's home. Sunday's show of force came a day after a
bullet smashed through a second-story window at the home of Col.
Jorge Torres, penetrated a wooden door and dropped to the floor less
than one foot from his son's bed, the U.S. Southern Command said in
a statement.
   No one was injured, but Torres and his wife were ``shaken up,''
the statement said.
   It said the bullet was fired from a Soviet-made AK-47 rifle and
came from the vicinity of Chorillo, a Panama City neighborhood
across a belt of water from the Fort Amador compound.
   ``U.S. authorities have verbally protested the incident because
of its obvious threat to the safety of the U.S. families and
children who are residing at Fort Amador. The incident is being
investigated,'' the statement said.
   ``The exercise (Sunday) was intended to test U.S. responsiveness
as well as reassure the families at Amador of our ability to protect
them,'' it said.
   Panamanian defense force spokesmen refused immediate comment on
the incident.
   Panama's defense forces have their headquarters in Chorillo, but
Noriega also maintains an office at Fort Amador, a facility the
countries share under the 1977 Panama Canal treaties.
   Noriega commands Panama's defense forces and is the country's de
facto leader.
   The Southern Command statement said helicopter gunships and
armored personnel carriers of the 5th Infantry Division were
deployed at Fort Amador for several hours Sunday. President Bush
sent in 5th Division units in May after the Noriega-controlled
government annulled elections the opposition appeared to be winning.
   Saturday's incident was the latest in a series that has
contributed to growing tensions between U.S. and Noriega forces.
   Pro-Noriega demonstrators blocked the entrance to a U.S.
installation for half an hour last week, and a U.S. general said
Friday he thought Washington should impose a military solution to
remove Noriega.
   Noriega's office at Fort Amador overlooks a U.S. naval station
and is across the street from a supply and intelligence
headquarters. He must pass U.S. military police posts to get to the
building.
   The Panamanians also use the fort as a training area and
headquarters for several units. Gen. Omar Torrijos, who became a
national hero when he signed the treaties returning the Panama Canal
to Panamanian control at the end of 1999, is buried on the grounds.
   Washington has imposed economic sanctions on the Panamanian
government in an effort to remove Noriega since he was indicted on
drug trafficking charges in Florida.
   Noriega says the charges are trumped up and part of a U.S. plot
to renege on the canal treaties.
</TEXT>
