<HEAD>Botha-Mandela Meeting Welcomed by U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday welcomed last
week's meeting between South African President P.W. Botha and
imprisoned black nationalist Nelson Mandela.
   The department urged the South African government to free Mandela
and take other steps to create a climate for peaceful negotiation of
the country's problems.
   Department spokesman Richard Boucher termed the Botha-Mandela
meeting ``symbolic recognition by the South African government of
the important role Nelson Mandela and other black leaders will have
to play in the search for a peacefully negotiated solution to South
Africa's problems.
   ``We hope the South African government will take steps to create
a climate in which such negotiations can take place,'' Boucher added
to reporters.
   ``These would include release of Mandela and all political
prisoners, the lifting of the bans on political organizations and
the lifting of restrictions on other political leaders.''
</TEXT>
