<FIRST>r w AM-AppleBailout     07-10 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apple Bailout,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says Apples Donated May Have Alar Traces, But Will Be Safe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apples to be donated to charity in a $15
million bailout of growers may contain traces of Alar but will
nonetheless be safe to eat, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   ``We are simply not going to be poisoning people,'' said Arthur
Whitmore, a department spokesman. ``They may or may not have Alar in
them, but our position is that these apples are safe. There is no
reason not to eat apples.''
   The department announced Friday it would spend up to $15 million
in an effort to help reduce a huge surplus of apples created when
consumers stopped buying amid fears over the use of Alar.
   As originally envisioned, the department would have purchased the
apples outright and then donated them to schools, prisons, public
assistance food programs and others.
   The department now plans to have the growers donate the apples to
various groups and then be reimbursed by the department.
   ``We would never formally take possession of the apples,'' said
Whitmore, adding that such programs are designed to ``correct market
distortions involving surplus quantities of commodity.''
   The industry has estimated that 5 million to 7 million boxes of
apples from last year's crop, valued at between $40 million and $56
million, remain unsold with this year's harvest only weeks away.
   The department said that prices had fallen $3 to $4 per carton
from what they were a year ago and the nation's 20,000 apple growers
have estimated total losses at well over $100 million.
   Alar is used to enchance apple color, ease of harvesting and life
in storage.
   The Alar controversy began in late February when a private
environmental advocacy group, the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said eating apples treated with the chemical substantially increases
the risk of cancer in children.
   The Environmental Protection Agency and the Food and Drug
Administration disputed the environmental group's report as a major
exaggeration of the risk, but sales fell immediately.
   Even though EPA criticized the study, the agency plans to ban the
use of Alar next spring and in the interim has proposed slashing the
allowable limit on crops from 20 parts per million to one part per
million.
   The only manufacturer has withdrawn Alar from the U.S. market.
   Paul Allen, a spokesman for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, said Monday that his group was ``not endorsing, nor
opposing'' the Agriculture Department's bailout.
   ``An individual bite of an apple or a sip of apple juice that may
have a trace of Alar is not a great cause for alarm,'' said Allen.
``The public health threat from Alar involves prolonged exposure.''
   Republican Rep. Sid Morrison, an apple grower whose central
Washington state district produces roughly half of the nation's
apples, said Monday that even though many of the apples that will be
donated through the USDA program may have traces of the Alar the
levels will be within even the EPA's new proposed limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1853EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe     07-10 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four From Washington HUD Office Reassigned Pending Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four employees at the Washington field office
of the Department of Housing and Urban Development were reassigned
Monday to the agency's headquarters pending investigations of their
roles in mismanagement officials believe cost the government $10
million.
   The four, including the former head of the field office, had been
placed on 30-day administrative leave at the outset of the
investigation last month but that period expired Monday. HUD
officials exercised their option to place the four on 90-day
temporary assignments.
   They will be assigned, beginning Tuesday, to non-management
positions in four separate offices within HUD headquarters, said HUD
spokesman Robert Nipp. They were notified of the move Monday in
letters from Edwin Gardner, HUD's deputy undersecretary for field
coordination.
   ``The investigation continues,'' Nipp said.
   An audit of the Washington field office uncovered lax financial
and management controls that allowed private closing agents HUD
contracts to handle the sale and acquisitions of single-family
property to delay payments to the government and in some cases not
make required payments.
   Audits of closing agents nationwide found similar problems in
many states, and those audits now are part of a congressional
investigation into allegations of influence-peddling, mismanagement
and other problems at HUD during the Reagan administration.
   Secretary Jack Kemp, scheduled to appear before Congress on
Tuesday, said Monday that the agency's problems would not be used as
an excuse to curtail housing programs designed to help low- and
moderate-income Americans.
   ``We're not going to allow it to be a reason to close down the
programs of HUD,'' Kemp said in a brief reference to the scandal in
a speech he made in Detroit to the convention of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   The four Washington workers reassigned to headquarters were I.
Margaret White, who had headed the District field office for five
years; Robert B. Warner, its director of housing management; Charles
W. Womble, a single-family home loan specialist; and Everett
Rothschild, head of property disposition.
   The field office oversees HUD properties in the District of
Columbia and parts of Maryland and Virginia.
   Among the private closing agents in the region under scrutiny is
Marilyn Harrell, the so-called ``Robin HUD'' who has said she took
$5.5 million that belonged to HUD and donated most of it to programs
to help the poor.
   About a dozen closing agents nationwide may have cost the
government more than $20 million by withholding money owed the
department or sending it in late, costing the government interest,
officials believe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
