<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0660 07-10 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0660,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Crisis Touched Off by Labor Threat to Bolt Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to inlcude Peres statement; picks up 5th
pvs `Labor legislators' and INSERTS 1 graf after 18th, `Peres, the' with
Mubarak comment</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's government was thrown into crisis
Monday when senior leaders of the left-leaning Labor Party voted to
recommend leaving the coalition Cabinet, a move that could force
national elections.
   Labor's Leadership Bureau adopted a proposal, which now goes to
the party's decision-making Central Committee, that accused Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir of derailing efforts to end the Palestinian
uprising with tough, new conditions set by his Likud bloc, Labor's
coalition partner.
   ``There is no room under these circumstances for the continuation
of the government,'' said Finance Minister Shimon Peres, the Labor
chairman, as he recommended pulling out of the Cabinet.
   His colleagues applauded loudly and passed his proposal 45-2,
with six abstentions.
   Later, Peres predicted elections in a few months.
   ``I assume that the central (committee) ... will discuss when we
want elections,'' he told the national science institute. ``When two
parties come to a situation of disagreement and breaking apart ...
they go for new elections.''
   Labor legislators underscored their anger by walking out of
Parliament Monday when it voted on five left-wing motions of no
confidence.
   The government easily overturned the motions by a vote of 41-12
votes with five abstentions.
   It is the most serious crisis since the government was formed in
December after weeks of negotiations with small religious parties.
The Tel Aviv stock market dropped 4 percent at the news.
   But Labor leaders gave themselves room to maneuver, hinting they
might not withdraw if real progress was made to arrange peace
negotiations with Palestinians before next month's meeting of their
1,350-member Central Committee.
   Shamir, in a placatory effort, said he will call for a vote at
Sunday's Cabinet meeting to reaffirm support for the government
peace initiative, Israel television reported.
   Labor and Likud, which have ruled jointly since 1984 elections
ended in virtual deadlock, have survived several ideological crises.
   Some Labor leaders said a final decision could hinge on next
week's visit by three U.S. State Department officials and whether
they will make any progress toward starting an Israeli peace
dialogue with Palestinians.
   Israeli reports said Secretary of State James A. Baker III had
asked Labor leaders through Ambassador William Brown to refrain from
leaving the government, fearing this would mire U.S. efforts.
   Labor's decision sparked anger in Likud. Shamir called Labor's
vote ``a mistaken decision'' and said dissolving the Cabinet will
leave ``no choice than to hold early elections which are not needed
by the country at this moment.''
   ``The prime minister's bureau stresses and reiterates that the
government peace plan is still alive,'' a communique from his office
said.
   The statement also accused Labor of ``playing into the hands of
the Arabs ... and relieving the Arabs of any need to respond to the
peace initiative.'' The Palestine Liberation Organization so far has
rejected the plan.
   Shamir has said he agrees with conditions adopted by his party
July 5, but that the tough stances are not binding on the peace
iniative, which calls for elections among Palestinians in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Those elected are to negotiate with Israel for autonomy, with
later talks deciding the territories' final status.
   Peres, the government vice premier, argued in a fiery speech that
Likud's stance torpedoed the peace plan. Labor's No. 2 man, Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, said the plan had been ``castrated.''
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, the only Arab country that has
signed a peace agreement with Israel, said in Cairo the tough new
conditions could undermine Shamir's entire peace proposal.
   Peres especially criticized Likud's demand that proposed
elections be postponed until the uprising is ended. At least 555
Palestinians and 35 Israelis have died in the 19-month revolt.
   ``What does that mean? Granting veto power to all the extremists
in the territories. We shouldn't block negotiations just because the
terrorists don't want them,'' Peres shouted.
   He also objected to Likud's demand to continue building Jewish
settlements in the occupied territories and its rejection of the
U.S.-backed formula of trading ``territory for peace.''
   The three-hour meeting ended with Labor's Central Committee
recommending: ``That following the decisions of the Likud Central
Committee that harmed the changes of the government's peace
initiative, there is no room ... for the continuation of the
government.''
   More than 60 leaders in the 120-member bureau stayed away from
the vote, but Peres expressed confidence the Central Committee would
vote to pull out unless steps are taken to rescue the peace plan.
   If Labor's 11 ministers quit the 26-member Cabinet, Shamir could
technically form a narrow government with religious and right-wing
factions. But he said he expected new elections.
   According to opinion polls, Likud stands a good chance of
repeating its victory over Labor in the last elections in November
1988, when it got 40 seats to Labor's 39 in the 120-member
Parliament.
</TEXT>
