<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Trinder     07-10 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Trinder,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Comedian Tommy Trinder Dies At Age 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Tommy Trinder, whose nimble, irreverent
wit endeared him to generations of Britons, died Monday at age 80.
   His death was announced by the show business charity
organization, The Water Rats, which he led in 1955, 1963 and 1965.
   It said Trinder died at St. Peter's Hospital in Chertsey, just
west of London, after a long illness. The nature of the illness was
not disclosed.
   Thomas Edward Trinder was born March 24, 1909, the son of a
London streetcar driver. He made his London debut at age 13 at the
old Collins Music Hall.
   By 17, he was principal comic in touring revues put on by Archie
Pitt, to whom comedian Gracie Fields was once married.
   Trinder became a favorite at London clubs, theaters and dance
halls, and in 1938 made the first of many appearances at the
Palladium. During World War II he entertained British soldiers all
over the world, and later toured the United States.
   He appeared on the popular TV program ``In Town Tonight'' and the
long-running British Broadcasting Corp. radio panel game ``Does The
Team Think?'' and was host of Independent Television's ``Sunday
Night at the London Palladium.''
   Trinder's movie credits included ``The Foreman Went to France''
in 1942 and ``Fiddlers Three'' in 1944.
   Queen Elizabeth II made Trinder a commander in the Order of the
British Empire in 1975.
</TEXT>
