<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Elections     07-10 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Elections,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Wins Tijuana Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservative National Action Party won the
recent Tijuana mayoral election, strengthening the opposition's hold
in Baja California state, according to official results announced
Monday.
   The victory by Carlos Montejo Fabela confirmed the heavy losses
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party suffered in the
state in the July 2 elections. At that time the party, known as the
PRI, lost its first gubernatorial race in its 60-year history to
National Action.
   The PRI confirmed it lost the race in Tijuana, across the
U.S.-Mexico border from San Diego, according to Notimex, the
government news agency.
   Partial results announced by the state electoral commission also
showed that National Action won in all six Tijuana legislative
districts.
   Montejo Fabela said National Action lost the mayoral race in
Mexicali and Tecate. The party has claimed victory in Ensenada.
   The PRI has never lost a presidential election; it suffered its
first Senate losses in elections a year ago.
   Partial results in western Michoacan state _ where the PRI lost
ground in last year's vote _ showed the PRI won six of 18
legislative seats and the leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party won
two, the Excelsior news service said.
   The PRI on Monday tried to play down its losses.
   The party's secretary-general, Rafael Rodriguez Barrera, said its
losses in Baja California ``do not have an important significance
for the PRI,'' Notimex reported.
   ``What is important is the capacity for recuperation to
compensate for the defeats and this has been done on several
occasions,'' Rodriguez Barrera said.
   The PRI in recent years has increasingly maintained its hold by
vote fraud.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who has struck several
dramatic blows against fraud and corruption since taking office Dec.
1, had promised clean elections.
   The opposition, however, has accused the PRI of fraud in the
latest elections.
</TEXT>
