<FIRST>u a AM-Puppeteers     07-10 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puppeteers,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Puppeteers Gather For Annual Festival To Share Their Handy Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 700 puppeteers gathered Monday to
show off their handy work in an effort to give new life to the
inanimate objects.
   ``Puppetry is an ancient art and it's been around probably as
long as we have,'' Diane Rains said as she smoothed the brown yarn
hair of Punch, the 2-foot, plastic-headed star of her puppet
company, Freshwater Pearls.
   ``We're all here to try to keep it going,'' said Ms. Rains, 34, a
former zookeeper who abandoned work on a doctorate in veterinary
physiology for the more creative rewards of puppeteering.
   The 49th annual Puppeteers of America National Festival, held on
the campus of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, covers just
about anything a puppeteer would want to know. The Puppeteers of
America, based in Pasadena, Calif., has just 2,000 members.
   In workshops and performances, puppeteers demonstrate their
techniques and learn the history of puppetry. The convention, which
runs through Saturday, also has a room filled with puppets,
marionette kits, videos of puppet shows, puppet wigs and even puppet
postcards and puppet coloring books.
   Part conference and part theatrical marathon with daily puppet
shows, the festival is also a social occasion bringing puppeteers
together from across the country.
   ``It's a very isolated profession,'' said Ms. Rains, who with her
husband, Stu Janis, put on a 19th century version of ``Punch and
Judy'' in schools, shopping malls and art fairs around Minneapolis
and St. Paul, Minn., near their Maplewood home.
   ``Puppeteers are usually very driven, creative people,'' said
Nancy Laverick, director of the festival. ``You've brought life to
something, then emotion.''
   Unlike Asia and Europe, where for centuries puppetry has
enlivened religious practices while entertaining and educating, the
United States remains largely an empty stage when it comes to
puppets.
   Yes, there was Kukla, Fran and Ollie, and any puppeteer will
credit Jim Henson and his Muppets with giving puppetry a boost.
   But there are only about two dozen full-time puppet troupes akin
to the puppet theaters of Europe and Asia, according to Janet
Bradley, 46, of Tears of Joy Theatre in Vancouver, Wash.
   Her shows, based on folk stories and myths, are performed largely
for schoolchildren.
   ``For me, these stories speak to us, about life and death, not
wanting to grow up and about growing old. I want to bring it to
life,'' she said. ``This is real and alive and happening. That's the
essence of good theater.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0160 </DOCNO>
