<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-10 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wind, Hail in the East, Hot and Humid in the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Damaging winds and large hail hit New York, Vermont and
Massachusetts on Monday, and showers and thunderstorms drenched
parts of the South and the Rocky Mountains.
   Thunderstorm winds downed trees in Schenectady, N.Y., Montpelier,
Vt., and Williamstown, Mass., and toppled power lines in Albany, N.Y.
   Winds gusted near 60 mph in Middleburg, N.Y., and Northfield,
Mass. In West Boylston, Mass., officials said they received reports
of a tornado after high winds swept through the area, knocking out
power and telephones, felling trees and damaging homes. Main roads
into the town were blocked, officials said.
   No injuries were reported.
   Ping pong ball-size hail pounded Stephentown, N.Y., and
golfball-size hail fell in Montpelier.
   Showers and thunderstorms were also scattered across parts of the
Tennessee and lower Mississippi valleys, the western Gulf Coast and
the Rockies.
   Hot, humid weather prevailed south of a cold front from the
central and southern Plains to the south Atlantic Coast. Readings
were in the upper 80s and 90s throughout much of the area.
   Temperatures climbed above 95 degrees in much of northern
Illinois, parts of northeast Kansas, northeast Iowa and southeastern
North Carolina.
   The weather was cooler and less humid to the north of the front.
Early afternoon temperatures were in the 70s and 80s from the upper
Great Lakes to the northern Plains. Milwaukee, Wis., dropped from 90
degrees to 77 degrees in just 13 minutes as the cold front moved
through the area.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees in Arcata, Calif., and Bremerton, Wash., to 101 degrees in
Needles, Calif.
   The nation's low was 29 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   Tuesday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in the northern Plains, the upper Mississippi and Ohio valleys, the
mid-Atlantic coast and northern Maine; widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms along the south Atlantic coast, the Tennessee and
lower Mississippi valleys and the Texas coast; and isolated showers
and thunderstorms over Utah and Arizona.
   High temperatures in the 90s were predicted for much of the
nation; the 70s and 80s for northern New England, the Great Lakes,
the northern Plains, parts of the northern Rockies, the Pacific
Northwest and coastal sections of California; and between 100 and
110 degrees in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
