<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Walesa 1stLd-Writethru a0603 07-10 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Walesa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Visit Another Step in Walesa Switch from Shipyard to Statecraft</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs to include comments on Gorbachev;
picks up 6th graf pvs, Walesa and...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa has gone from
fixing electric carts at the Lenin Shipyard to leading the strongest
opposition movement in the history of the Soviet bloc.
   On Tuesday, the Walesas, Lech and Danuta, are having special
guests for lunch at the house they moved into just last year:
President Bush and his wife Barbara.
   Walesa repaired his last shipyard cart early this year before
entering talks with communist authorities that led to the
legalization of Solidarity in April after a seven-year ban and its
landslide win in last month's elections.
   Now the 45-year-old Walesa works in an office at the newly opened
Solidarity national headquarters.
   ``I am fond of him,'' Walesa said Monday of Bush. ``He is a
high-class politician, a great intellect, quite straightforward, a
fantastic president.''
   The union leader also expressed his admiration for Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, describing him as a ``fantastic juggler.''
   ``I admire Mr. Gorbachev,'' Walesa said on NBC news. ``He is
truly a great juggler of great class, it's such a gigantic country
with such problems. He has to be a great juggler to make it.''
   Walesa and Bush met during the then-vice president's trip to
Poland in 1987, when they conferred at the U.S. Ambassador's
residence in Warsaw and together visited the grave of murdered
pro-Solidarity priest the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko.
   The Solidarity chief and 1983 Nobel Peace Prize laureate has
begun to assume the trappings of the globe-trotting statesman and
political leader he is. He occasionally refers to himself as ``we.''
   But the father of eight retains a knack for the common touch.
   That touch will be much in evidence when the Bushes arrive for
lunch at 54 Polanki Street in Gdansk, not far from the crowded
high-rise apartment block where the Walesa family used to live.
   The meal will be a private affair between the Bushes and the
Walesas; the only other person in attendance will be an interpreter
who will be working, not eating.
   Like any other guest, the Bushes will enter the Walesa house
through the back door, walking through the kitchen on the way to the
dining room.
   Walesa is proud of the house he purchased and renovated last year
with earnings from his autobiography, ``A Way of Hope.''
   A stuccoed brick single-family house that would raise no eyebrows
in the United States or Western Europe, it is a dwelling that many
Poles would regard as a palace compared to their typically cramped
apartments.
   It has a garden and small orchard where Walesa will take Bush for
a stroll, and space enough for a home office filled with mementoes.
   Walesa also has a satellite dish to pull in foreign television
broadcasts on his color television.
   The dining room is decorated with paintings of nature scenes and
religious themes. In the living room hangs a portrait of Polish-born
Pope John Paul II. ``My highest authority,'' Walesa calls him.
   When Walesa was traveling the country last fall meeting workers
in the aftermath of a wave of strikes, he sometimes had to explain
the house to followers who feared he was putting on airs.
   ``Look, I wrote a book,'' he would answer. ``I have eight kids.''
The explanation usually sufficed.
   After lunch, Bush will visit the workers' monument outside the
Lenin shipyard, where Solidarity was born in August 1980.
   Danuta Walesa, 39, has put her friend Grazyna Pusz in charge of
cooking for the Bushes. Mrs. Pusz's husband Krzysztof is Walesa's
longtime assistant.
   The menu includes simple and wholesome Polish dishes, in an array
that should make the Walesas' table groan.
   Appetizers will include smoked salmon and smoked eel, the latter
a Gdansk specialty, and a tray of Polish cold cuts.
   ``Chlodnik,'' a cold summertime soup made from beets and sour
cream, and mushroom soup will be next, with the main course to
include turkey, veal, pork with mushrooms, beef and new potatoes.
   Dessert will be a jelly made from wild strawberries, chocolate
cake and a strawberry pie.
   Mrs. Walesa said she planned to ``just be sitting, doing nothing
and enjoying being the guest. ... I trust my friend.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
