<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-BushRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0690 07-10 1181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0690,1200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Praise for Reforms and a Modest Aid Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf pvs to include Jaruzelski comments,
picks up 11th graf pvs, Earlier, Bush...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a day of high symbolism
and support for Poland's strides toward democracy, offered on Monday
a modest economic aid package intended to help ``redeem the promise
of a free Polish republic.''
   A key element is a $100 million U.S. fund _ provided Congress
approves _ to support the Polish private sector as the Soviet bloc
country moves away from its Marxist economy.
   But the dimensions of the U.S. offer could fall short of Lech
Walesa's aspirations. The leader of the Solidarity trade union
movement is expected to ask Bush on Tuesday when they meet in Gdansk
to back a $10 billion program of international help for Poland.
   Even so, a clearly exhilirated Bush assured the Polish
parliament, where Solidarity holds 260 of 560 seats, that ``the
Western democracies will stand with the Polish people, and other
peoples of this region.''
   Although interrupted by applause five times and given a standing
ovation at the end of his speech, Bush encountered little more than
a correct response from the parliament and a tepid reception on the
streets of Warsaw.
   The 4,000 or so people that watched Bush's 12-car motorcade drive
through the streets of this sweltering city waved small paper
American flags listlessly. Occassionally, there were shouts of
``Long life. Long life.''
   The president wound up his busy day as guest at a state dinner
hosted by the Communist Party leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
Striking much the same tone as in his speech to parliament, Bush
said in a toast that Poland was entering a new era and was
``beginning, once again, to command its own destiny.''
   For his part, Jaruzelski said in his toast that the Polish
government does not want to ``return to old resentments and
emotions'' in its relations with the United States, but hopes to
``look into the future, to construct a sort of `bridge' across the
Atlantic.''
   As the president's motorcade arrived at Radziwill Palace for the
dinner, demonstrators among 1,000 people outside could be heard
shouting ``down with Communism'' and ``Jaruzelski must go.''
   There was no indication whether Bush could hear the protests,
which appeared to have been staged by splinter opposition groups.
   Jaruzelski, in an interview with ABC news, praised his meeting
with Bush, saying: ``It was a very rich day, rich in substance, rich
in political facts.''
   He also said he consulted with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev,
and added: ``I really am heartened that the leaders of the two big
powers are guided by the same intentions and I feel that this bodes
well for the future.''
   Earlier, Bush squeezed in a short pitching session with Polish
Little Leaguers.
   Handing his dark suit jacket to his wife, Barbara, the president
put an orange fielder's glove on his right hand and powered a
baseball to a 12-year-old Polish pitching star on the back lawn of
U.S. Ambassador John Davis's residence.
   ``Make sure, he doesn't throw it wild, and wipe my wife out,''
Bush, the captain of the 1948 Yale University baseball team, told
his security guard as Adam Szczepanski returned the president's
offering with equal force.
   The well-attended session was designed to support the development
of America's national pastime in this European country.
   As for the offer of financial assistance, Bush:
   _Pledged to ask Congress for a $100 million ``enterprise fund''
to support Polish entrepreneurs. Moreover, he said he will ask other
industrialized democracies to undertake similar initiatives at this
weekend's western economic summit meeting in Paris.
   _Said he would also ask Congress to approve $15 million to fight
air and water pollution in Krakow, once the royal capital.
   _Promised to open a U.S. educational and cultural center in
Warsaw. Poland, he added, should do the same in the United States.
   _Told the parliament he would ask his six summit partners to
quickly support rescheduling of up to $5 billion of Poland's
staggering international debt of $39 billion.
   _Said he would encourage the World Bank to proceed with $325
million in loans to help Polish agriculture and industry ``reach the
production levels that they are clearly capable of.''
   But Bush stressed that the aid would come with a string attached
_ that Poland would have to adopt austerity measures.
   ``There can be no substitute for Poland's own efforts,'' he said,
telling the parliament, ``I must speak honestly _ economic reform
and recovery cannot occur without sacrifices.''
   Bush told the parliament that Poland must choose either a free
market economy or socialism. ``Your responsibility for your
country's future is immense,'' he said.
   Jaruzelski, acknowledged as much in introducing Bush to
parliament.
   ``We are fully aware that the biggest work is up to us ourselves.
... But we do not want to be alone,'' the general said.
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski told Bush the speech
``contained many thoughts permeated with realism.'' Foreign Minister
Tadeusz Olechowski said his nation was not looking for ``a rain of
gold''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III told a news conference the
primary objective of the U.S. aid package is to lower Polish
inflation from its current 100 percent and to ease government
subsidies for heavy industry.
   Baker said that Bush, in devising his package, ``recognizes there
will be some trying times ahead'' for Poland in meeting U.S. and
international standards.
   Bush himself cautioned parliament that the United States would
not provide ``unsound credits made without regard to the necessary
reforms.''
   Two years ago, the parliament withheld its support from an
austerity program that would have meant increases of 100 percent or
more in rents and food prices.
   Addressing the parliament, Bush also sought to inspire Polish
reformers.
   He said that, now, ``this generation's calling is to redeem the
promise of a free Polish republic. Poland has not been lost so long
as the Polish spirit lives.''
   Earlier, in a speech at a luncheon with Jaruzelski, who is
playing a pivotal role in restructuring the Polish economic and
political systems, Bush called on both the party and Solidarity ``to
rise above the mistrust'' and work together to meet common
challenges.
   ``The United States will stand with Poland,'' Bush declared. ``We
will support Poland's hopeful mission, unparalleled in your
history.''
   Bush also paid his respects at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier,
then visited the site of the Warsaw Ghetto, bowing his head in
tribute to the once-vibrant Jewish community that was annihilated
after standing virtually alone against the World War II Nazi
occupation.
   A rabbi, in the black kaftan of the Hasidic movement, quietly
said a prayer as tears streamed down the cheeks of a handful of the
remnants of Polish jewry.
   Bush's visit to Poland is the first stop on a 10-day trip to
Europe that includes the first-ever visit by an American president
to Hungary. He also will travel to Paris for a seven-nation economic
summit and stop briefly in the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
