<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Rushdie'sWife     07-10 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Rushdie's Wife,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie's Novelist Wife Says She's Living Like `Paranoid Schizophrenic'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. author Marianne Wiggins says she lives ``the
life of a paranoid schizophrenic'' since the late Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini called on Moslems to kill her novelist husband Salman
Rushdie, according to a report published Monday.
   ``Suddenly, I have been removed from the world and made into this
person alienatd in the extreme,'' she was quoted as saying in an
interview in the August issue of Options, a monthly woman's magazine.
   Ms. Wiggins and Rushdie have been in hiding under police guard
since Khomeini issued the death call on Feb. 14. The leader of
Iran's Islamic revolution said Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic
Verses'' blasphemes the religion.
   Anne Cabron wrote that she interviewed Ms. Wiggins by telephone
and did not ask where she was.
   ``The thing about this situation is that one is completely of
good mental health and yet living the life of a paranoid
schizophrenic,'' Ms. Wiggins, a native of Lancaster, Pa., was quoted
as saying.
   ``One is always alarmed at strangers,'' she said. ``What has
become impossible is the flow of society. You can no longer pass
down the street and encounter a stranger. You lose all sense of
spontaneity because you live in fear. Fear is an element that used
to be on the far side of the earth.''
   Her latest novel, ``John Dollar,'' was published the day before
Khomeini's death call.
   Ms. Wiggins, 41, who married Rushdie in January 1988, said she
and her husband are keeping diaries and keeping in contact with
their families.
</TEXT>
