<FIRST>r w AM-GeologyAgreement     07-10 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Geology Agreement,307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Arrive With Gifts, But Americans Have None</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Soviet scientists arrived Monday to
formally exchange copies of a scientific agreement with U.S.
scientists, they came bearing gifts.
   The Americans had none and had to scramble to find something to
present their guests.
   Two Soviet geologists attending the 28th International Geological
Congress met Monday at a news conference with Dallas Peck, director
of the U.S. Geological Survey, to initiate formally an agreement to
share geological research.
   The first Soviet speaker, Yeveny A. Kozlovsky, former president
of the USSR ministry of geology, presented Peck with a highly
polished purple stone sphere sitting within a half sphere of
polished green stone. Both stones gleamed with a gemlike quality and
Kozlovsky said they represented the Earth and its core.
   Peck responded with a group of maps, identical to those being
handed out routinely next door in the press room.
   The second Soviet speaker, M.D. Pelmenev, deputy minister of
geology, presented Peck with a cut and polished stone on which a
forest scene had been created using particles of colored gemstone.
   Peck was able to respond with a back copy of a U.S. geology
magazine that had been hastily gathered up by an aide.
   Obviously embarassed by the fact that the Americans had not
prepared for an exchange of gifts, Peck told the Soviets, ``We start
this off by our owing you one.''
   The agreement calls for American and Soviet geologists to
exchange the results of research conducted in their respective
countries. It eventually will lead to an exchange of field trips
that will involve the study of various geological formations in the
two countries. The two countries reached the agreement after two
years of negotiation and the ceremony Monday marked the formal
exchange of copies of the signed agreement.
</TEXT>
