<FIRST>r a AM-JetEngines     07-10 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jet Engines,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Says Jet Fighter Engines Returned To Hill Air Force Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILL AIR FORCE BASE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI returned three stolen
F-16 jet fighter engines to the Air Force on Monday after processing
them for evidence, an agent said.
   However, FBI Agent Tim Screen would neither confirm nor deny
reports the disappearance of the $2 million engines was part of a
19-month ``sting'' operation aimed at a purported theft ring at the
base.
   Asked if suspects had been identified or if arrests were
imminent, Screen said, ``We're working on that now. We're
investigating certain people.'' He declined to say whether the
people were on base.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said in Washington that Department of
Defense officials had told him a great number of other thefts had
been reported at Hill. He said many countries ``would love to get
hold of the engines'' to ``figure out our technology.''
   ``This looks like it will be a strong embarrassment for the state
of Utah,'' he said. ``It involves lots of dollars, that's all I can
say.''
   The Pratt &amp; Whitney F100-PW-200 engines were reported missing
last Wednesday by maintenance personnel returning from the
Independence Day holiday, base officials said. The engines are each
17 feet long, 34 inches in diameter, and weigh 3,200 pounds.
   The FBI turned the engines and a towing vehicle over to the Air
Force at 3:30 a.m. after checking them for evidence at a secret FBI
storage facility in Salt Lake City, about 30 miles to the south,
Screen said.
   Screen said further information was not available pending the
outcome of an investigation by the FBI, the Department of Defense
and the Air Force Office of Special Investigations.
   Hatch said the investigation was close to concluding, and that he
had been told the theft apparently was committed by Hill employees
or others familiar with base operations.
   ``They knew enough to cut locks on a gate, and replace them with
similar locks,'' the senator said, adding that the engines
apparently were taken from the base through a gate north of the
taxiway that is not patrolled often.
   Seventy-two F-16 fighters are assigned to the 388th Tactical
Fighter Wing, the base's main group, while 24 are used for the Air
Force Reserve 419th wing.
</TEXT>
