<SECOND>AM-Space-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0684,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Seeks Moon Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf: ``We believe,'' to identify Downs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, which next week celebrates
the 20th anniversary of man's first moon landing, should establish a
permanent moon settlement, the National Space Society said Monday.
   The group, a public membership organization dedicated to
strengthening the U.S. civilian space effort, made its request in a
letter to President Bush.
   ``We believe this lunar settlement is the most appropriate goal
for the United States after the Freedom Space Station is
established,'' wrote TV figure Hugh Downs, chairman of the society's
board of governors
   ``The technologies, utilization of the moon's resources and
experience derived from the lunar effort are cucial as a stepping
stone to further human expansion into the solar system, including
future expeditions to Mars and beyond.''
   Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin landed on the moon July 20, 1969.
They were the first of 12 Americans to do so.
