<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Executions     07-10 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Executions,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says 2,000 Detainees Executed Since Cease-Fire, Deputy
Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's main opposition group said Monday
it has sent the U.N. secretary-general a list of 2,023 political
prisoners allegedly executed in Iran since the cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war.
   The opposition also claimed that an Iranian legislator who
resigned last week has been detained by security police.
   Massoud Rajavi, leader of the Baghdad-based Mujahedeen Khalq, or
People's Holy Warriors, claimed those executed were tortured, and
that many political prisoners were being killed under the pretext of
a crackdown on drug traffickers.
   The Mujahedeen Khalq is based in Baghdad, Iraq. In a statement
sent by telex to The Associated Press in Nicosia, Rajavi said names
on the list sent to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
``formed only a fraction'' of politically inspired killings carried
out since a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire Aug. 20 halted eight years of
war between Iran and Iraq. His claims could not be confirmed
independently.
   The United Nations and international humanitarian agencies,
including London-based Amnesty International, earlier this year
accused Iran of executing several hundred political detainees.
   Rajavi said a new wave of executions and arrests followed the
June 3 death of Iran's spiritual leader, the Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   ``In the month that has elapsed since Khomeini's death, the
remnants of his regime ... have continued street executions on an
extensive scale to terrorize the people,'' the statement said.
   ``In many cities ... women have been hanged in public alongside
men and their bodies left hanging for several days to teach the
public a lesson,'' it said.
   In a separate statement, the Mujahedeen claimed legislator
Abdolmajid Sharpasand of the northern Iranian town of Kharadj, was
detained by the secret police along with several well-known town
clergymen. It gave no date for the arrest and it was not possible to
confirm the report independently.
   Iran's official media has said only that other legislators
demanded Sharpasand resign because of his ``indecent attitude.''
   The Mujahedeen statement claimed Sharpasand announced in
parliament on July 2 that he was resigning, citing ``grave anxiety
over the country's political future'' and the ``concentration of
power in a few hands.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
