<FIRST>r w AM-US-India 1stLd-Writethru   07-10 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-India, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0676,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Cooperation Sought Against Chemical Proliferation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last two grafs with three grafs embassy comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Monday it expects the
Indian government to cooperate in clamping strict controls on the
export of chemicals that can be used to make poison gas and other
chemical weapons.
   ``It is our hope that all countries, including India, which are
capable of manufacturing the precursors needed to produce these
deadly weapons will institute very strict controls on their
exports,'' department spokesman Richard Boucher told reporters.
   He was commenting on a New York Times report that the tightening
of controls on the export of substances useful in chemical weapons
by the United States, Japan and European nations has made Indian
companies major sources for shipments of such material to Iran, Iraq
and Egypt.
   The spread of chemical weapons is a global problem of concern
``and I think it's a mutual concern that we share with other
countries such as India,'' Boucher said.
   The United States is discussing with India and other countries
how to curb this spread, he said, adding, ``We're confident that the
government of India will be taking all measures to control this
trade.''
   Boucher did not name the other countries and said he could not
rank the importance of various countries as suppliers.
   He said he was unable to describe the Indian response to U.S.
concerns, ``except to say that we, for our part, are very hopeful
that we can work with the Indian government to control the flow of
these chemicals.''
   An Indian Embassy statement issued late Monday in Washington said
that ``India is not involved in the production or trading of
chemical weapons as a matter of policy,'' and is committed to their
total elimination.
   It added that only recently had there come to India's attention
the problem of ``dual-use items which have legitimate commercial
applications in the pesticide industry, etc. There is no
well-established international regime to take care of such
chemicals.''
   It said the United States appreciated India's facilitating the
return of a shipment of 257 tons of Indian-made thionyl chloride, an
essential of mustard gas that is widely traded for the manufacture
of pesticides, after its movement from India to Iran via Dubai was
halted by the West German trading company that reportedly brokered
the deal.
</TEXT>
