<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 2114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Aguilar     07-10 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aguilar,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Arraigned On Conspiracy, Racketeering Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S District Judge Robert Aguilar faced a
court for the first time as a criminal defendant Monday and pleaded
innocent to eight felony charges.
   Aguilar, 58, was indicted by a federal grand jury last month on
charges he used his office to do favors for convicted felons.
   Among other things, he is alleged to have sought favorable
treatment for two felons from other federal judges and tipped off an
ex-mobster about a court-ordered wiretap. In the process, the
indictment said, Aguilar turned his office into a ``racketeering
enterprise'' to obstruct justice.
   Aguilar, a 1980 appointee of President Carter, has not commented,
but his lawyers contend the case is politically motivated because of
Aguilar's liberal record and his rulings against the government in
several important cases.
   If convicted, Aguilar faces up to 55 years in prison. The
indictment is the fourth this decade against a federal judge and the
first racketerring charge ever against a federal judge.
   Monday's arraignment before visiting U.S. District Judge Howard
Bratton of Albuquerque, N.M., lasted less than 20 minutes, and
Aguilar stood with his lawyers before the bench for less than three
minutes.
   Dressed in a gray business suit, he repeated ``the plea is not
guilty'' to the first two charges read by the court clerk, before
Bratton said further reading of the charges was unnecessary.
   Allowed to go free without bail, Aguilar left through a rear exit
without talking to reporters.
   Aguilar, who can be removed from office only by congressional
impeachment, has retained his judge's title and $89,500 salary, but
relinquished most of his duties while the case is pending.
   Justice Department prosecutor Ralph Martin did not object to the
no-bail release, but asked Bratton to prohibit Aguilar from
contacting any potential witnesses. Martin noted that one charge
accuses the judge of advising a witness to lie to the grand jury.
Bratton refused the request.
   Defense lawyer Patrick Hallinan told reporters the request would
have barred Aguilar from speaking to ``half of his family'' and
described it as part of the government's campaign to portray Aguilar
as a corrupt judge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
