<FIRST>r a AM-PTLTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0693 07-10 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakker Secretary Says She Could Sign His Name to Checks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th, `The Taggarts...' to UPDATE with judge
in Charlotte denying change of venue for Bakker; picks up 7th graf pvs,
`Miss Fulbright...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker's former executive secretary
said Monday she had unlimited authority to sign the TV evangelist's
name on checks and other documents.
   ``He liked it (the signature) to look like his,'' said Shirley
Fulbright, testifying at the federal tax evasion trial of two former
PTL officials, brothers David and James Taggart. ``I tried my best.''
   Miss Fulbright also said David Taggart once boasted he had job
security at PTL because of things he knew about Bakker, who built
the evangelical empire before stepping down in 1987 in a sex and
money scandal.
   ``I vaguely remember a comment he made in jest, jokingly, in
which he said something to the effect that Mr. Bakker would not fire
him or me because of some of the things we knew about him,'' Miss
Fulbright said.
   ``He laughingly said he knew a lot about Jim Bakker. That's
all,'' she said when pressed by special prosecutor David Brown for
specifics.
   The Taggarts are charged with failing to pay $487,000 in taxes
from 1984 to 1987 on $1.1 million that prosecutors say the Taggarts
diverted from the ministry for their personal use by taking cash
advances on PTL credit cards and using blank ministry checks.
   Bakker is charged in Charlotte, N.C., with fraud and conspiracy
concerning PTL operations. A federal magistrate ruled Monday that
Bakker can be tried in that city without fear of pretrial publicity
because two years have elapsed since his resignation drew media
coverage of the ``holy war'' in television ministries.
   Miss Fulbright testified that she signed Bakker's name to several
documents authorizing payment to the Taggarts without Bakker's
knowledge. One memorandum authorized PTL to pay James Taggart's
interior design firm a $10,000-a-month retainer. Another authorized
a $100,000 payment to the firm.
   She said she also signed an authorization to pay David Taggart a
$120,000 bonus shortly before Bakker's resignation.
   Miss Fulbright testified she signed Bakker's name at the
direction of David Taggart.
   ``Did this ever cause you concern, Miss Fulbright,'' Brown asked
her.
   ``At that moment, I did not know what it represented,'' she said.
``Later on, I realized what they did represent.''
   Under cross-examination, Miss Fulbright testified that Bakker
previously had given her the authority to sign his name on
documents, including checks, letters and memos. Miss Fulbright said
she knew of no limitations on her authority to use Bakker's
signature and said her work was personally examined by Bakker.
   ``I assumed I could sign everything ... if it were necessary,''
she said.
   Witnesses have testified that the Taggarts shared expenses on an
apartment in exclusive Trump Towers in New York City, gave each
other Jaguars for Christmas presents and bought expensive jewelry at
Cartier and Gucci.
   If convicted, the Taggarts could each receive 30 years in prison
and fines totaling $1.35 million.
</TEXT>
