<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Salvador-Law Adv18   07-10 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Law, Adv 18,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs July 18 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Opposition Decries Salvadoran Anti-Terrorist Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new government of President
Alfredo Christiani is proposing stiff prison terms for those taking
part in activities of union, peasant and human rights organizations
considered guerrilla fronts.
   The Christian Democratic Party, which handed over power in June
to the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, termed
the bill ``fascist.''
   The entire political opposition has condemned the draft
legislation, which seems certain to be passed by Arena's legislative
majority.
   Opponents say the bill, which overhauls the penal code,
drastically erodes constitutional rights, including freedom of the
press.
   The New York-based Committee to Protect Journalists sent a telex
message to Cristiani expressing alarm that the legislation will
``severely hamper (journalists') ability to exercise their
internationally recognized right to pursue their profession.''
   The government says the legislation is necessary to combat
terrorism.
   It was presented to the unicameral legislature late in June amid
a spate of assassinations and bombings authorities blamed on
guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN.
   The insurgents have denied responsibility for attacks on
non-military officials and say some members of the far right are
employing terrorist tactics to eliminate rivals.
   They also accuse the government and military of wanton violence
in an effort to gain support for harsh legislative measures.
   A 9-year-old civil war between the Marxist-led rebels and the
Salvadoran government has left an estimated 70,000 dead, most of
them civilians.
   The legislation provides for prison terms of up to 30 years for
those convicted of murder, kidnapping, armed assault or sabotage
intended ``to provoke a state of terror.''
   It also provides up to 20 years in prison for those who take part
in peaceful takeovers or sit-ins at public buildings, schools,
embassies or churches. Those who block traffic with demonstrations
or marches, as well as those who paint slogans on public or private
buildings, could be sentenced to five years.
   Dozens of left-leaning ``popular organizations'' of workers,
peasants, displaced people and rights activists routinely employ
marches, sit-ins and graffiti to express their views.
   The legislation provides for up to 10 years in prison for anyone
``who voluntarily collaborates toward the realization of the goals
of any terrorist group, band or organization.''
   Authorities consider most ``popular organizations'' fronts for
FMLN activity. The state pays for advertisements in newspapers
explicitly linking union, rights and peasant groups to the insurgent
army.
   The popular organizations deny the charges.
   ``This is the old `sea-and-fish' thesis,'' said the Rev. Segundo
Montes, a Jesuit priest and director of the Human Rights Institute
of the prestigious Central American University. He referred to the
tenet that guerrilla forces _ the fish _ move undetected through a
sympathetic populace _ the sea.
   ``But the sea is now more than the rural population,'' he said.
``It includes unions and humanitarian organizations. The right sees
demands for higher wages not as demands for higher wages, but as
support for Marxist revolution.
   ``The object of this law is to make repression legal, to destroy
everything leftist,'' he said in an interview.
   The local and international press corps are concerned about the
bill's provision of a maximum four-year prison term for anyone ``who
in any manner spreads or promulgates propaganda that subverts the
public order.''
   The draft does not define what constitutes subversion of the
public order.
   Communications Minister Mauricio Sandoval met with local and
foreign reporters in an attempt to assure them that the law was not
designed to restrict the press, but the journalists left the meeting
unsatisfied.
   ``The law's sweeping language could be interpreted to include
almost any type of legitimate reporting,'' said the Committee to
Protect Journalists' telex message to Cristiani.
   The Christian Democrats, in a communique labeling the proposed
law ``fascist,'' said it was ``an attack on the most elemental human
rights'' and an attempt ``to impose state terrorism that would favor
the FMLN and prejudice the people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs July 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-BushNegroes Adv19   07-10 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Negroes, Adv 19,0821</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19 ^For Release Wed PMs July 19 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>War Uproots Isolated Bush Negroes in South America</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LAURENT, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along the muddy Maroni River
deep in the Amazon rain forest, thousands of refugees wait for an
obscure civil war to end in neighboring Suriname.
   They are Bush Negroes, descendants of West African slaves who
fled into the jungle after Dutch colonists brought them across the
Atlantic hundreds of years ago to work the plantations.
   From the late 1600s to the early 1800s, thousands of slaves
fought off the settlers, destroying plantations, freeing other
slaves and vanishing into the vast tropical hinterland.
   Isolated like many Indian tribes of the Amazon region, the Bush
Negroes have their own language and culture.
   ``For three centuries, the Bush Afro-Americans have been a nation
within a nation,'' Arthur Hailey, author of ``Roots,'' wrote in the
introduction to a history of the Bush Negroes. ``They have remained
independent and faithful to African traditions like no other group
in the New World.''
   Today, they flee a three-year war between Suriname's National
Army and the Jungle Commando, a rebel group of about 200 whose
leader, Ronny Brunswijk, is a Bush Negro from the Mongo Tapu village
in eastern Suriname.
   Most Bush Negroes come from thatched hut villages in eastern
Suriname, where they exist by fishing, hunting, planting crops and
gathering wild nuts and fruits.
   They number about 65,000 in six tribal nations _ the Aukaner,
Ndjuka, Saramaka, Paramaka, Matuari and Kwinti.
   Since the fighting erupted in 1986 in Suriname, hundreds of Bush
Negroes have been killed and many villages destroyed. The military
accuses Bush Negroes of being rebels or of aiding them.
   More than 7,000 Bush Negroes and hundreds of Amerindians have
crossed the Maroni River to camps near St. Laurent in this French
territory.
   About 10,000 others have fled to Suriname's capital, Paramaribo.
   They tell similar stories of the army burning their villages and
killing their children, husbands and wives.
   ``The military burned my village, my hut, with everything in it.
Every day it's bang-bang-bang,'' said Swanita, the mother of seven
children.
   Most Bush Negroes aren't involved in the war and say they just
want to live in peace.
   Although Ronny Brunswijk is one of them, many Bush Negroes,
including his brother John, are baffled by him.
   ``I don't know what he wants; he never told me,'' said John, 25,
who is chief of the Ndjukas and came to the Acarouany camp with his
wife and two children 2{ years ago. ``But I'm not like him. I don't
like fighting.''
   Ronny, 27, is a Cuban-trained soldier who was the personal
bodyguard of Cmdr. Desi Bouterse of Suriname's armed forces until
being fired in 1986.
   Details of their falling out are unknown, but the war is seen as
a personal feud between Brunswijk and the 42-year-old Bouterse.
   After he was fired, Brunswijk is said to have taken arms and
ammunition with him. He robbed banks and gave the money to his
people, gaining the reputation of a Robin Hood. But in June, 1986,
Bouterse's army attacked Brunswijk's village, and the Jungle
Commando was born.
   The refugees are shunned in French Guiana, a land of 80,000
people on the northern shoulder of South America. In St. Laurent,
with a population of 7,000, many blame them for a rise in drug
trafficking, robbery and murder.
   The refugees live outside St. Laurent in four camps, each run by
about 20 French military police. To leave even for a few hours, they
need permission and are transported on military trucks.
   ``The refugees live in good conditions and have plenty of food
and medical care,'' said Guido Coosemans, head of the United Nations
High Commission for Refugees office in St. Laurent. ``But the
problem is that the camps are more or less closed camps, and there
is no possibility of employment.''
   Many view the Bush Negroes, also known as Maroons, as primitive
because of their isolated existence.
   ``Maroons are the people who have the most problems right now. If
they come to Paramaribo, they get the lowest paid jobs and live in
the worst conditions,'' said Gloria Leurs, of the human-rights
organization Mooiwana '86, named after a Surinamese village where at
least 35 refugees were killed in an army raid Nov. 29, 1986.
   The French government is waiting to see if a peace agreement,
signed in early June between the government and Brunswijk, takes
hold before repatriating the refugees to Suriname.
   The refugees are wary.
   ``We don't believe the army wants peace,'' said 27-year-old
Nathaniel, the ``granman,'' or chief, of the Acarouany refugee camp,
which has 1,428 refugees. ``If we go back, they will kill us.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs July 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
