<FIRST>a a BC-TodayinHistory Adv17   07-10 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Today in History, Adv17,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, July 17, the 198th day of 1989. There are 167
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On July 17, 1938, aviator Douglas Corrigan took off from New York
with the stated intention of going to California, but ended up the
next day in Ireland, earning himself the nickname Wrong Way Corrigan.
   On this date:
   In 1821, Spain ceded Florida to the United States.
   In 1841, the British humor magazine Punch was first published.
   In 1889, mystery writer Erle Stanley Gardner, who created the
character of defense attorney Perry Mason, was born in Malden, Mass.
   In 1898, during the Spanish-American War, the Spaniards
surrendered to the Americans at Santiago, Cuba.
   In 1917, the British royal family adopted the name Windsor.
   In 1935, the entertainment industry publication Variety ran its
classic headline, ``Sticks Nix Hick Pix.'' (Translation: Rural
audiences don't like movies with rural themes.)
   In 1945, President Harry S. Truman, Soviet Premier Josef Stalin
and British Prime Minister Winston S. Churchill began meeting at
Potsdam in the final Allied summit of World War II.
   In 1948, southern Democrats opposed to the nomination of
President Harry S. Truman met in Birmingham, Ala., to endorse South
Carolina Gov. Strom Thurmond.
   In 1955, Disneyland had its opening day in Anaheim, Calif.
   In 1975, Apollo and Soyuz spacecraft docked in orbit in the first
superpower linkup of its kind.
   In 1980, Ronald Reagan formally accepted the Republican
nomination for president at the party's convention in Detroit.
   In 1981, two walkways above the lobby of Kansas City's Hyatt
Regency Hotel collapsed, killing 114 people and injuring 200 others.
   In 1987, 10 teen-agers were killed when raging floodwaters from
the Guadalupe River near Comfort, Texas, swept away a church bus and
van holding 43 people.
   Ten years ago: Nicaraguan President Anastasio Somoza resigned and
fled into exile in Miami. President Carter asked for and received
offers of resignation from his entire Cabinet and senior White House
staff in a major shake-up. The National League defeated the American
League 7-6 in the All-Star Game.
   Five years ago: The Rev. Jesse Jackson, addressing the Democratic
convention in San Francisco, asked the party to forgive him for any
error of ``temper, taste or tone'' during his presidential campaign.
   One year ago: Michael Dukakis arrived in Atlanta to claim the
Democratic nomination for president.
   Today's birthdays: TV personality Art Linkletter is 77. Comedian
Phyllis Diller is 72. Actor Donald Sutherland is 55. Comedy writer
Pat McCormick is 55. Actress-singer Diahann Carroll is 54. Actress
Lucie Arnaz is 38. Actor David Hasselhoff is 37. Singer Phoebe Snow
is 37. Singer Nicolette Larson is 37.
   Thought for today: ``A life spent in making mistakes is not only
more honorable but more useful than a life spent in doing nothing.''
_ George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance For Release Monday, July 17</NOTE>
