<SECOND>BC-Today in History, Adv22,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, July 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cleaveland is cq in 6th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, July 22, the 203rd day of 1989. There are 162
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty years ago, on July 22, 1969, Apollo 11 astronauts Neil
Armstrong, Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin and Michael Collins, safely
reunited aboard the command module, blasted out of lunar orbit for
the start of their journey home after the first landing on the moon.
   On this date:
   In 1587, a second English colony _ like the first fated to vanish
under mysterious circumstances _ was established on Roanoke Island
off North Carolina.
   In 1796, Cleveland, Ohio, was founded by Gen. Moses Cleaveland.
   In 1812, English troops under the Duke of Wellington defeated the
French at the Battle of Salamanca in Spain.
   In 1844, Anglican clergyman William Archibald Spooner _ whose
habit of transposing words or syllables in his speech resulted in
the term ``spoonerisms'' _ was born in London.
   In 1916, a bomb went off during a Preparedness Day parade in San
Francisco, killing 10 people.
   In 1933, American aviator Wiley Post completed the first solo
flight around the world in seven days, 18 hours and 45 minutes.
   In 1934, John Dillinger was shot to death by federal agents
outside Chicago's Biograph Theater.
   In 1937, the Senate rejected President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
proposal to add more justices to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   In 1942, gasoline rationing began in the United States during
World War II.
   In 1943, Allied forces captured Palermo, Sicily.
   In 1975, the U.S. House of Representatives joined the Senate in
voting to restore American citizenship to Confederate Gen. Robert E.
Lee, more than a century after his death.
   In 1981, Turkish terrorist Mehmet Ali Agca was sentenced in a
Rome court to life in prison for shooting Pope John Paul II.
   In 1986, for the first time in a half-century, the U.S. House of
Representatives impeached a federal official. Judge Harry E.
Claiborne was later convicted by the Senate of tax evasion and of
bringing disrepute on the federal courts.
   Ten years ago: First Lady Rosalynn Carter stumped the nation's
heartland, assuring a number of groups, including the National Urban
League in Chicago, that her husband was able to lead the country out
of what she termed a crisis.
   Five years ago: Egyptian university student Isama Ahmed Momtaza
set a men's world record time for swimming the English Channel both
ways non-stop, completing the journey in 21 hours and 37 minutes.
   One year ago: Iran and Iraq said they would send their foreign
ministers to New York to meet with U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar, after Iran said it would accept a U.N. cease-fire
resolution.
   Today's birthdays: Rose Kennedy is 99. Psychiatrist Dr. Karl
Menninger is 96. Sen. William Roth, R-Del., is 68. Senate Minority
Leader Bob Dole, R-Kansas, is 66. Singer Margaret Whiting is 65.
Actor-comedian Orson Bean is 61. Fashion designer Oscar de la Renta
is 57. Actor Terence Stamp is 49. Game show host Alex Trebek is 49.
Actor-singer Bobby Sherman is 44. Actor-comedian-director Albert
Brooks is 42.
   Thought for today: ``There is a single light of science, and to
brighten it anywhere is to brighten it everywhere.'' _ Isaac Asimov,
American author.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance For Release Saturday, July 22</NOTE>
