<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Europe-1992-Americans Adv16   07-10 1170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe-1992-Americans, Adv 16,1215</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Companies Seeking Footholds for 1992 in Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   What lies in store for Americans when a dozen
West European nations open up their trading doors in 1992? U.S.
businessmen can't be totally certain, but many of them see
opportunity. This is one of a series of occasional reports on what
is in store in Western Europe when traditional trade barriers are
removed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American businesses are rushing to open
factories, snap up companies and sell their products to take
advantage of the giant consumer market that will be formed in
Western Europe in 1992.
   U.S. corporate executives are plotting strategy for the single
market that will be created when the dozen nations of the European
Economic Community get rid of the many trade barriers separating
them.
   ``It is no more business as usual,'' advises Data Resources Inc.,
a Massachusetts-based consulting firm.
   Businesses agree.
   ``1992 will happen,'' said William Gibson, president of Digital
Microwave Corp., a San Jose, Calif., company. ``Europe will look
very much like the United States.''
   ``The opportunities here are very great,'' said Chris Chaney,
sitting in the just-opened European office of Multiflow, a
computer-maker based in Branford, Conn.
   The date 1992 has become the catchword for the move by the EEC
trading bloc to allow the free movement of people, money, goods and
services among the 12 member nations. Its deadline for creating the
single, European-wide market is Dec. 31, 1992.
   Carla Hills, the U.S. trade representative, told Congress in
Washington recently, ``No other market is as important for American
exporters or our investors as is the market of the European
Community.''
   The EEC, also known as the Common Market, was the United States'
largest trading partner last year.
   American companies of all sizes _ and in a variety of fields _
want to get into the market under the deadline.
   ``1992 is now'' and companies need to get a toehold in the
European market, said Paul Sher, director of EEC affairs for Hill
and Knowlton, the U.S. public relations firm.
   Alfred Kingon, the former U.S. ambassador to the community, said,
``One option nobody has is to wait until 1992 to see what shape the
market is going to be. ... They have to do their thinking now.''
   Paul Provost, director of EEC public affairs for the American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., said companies are investing money,
hiring employees and setting up research and development facilities.
   Some worry the community will set up barriers denying outsiders
access to its 320 million people.
   ``There is a fear that advocates of a `Europe-for-the-Europeans'
approach may succeed in delaying or taking charge of key elements of
the 1992 agenda,'' said James Robinson, chairman of American Express.
   ``That could lead to discrimination against companies of
non-European parentage,'' he said in a speech in Brussels.
   A recent U.S. Commerce Department report said American companies
should benefit from the single market. But, it cautioned, a danger
exists if the program is put into effect ``in a less than open
fashion.''
   California's Digital Microwave, which makes high performance
short-haul transmission products, doesn't want to be excluded.
   ``Our intent is to become a European supplier,'' said Gibson.
Last year, the company opened a high-tech factory in Scotland.
   The fear of ``Fortress Europe'' was much stronger last year. But
the EEC has tried to calm anxieties that it will throw up
protectionist barriers to keep others out.
   ``The whole Fortress Europe (concern) has cooled off,'' said
Eamonn Bates, EEC affairs manager for the American Chamber of
Commerce in Brussels.
   ``People have got more informed and now know a lot more about
1992. They realize it's not all bad news.''
   In a key move, the community backed off a proposal that appeared
to discriminate against foreign banks and financial institutions,
which do billions of dollars worth of business in Europe.
   Bates said U.S. businesses were encouraged that ``things can be
worked out if you deal with (community officials) properly.''
   The latest red flags have been hoisted over the community's plans
for regulating TV programming, industrial standards and government
purchases in the fields of telecommunications, water, energy and
transportation.
   Mrs. Hills has complained about the move to require that a
majority of entertainment programs shown on European TV be made in
Europe. She said it would ``almost certainly have a disastrous
effect'' on the American industry's earnings in Europe.
   The United States has also objected to a plan to let governments
reject bids for telecommunications products if more than half the
components were made outside the community. Such ``local content''
provisions also have surfaced in purchasing proposals for energy,
water and transportation.
   But big multinational companies with long histories in Europe say
they're ready.
   Since the 1950s, International Business Machines Corp. has
maintained a pan-European manufacturing approach.
   ``It made business sense to treat Europe as an entity,'' said IBM
spokesman John Wells in Paris.
   IBM has a dozen manufacturing plants in the EEC countries. More
than 90 percent of the products it sells in Europe are made in
Europe.
   Other companies are strengthening their positions.
   In 1986, American companies completed 89 mergers and
acquisitions, worth $1.4 billion, in the trading bloc, according to
Martin Sikora, editor of the Philadelphia-based magazine Mergers &amp;
Acquisitions.
   The number of deals rose to 107, valued at $2.4 billion, in 1987
and amounted to 82, worth $2.1 billion, last year. Most were in
food, pharmaceuticals, industrial equipment, and electronics and
computers.
   ``It allows larger, stronger, more aggressive companies to play
in this vast market,'' Sikora said.
   Whirlpool Corp. appeared to gain a firm base in Europe after
agreeing last year to form a joint venture with the major domestic
appliances division of Philips, the Dutch electronics giant.
   AT&amp;T and Philips set up a telecommunications partnership in the
early 1980s. And AT&amp;T linked up last June with Italtel, the Italian
telecommunications equipment maker, and STET, the state-holding
company that is Italtel's parent.
   Many Americans see a chance to boost their sales in the new
market, which is expected to force European companies to improve
their operations and become more competitive.
   Compaq Computer, a big maker of personal computers for European
businesses, sees an even greater demand in the single market.
   ``Companies are doing everything they can to position
themselves,'' said James D'Arezzo, marketing vice president for
Compaq's international office in Munich, Germany. ``We're reaping
that benefit.''
   To meet increased demand, the Houston-based company plans to
double the size of its manufacturing plant in Scotland.
   Stonhard, maker of epoxy industrial floors, wants to take
advantage of Europeans' increasing need for better factories, said
James Baldino, managing director of the company's European
operations.
   The company, based in Maple Shade, N.J., opened the Brussels
office in 1987 to expand its business and later got caught up in the
1992 push.
   ``For us, the timing could not be better,'' said Baldino.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
