<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   07-10 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Madame Sousatzka'' (MCA-Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated
PG-13)
   
   In ``Madame Sousatzka,'' Shirley MacLaine teaches piano and a
side course on life. Both are required classes for her students.
   MacLaine plays an aging, eccentric piano instructor who demands
total obedience and absolute faith in her methods. ``I teach not
only how to play the piano but how to live,'' she declares.
   In her London flat, musty and riddled with dusty relics from her
mysterious past, Sousatzka tries to mold and shape her aspiring
prodigies. But sometimes the young students are not as malleable as
she would like.
   The movie revolves around just such a conflict.
   Manek Sen, an Indian immigrant with a flair for the piano, is
brought to the madame by his mother, who sees dollar signs in her
son's budding talent.
   Manek, delightfully played by Navin Chowdhry, is a young man
struggling through adolescence, his culture and his gift. Madame
Sousatzka wants complete compliance; Manek would like to roller
skate on occasion with his pals.
   The rest of the film spins between these two revolving wills.
   MacLaine, shrouded in her colorful shawl and forever dousing
herself with perfume, reveals in the end that beneath her pedantry
is a lonely soul.
   Mankek, in turn, learns an important lesson in self-reliance when
he is forced to make a major decision for himself.
   There also are some intriguing subplots involving Peggy Ashcroft,
Twiggy and the other residents of MacLaine's building as they face
encroaching commercial development.
   But it's MacLaine who haunts the memory of Madame Sousatzka and
in watching it one can learn a few subtle and bittersweet lessons of
life.
   By Patricia Bibby, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Stripped to Kill II'' (MGM-UA. VHS-Beta, $79.95. Rated R)
   
   ``Stripped to Kill II'' is a mystery about a serial killer with a
lot of gratuitous stripping _ as one would expect from the title.
It's really not a bad movie, but the filmmakers seemed to think that
since the action takes place in a strip joint, they must focus on
that lost art.
   The story has a number of nice twists and a good buildup of
suspense as the climax nears. Unfortunately, the pace is constantly
interrupted by the obligatory disrobing of would-be victims.
   Interestingly, the biggest failure of ``Stripped to Kill II'' is
its misguided attempt at eroticism. What is intended as a tease is
merely a turnoff. The other major failing in the movie is the
stilted and cliche-ridden dialogue.
   But the quality of the filming is very good, with a nice smoky,
sleazy atmosphere in the club and its environs.
   The mystery is pretty simple, the Paragon club's strippers are
being killed one-by-one. Each has her throat slashed, and before
each murder, a stripper (Maria Ford) has a dream about the gruesome
death.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
