<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Sartain Adv21-23   07-10 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Sartain, Adv 21-23,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 21-23 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Gailard Sartain _ a Once Rejected Actor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gailard Sartain tried out for acting
roles in high school and college, but never made the cast.
   But he didn't give up on his ambition to become an actor. Thanks
to his perseverance, he's become a familiar face on TV and in movies
during the past 17 years.
   The rotund 44-year-old performer has been doing skits since 1972
on ``Hee Haw,'' the syndicated country music-humor show on TV. He's
also appeared in 23 movies, most recently portraying a sheriff in
``Mississippi Burning.''
   He didn't get discouraged after being rejected for parts in
productions while in high school in his native Tulsa, Okla., and at
the University of Tulsa.
   ``I tried out for stuff, but never got in,'' Sartain recalled in
an interview at a TV studio in the Grand Ole Opry House as he
awaited ``Hee Haw'' tapings to resume.
   ``I wasn't in the right clique or in the theater department,'' he
said. ``Even in high school, there was a clique. At the college
level, it was a major clique, and if you weren't a drama major, you
might get to play a doorstop or something.''
   He first got noticed in the early 1970s while doing some comedy
routines as host of late-night movies on a Tulsa TV station. This
led to ``Hee Haw,'' and his ``Hee Haw'' skits led to dramatic motion
picture roles.
   He portrayed the Big Bopper in ``The Buddy Holly Story,'' and
also was in ``Hard Country'' with Jan-Michael Vincent and Kim
Basinger, ``Roadie'' with Art Carney and Meat Loaf and ``The Jerk''
and ``All of Me,'' both starring Steve Martin.
   On ``Hee Haw,'' he's best known as the bumbling Maynard in a
general store segment, and Hammerhead in a spot about a hotel. He
also has been in segments originating in a flea market and a truck
stop. This fall, he'll be seen in two new spots: ``Eyewitless News''
and the Kornfield Kounty Kourtroom.
   Because of his comedy work in the cornpone ``Hee Haw,'' some
people didn't recognize him as the sheriff in ``Mississippi
Burning.''
   ``I've been told people don't believe I was the sheriff,''
Sartain said. ``They say, `No, not Maynard. What are you talking
about?'''
   He considers his work in ``Mississippi Burning'' as his best to
date.
   ``It's a quality film and I enjoyed it. It was a real departure
for me. A couple of scenes of mine were brutal. There was an
undercurrent of hatred and hostility. It was a gigantic departure
from `Hee Haw.'''
   He has already finished two other movies that will be released in
coming months _ ``Blaze,'' starring Paul Newman, and ``Love at
Large,'' starring Tom Berenger.
   He enjoys the camaraderie of ``Hee Haw,'' which is taped in June
and October, thus permitting him to accept movie roles the rest of
the year.
   ``It's a family feeling,'' Sartain said. ``You don't have to
force anything. It's like a giant birthday party.''
   He believes the show has lasted since 1968 because of the
relaxing feeling it projects.
   ``Once you become acclimated to the show, it's comfortable. It's
a literal institution as far as television goes. I think people know
what to expect and like it.''
   The longevity of the show has surprised even him.
   ``I felt 15 years ago that I had one year left. Now, it could go
on another two months or 10 years. It depends on who is left
standing.''
   The one-hour show, starring Roy Clark, has featured virtually
every major country music star down through the years. It is seen by
about 13 million viewers on more than 200 stations in this country
and Canada, usually early Saturday night. Even if it were to end
production today, it would have vaults of programs to use for reruns.
   ``It's a real pleasant thing to do,'' Sartain said about the show.
   Prior to doing the Tulsa TV show, he was a writer-illustrator for
Hallmark Cards for about a year. He still is interested in painting.
   ``In 1985 I sold about half of my 18 pieces,'' he said. ``Now I
miss them. They were like my kids.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, July 21-23</NOTE>
