<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Accessories     07-10 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Accessories,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Accessories</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY704, NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   They always fit, they last for years, they endure through
transient fashion changes _ and they are among the biggest sellers
of this season's fashion scene.
   They are accessories _ scarves, handbags, jewelry, anything to
decorate and accent clothing. Accessories magazine estimates that
the customers bought about $14 billion worth of these last year.
   Some prestigious names are making a showing in new parts of this
lucrative market _ like Tiffany and Cartier, New York Fifth Avenue
jewellers who both are marketing scarves, handbags and other small
leather goods.
   Tiffany's entry into scarves began with a few designs made up for
the store's 150th anniversary two years ago. Sales _ at $150 each _
were so rewarding that the store now currently stocks about 200
designs at its outlets around the country and overseas. Exotic
florals and chinoiserie, bordered with logo designs, dominate the
all-silk collection.
   ``Jewelry is the ultimate accessory, and we see our scarves as an
extension of our jewelry,'' says Tiffany's design director John
Loring. ``The scarves are already having a very nice career for
themselves.''
   Tiffany handbags are dressy and classic in silk and leather, all
with signature details _ including one with a large ``T'' closure.
   Cartier's scarves include some imprinted with graphics of
precious jewelry, signed with store's boutique logo, Must de
Cartier. They blend with a line of silk evening bags with similar
designs.
   Cartier says that one of its more popular categories is watches _
wardrobes of them, including their Pasha watches. Men, especially,
are conscious of watches as fashion accessories. Cartier offers them
with straps in vivid primary colors, like bottle green, to black
crocodile and gold. ``Watches are one item of jewelry which men can
use to make a distinctive statement both about their individual
personalities and their success without stepping out of bounds of
proper male etiquette,'' says Jill Romeo King, boutique manager at
Cartier's New York store.
   If jewelry is the ultimate accessory, it's still not necessary to
lay out a lot of money for ``good'' pieces, like natural stones and
precious metals. The American Gem Society reports that colored
gemstones are enjoying a current surge in popularity. Rarity and
price range widely, but most are affordable for most people. Some of
the most common and popular gems include peridot (bright green),
rubellite tourmaline (hot pink), aquamarine (pale blue), kunzite
(pale pink), citrine (honey tones), and amethyst (purple).
   William G. Underwood, president of the society, says interest in
the stones began building in the early 1980s, when British Princess
Diana chose a sapphire and diamond engagement ring. An AGS survey
also revealed strong preference for pearls.
   These pieces increase in both sentimental and actual value,
Underwood says, and they never go out of style. ``Many of the
popular jewelry designs today came from the 40s and 50s when pearls
and pins were staple items in a woman's jewelry wardrobe.''
   New York jewelry designer Denise Solay adds: ``Jewelry is
seasonless and timeless and allows a woman to make a personal
statement on her own terms.'' She markets her designs, strongly
influenced by her world travels, through her own company, A World on
a String.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
