<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Maternity</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY708</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Because today's expectant mothers continue to work through most
of their pregnancies, they choose more fashionable maternity clothes
and plan to continue wearing them after delivery, says a maternity
wear designer.
   Judy Loeb, design director for the Trio line from Jeanette
Maternities Inc., says women aren't borrowing these clothes as much
as they did in the past because new designs are more appropriate to
the workplace. Loeb, who designed the popular rhinestone-decorated
``Baby'' T-shirt several years ago, says these pointers should be
kept in mind when shopping for the new styles:
   _ Oversized regular clothes won't fit properly because they
aren't designed to compensate for a larger stomach and are likely to
hike up.
   _ Choose your regular size in maternity lines.
   _ Don't buy too much for one occasion. Balance the wardrobe
between business and weekend wear
   _ Try support pantyhose to reduce leg discomfort during pregnancy.
   _ A maternity slip or petticoat will make clothes drape better
and give you a smoother silhouette.
   _ Tops should be long enough to cover your stomach, derriere and
hips.
   _ Natural fibers such as cotton, wool and some rayons will be
most comfortable.
   _ Don't buy everything at once. Space your purchases carefully,
buying special occasion clothes when and if you need them. Allow for
impulse shopping late in your pregnancy.
</TEXT>
