<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Disabled     07-10 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Disabled,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Disabled</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY710</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When actress and model Pamela Ann Martin suffered a disabling
spinal stroke she spent a year in a hospital, flat on her back _ but
she still managed to get to a shopping mall on a stretcher to follow
her passion for fashion.
   ``I was the only person shopping for clothes from a horizontal
position,'' recalls the vivacious brunette, who graduated from
California's Brooks College with a degree in fashion merchandising
and design.
   A physical therapy counselor encouraged Pamela to become a
computer programmer or a keypunch operator but that was much too
uncreative, she says, adding:
   ``I told them I was going to Hollywood to study acting. They
laughed.''
   But now, more than a decade after her stroke, the 35-year-old Ms.
Martin's determination has paid off with wheelchair appearances in
several television dramas, feature films and national talk shows.
She also writes a column, ``Rolling With Laughter,'' and recently
created the cartoon feature ``Wheelies.''
   Her modeling gigs have been mainly in behalf of Everest &amp;
Jennings, a California-based firm that produces ``Avenues,'' a
catalog line of fashionable clothing with hidden features to speed
dressing for wheelchair users.
   ``People who are disabled deserve to have a positive fashion
image,'' says Pamela, whose modeling endeavors began at the age of
6. ``I did fashion shows for charity and social events throughout my
schoolgirl and college days.
   ``Now the biggest difference between my ability and disability is
that I model on wheels instead of in heels.
   ``Most people just jump in their clothes and _ zip _ they're off,
but for me, getting dressed can be a major project.''
   Often, she points out, conventional clothing doesn't fit or look
attractive on people who spend their day sitting. Jackets are too
long and too binding when propelling a sheelchair. Slacks are too
short and pockets are out of reach. Skirts drag and get caught in
wheels.
   Designers of clothes for wheelchair users should develop patterns
which flatter the seated figure, according to clothing consultants.
   ``To create clothing for special needs, you must use design to
solve problems,'' explains Dr. Naomi Reich, chairman of the
University of Arizona's Clothing and Textiles Department. ``That
requires analysis.''
   Research and testing indicate that such clothing should be cut
with extra fabric in the seat and less in the front.
   Other touches can include thigh pockets or hidden calf pockets
for keeping glasses, keys and other items within easy reach. And
some pants can have hidden ankle-to-knee zippers to speed dressing
and accommodate braces.
   According to Gret Atkins of Cornell University's Department of
Textiles and Apparel, clothing can be as much a barrier to
wheelchair users as a curb without a curb cut.
   ``Sometimes dressing can be so exhausting that they might choose
to stay in their nightwear and not go out or invite someone over,''
she says. ``We're such a visual society that most disabling
conditions _ whether an artificial limb, uneven gait or wheelchair _
call attention to themselves.
   ``If clothing draws further attention to disabilities then we
have failed as designers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Computer     07-10 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Computer,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computerization in the garment industry has
given new meaning to the term software _ make that softwear _ and
apparel design students at Cornell University are now learning to
design and cut patterns on machines similar to the ones they will be
using as professionals.
   A computer program normally used by architects and engineers,
AutoCAD, has been adapted to work with the soft lines and design
requirements of clothing. This microcomputer _ more affordable than
the huge computer systems in large apparel firms _ enables students
to carry out the entire garment design process, from preliminary
sketches to pattern layouts, or markers.
   Traditional paper pattern making requires slow, meticulous
cutting and taping. Lisa Gedzelman, a senior apparel design student
from Chappaqua, N.Y., says the computer eases this job. ``Revisions
to my skirt and short-sleeve jacket outfit that would normally call
for recutting the pattern by hand were quick and easy on the
computer.''
   The computers were installed in l988 with a grant from Project
Ezra, an $8 million IBM program providing computers for use by
Cornell.
   ``Probably eight to 10 schools are making their first use of
AutoCAD in apparel design courses, but Cornell may be the only one
that is taking the designs to the garment stage,'' says Anita
Racine, senior lecturer in the textiles and apparel department, who
teaches the class in computer-aided design.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Shoes     07-10 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Shoes,,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Shoes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If it's not as comfortable as an old shoe, don't buy the new one.
   So says Geof Bloom, whose company makes Hush Puppies footwear.
``When you're shopping for fall shoes, remember any shoe that
doesn't fit properly will cause some degree of pain,'' he says.
   He offers these tips for shoe shoppers:
   _ Shop for shoes in mid-afternoon, when your feet have swollen to
their normal maximum.
   _ Wear appropriate hosiery or socks, the same type you plan to
wear with the shoes.
   _ Postpone shopping if your feet hurt. You won't be able to tell
if it's the new pair that is uncomfortable.
   _ Try on both shoes. The left foot usually is larger than the
right.
   _ Try shoes by fit, not size. Different styles may fit
differently. If in doubt, try the next size up; the shoe may be only
a sixth of an inch longer, but that small margin can prove to be
what makes it wearable.
   _ Be aware of the difference between ``snug'' and ``tight.'' A
snug shoe may stretch a bit and mold to the foot in use. But don't
expect to break in a shoe that pinches or cramps.
   _ Stand up on your full weight and see if you can wiggle your
toes. There should be at least a half-inch space in front of your
longest toe.
   _ Make sure the widest part of your foot sits in the widest part
of the shoe. This will let the shoe and foot bend together.
   _ Walk as hard and fast as you do normally when trying on shoes.
Make several circuits around the shop or department.
   _ Test the shoes at home after you've purchased them. Walk around
the house on hard floors for at least five minutes to judge if the
shoes feel as comfortable as they did on the store's soft carpeting.
If they don't, remember that as long as you haven't worn the shoes
outdoors, you can return them to the store for a better fit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Cosmetics     07-10 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Cosmetics,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Cosmetics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The colors of the desert _ from golden sand to vibrant purple _
inspire the latest shades on the cosmetic palette, according to an
article in Harper's Bazaar.
   For lips, blushers and eye shadows, the magazine says, reds and
pastels are giving way to tan, beige, brown, sage green, brick,
burnt orange, turquoise, periwinkle and violet.
   There are many gradations in desert colors _ ``pale and serene to
gutsy and sultry,'' says the magazine.
   ``They evoke wonderful emotions, feelings of friendliness and
warmth from the earthy shades, and playfulness from the brights,''
says Leatrice Eiseman, executive director of the Pantone Color
Institute.
   She says ``people are traveling a lot more these days; they're
discovering America,'' particularly the Southwest.
   ``Visit the area and you're mesmerized by the terrain, the clear
blue sky, the incredible sunsets. These colors linger indelibly in
your mind and in the striking image you'd like to project,'' she
says.
   In general, makeup professionals agree that when lips are strong,
eyes should be less than vibrant, and vice-versa, she says. Cheek
color should always be minimal and well blended.
   For blondes, lips should be translucent beige by day and rich
brown at night, highlighted with transparent gold.
   Cheeks should be pale burnt umber by day, and light brick at
night.
   Eyes by day should be dusty sage green, while at night they
should be deep brown with a hint of gold highlight in the center of
the lid.
   For brunettes, lips by day should be semitranslucent orange-red,
worn well-blotted, switching at night to intense orange-red with
matte finish.
   Cheeks by day vary from palomino for pale skin and peach-orange
for tan. At night, switch to terra cotta, highlighted with gold on
the cheekbones.
   Brunette eyes should be russet on the lips by day, and at night
turquoise at the outer corner and yellow at the inner.
   Redheads should color their lips with very transparent
peach-orange by day, and terra cotta with a gold highlight at night.
   Cheeks should be peach-orange in the daytime and terra cotta at
night.
   Eyes by day should present sage green lids with lavender at the
outer corners in the daytime, changing by night to sage with
turquoise at the outer corner and lavender at the inner corner.
   The black color scheme calls for lips that are sand color by day
and intense orange-red mixed with mahogany at night.
   Cheeks should go from orange-brick by day to terra cotta at night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Fashion:Perms     07-10 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Perms,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fashion: Perms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If your past experience with permanent waving left you with a
wild and woolly cap and a feeling that your hair would crumble if
you put a comb to it, you might try one of the new perms that offer
less drastic results _ or non-permanent permanents.
   A line of home permanents, Epic Waves, depends on a milder
chemical formula that gives the user the options to ``try on'' a
perm temporarily, better control, and the ability to re-perm often.
   Developed by Gillette, the line is formulated with a
protein-building amino acid, cysteine, which, with ammonium
bisulfites, only partially restructures hair. Regular permanents use
chemicals that completely break down the molecular structure of hair
and rebuild it again.
   ``Our consumer research shows that the three biggest fears women
have about home perming are lack of control, long-term commitment,
and damage to hair by frequent perming,'' says Mary Ann Pesce,
marketing director for Gillete's hair care products.
   The company says its Try-on Perm is the first temporary home
permanent product. Aimed at the first-time user, it fades away
within two weeks, leaving hair with slightly more body. Adaptable
Perm lets the user control the level of curl. She can wait up to two
days for the curl to relax before locking in it with a finishing
rinse, or, if she still isn't satisfied, she can skip the finishing
rinse and let the hair return to its original form. Anytime Perm can
be used without damage up to nine times a year for those who like
frequent re-perming. Other processes, like coloring, can be used the
same day as the permanents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
