<DOCNO> AP890710-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-SPE--Fashion:Vests     07-10 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Fashion: Vests,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>FASHION: Vests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Go vest, young man, is the styling advice coming this fall from
some men's fashion designers, who note that even President Bush
wears a brocade vest with his tuxedo on some occasions.
   ``Vests are a strong item in all kinds of fabrications and
stylings and with details like leather buttons,'' says Randy
Ronning, men's fashion director at J.C. Penney Co. Inc. ``We expect
vests to be 25 percent of our sweater business.''
   Ronning feels the return of the vest as a way to invigorate the
wardrobe is part of a trend toward a more relaxed sophistication in
menswear favored by both European and American designers.
   Some fashion experts describe it as a new direction of easy
elegance, meaning a more casual approach to tailored clothing and a
dressier angle on sportswear.
   This could add up to the relaxed look of a knit sweater vest worn
with a business suit or the dressy flair of a fancy brocade vest
coupled with a sports jacket and casual pants, or a colorful
cardigan vest with jeans and a sports shirt.
   Designer Henry Grethel, for whom sweater dressing has become a
signature, offers a fall sportswear collection that features the
solid or patterned cardigan vest.
   ``Under a sportcoat or over a woven shirt, the cardigan vest
boasts an air of gentility,'' suggests a Grethel publicist. ``The
button shawl collar makes a comeback, and the classic, cable-design
mock turtleneck sweater is ever present.''
   Liz Claiborne, another designer, noting a trend of pattern mixing
with colliding colors, has a weekender collection described as
rugged and relaxed, with an emphasis on tops, outerwear and American
Indian motifs. A key item is the oiled cowhide jacket, ``cut sleek
and sporty.''
   As often happens when it comes to fashions, however, there is not
complete unanimity among the experts.
   Concerning vested interest, for example, Playboy magazine's
fashion consultant said recently three-piece suits (the ones with
vests) ``have definitely gone out of style....Unless the fall season
brings a resurgence of this style, you should retire your vests and
stick to wearing the two other pieces of your suit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
