<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--AgingEurope Adv13   07-10 1011</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Aging Europe, Adv 13,1038</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Growing Number of Elderly Stirs Europe Into Action, Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the storybook awakening of Rip Van Winkle, who
found he'd slept into old age, Western European nations are
discovering what it means to lose their youth.
   Parts of Europe already have the world's highest populations of
elderly people, and governments are recognizing the change,
especially in the faster-aging north, where retirees may comprise 40
percent of some populations by 2040. From West Germany to Greece,
countries are studying how fewer young people will support strained
pension and health care systems.
   But gloomy visions of crowded old-age homes and broken economies
are out of line, experts say. They worry about the poor and lonely,
but say most will be comfortable, with money to spend _ as
advertisers have already noticed.
   The challenge, experts say, will be to show society that age
doesn't mean illness or empty lives. No American-style Gray Panthers
have appeared to defend the cause, but a British seniors group is
fighting age discrimination.
   ``Europe is in the position to be the first to enter a new social
world, so what we decide to do is of great importance. Only now is
anybody taking any notice of it,'' says Peter Laslett, a Cambridge
University demographer and expert on aging.
   ``We can't look at it simply in terms of a burden,'' says
Laslett, 73, who likes to lace demographic data with lines from
Wordsworth on the joys of youth. ``It's an enormous challenge for
human beings for the first time to use their whole potential.''
   Demographers say that while the developing world will catch up
quickly, Europe has more than twice the global proportion of
elderly, or 12.4 percent, and northern Europe has 2.5 times the
world average. Southern Europe, with its higher birthrates, is aging
less rapidly. By the year 2000 every fourth person will be over 65
in Western Europe, by one estimate.
   The main reasons are life-enhancing medicine and falling
birthrates, and some say Europe has been slow to recognize the
magnitude of the change.
   ``We're waking up to it late in the day,'' says Sally Greengross,
secretary-general of Eurolink Age, a coalition promoting the cause
of the 60 million over-60s in the European Economic Community.
   France forbids forced retirement and job advertisements aren't
allowed to set age limits. But other nations, says Eurolink Age,
have yet to follow suit.
   The 12-nation EEC plans a ``Year of the Elderly,'' but red tape
has postponed it to 1991. The EEC budget for elderly affairs more
than doubled in 1988, but only to the equivalent of $738,000.
   Pensions are of primary concern, prompted by fears of future
workers paying hefty proportions of their salaries to support
pensioners.
   West Germany estimates 40 percent of its population will be over
65 by 2040, and its Employers Federation says employees would have
to pay 36 percent of their salaries, or double today's rate, to
sustain benefits.
   The West German cabinet has proposed reforms, including hiking
the retirement age for women from 60 to 65, the age at which men
retire. Italy is considering similar action. Most EEC citizens can
receive retirement benefits at 60 or 65. Danes work the latest, to
67, and Italian women leave at 55.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government has acted
to abolish a $130 weekly limit on what pensioners can earn before
losing some benefits. At the same time, it has been criticized for
cutting pensions as part of what the government calls ``weaning
Britons off the dependency culture.''
   The elderly increasingly contribute to the economy by filling in
for the shrinking numbers of the young. Already, some are being
wooed back by employers like Britain's Tesco supermarket chain,
which hires 55- to 69-year-olds.
   ``They're very reliable, conscientious, and don't need so much
training,'' says Barry Ball, the personnel manager who began Tesco's
scheme a year ago.
   ``I'm not ready for retirement _ work keeps me young,'' says
Doris Broderick, 58, who started working in a Tesco market coffee
shop six months ago after being laid off from serving coffee to
Lloyd's shipping staff.
   Success After Sixty, a British employment agency for over-50s,
reported a 60-percent jump in requests from companies in the first
two months of 1989 compared with the same period last year.
   But prejudice still keeps many from working, says the Association
of Retired Persons, a British group based on the American
Association of Retired Persons. ARP, which has signed up 25,000
members in eight months, hopes to expand to France and Germany.
   ``The elderly are just beginning to organize in France,'' said
Ariane Revol-Briard of France's 8-year-old Ministry for the Elderly.
In Germany, a politician recently suggested a political party for
those 60 and over.
   Southern European countries, on the other hand, have less use for
older workers. Spain, with 19 percent unemployment, is studying a
plan to offer tax breaks to companies which retire older workers
early.
   In the health field, Europeans are turning to home care to reduce
strain on care systems and promote independence, says Anthea Tinker,
head of Britain's Age Concern Institute of Gerontology and a
specialist on elderly housing.
ing Down for Octogenarian Novelist
</TEXT>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL BASKERVILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NELLYSFORD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After writing 70 books _ 31 of them
best-selling mysteries _ Phyllis A. Whitney scoffs at any suggestion
of quitting.
   ``Horrible! What could be more boring,'' said the 85-year-old
Grand Master of American mystery writers. ``I've slowed down in that
I only write one book a year. A writer is what I am.''
   Her most recent book, ``Rainbow in the Mist,'' was published in
April, its title inspired by rainbows that tower over the
mist-shrouded Ragged Mountains after thunderstorms have washed the
sky around the mountaintop home Miss Whitney built two years ago.
   Not one to rest on her laurels, Miss Whitney is putting the
finishing touches on her 71st book, ``The Singing Stones,'' and
researching No. 72. ``I don't stop between books. You have to start
on new ideas immediately. To have a new story start burgeoning in
your imagination _ that's what's exciting.''
   Miss Whitney, who last year received the Mystery Writers of
America's highest honor, began writing at age 12. ``I was going to a
missionary school in China, and the English teacher there encouraged
me. It went to my head and I've been writing ever since.''
   Born in Japan to American parents who later lived in the
Philippines and China, Miss Whitney saw the United States for the
first time at age 15, after her father died and her mother returned
home. Her mother died three years later and the teen-ager moved in
with an aunt in Chicago.
   ``I did everything. I worked in bookstores and libraries, read
manuscripts and lectured,'' she said of her ongoing attraction to
writing.
   She eventually landed a job as children's book editor for the
Chicago Sun and later had a similar job with The Philadelphia
Inquirer, all the while writing hundreds of short stories, many of
which did not sell.
   Her first hardcover success came in 1941 with ``A Place for
Ann,'' a book for teen-agers. Miss Whitney wrote three dozen novels,
including 20 mysteries, for young people before settling in as a
writer of adult mysteries with the publication of ``The Quicksilver
Pool'' in 1955.
   Among the international best-sellers that followed were ``Feather
on the Moon,'' ``Silversword,'' ``Flaming Tree,'' ``Dream of
Orchids,'' ``Rainsong'' and ``Emerald.'' More than 50 million copies
of her books are available in the United States and 18 foreign
countries, according to her publisher, Doubleday, and all of her
adult novels are still in print.
   Some critics have classified Miss Whitney's work as romantic
suspense, but she rejects that label. ``It's mystery suspense _ a
Whitney kind of book.''
   Indeed, ``Rainbow in the Mist,'' about a clairvoyant who helps
solve one woman's murder and another's disappearance, has only a
whisper of romance.
   The protagonist in ``Rainbow,'' as in all Miss Whitney's books,
is a woman. ``That's the point of view I have. I feel more
comfortable with it.''
   Miss Whitney herself ``was way ahead of talk of women's
liberation. I've always been a liberated woman. I kept my own name''
through two marriages.
   Miss Whitney maintains a rigid, six-day work schedule. ``I get to
my desk by 9 and work until noon.'' The creative process begins
before she sits down at the typewriter _ she shuns a word processor
because ``I couldn't think with all those mechanical things to do.''
   After lunch, she exercises with a brisk walk on the deck that
surrounds her home, then takes a nap. She's back at work at 2 p.m.
and calls it a day at 5.
   Her time away from research and writing is as carefully scheduled
as her work days. Her recreation consists of dinner out and a movie
on Saturday nights with her daughter and son-in-law, who live
nearby, and watching ``Murder, She Wrote'' on television on Sunday
nights. ``I don't have much social life. I like people, but they can
be distracting. Writers have to be disciplined.''
   Her books have been so successful because ``I tell a good story.
I offer optimism. All my books have happy endings. I don't see any
point in letting my readers down at the end. I'm an optimist _
people feel that in my books.''
   Miss Whitney seems to radiate that quality, her youthful spirit
and zest for life belying her age.
   ``I'm not old,'' she said. ``I don't have time to die.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Life'sPrime:LivingWills Adv13   07-10 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Life's Prime: Living Wills, Adv 13,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Living Wills Allow Planning for the Unforeseeable</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Vicki Gottlich is an attorney with the National
Senior Citizens Law Center, which is funded by the Legal Services
Corporation to give support to local legal services programs. It
does not represent individuals; if you have questions, or seek
representation, contact your local bar association or legal services
program.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By VICKI GOTTLICH</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most people, when planning for their future or for an unforeseen
illness, think only of ensuring that their financial affairs are in
order. It is equally important to protect the right to make
health-care decisions.
   Competent adults may consent to or refuse any medical treatment
that is proposed. But suppose they lack the capacity or are no
longer able to make a determination about the treatment. Who would
make that decision? In some cases, doctors would turn to family
members. Or they might go to court to ask that a guardian be
appointed to make medical decisions. The simplest, most effective
way is to give directions in advance about who has authority to
decide, and about what treatment is wanted or not wanted.
   Living wills are the most common document used to plan for future
medical care. Forty states have statutes recognizing living will
declarations. A living will gives directions about the medical
treatment you do or do not want in the event you are terminally ill
and unable to make treatment decisions or give directions to
doctors. It also names the person you decide should carry out your
wishes or should act on your behalf.
   There are limitations to the use of living wills. Because they
can be used only when a person is terminally ill and death is
imminent, they do not help incompetent patients who are not
terminal. If the treatment in question is not ``life-prolonging,''
it also may not be covered.
   Thus, a living will is not effective for an Alzheimer's patient
who needs some medical treatment, such as a cataract operation, but
is unable to give the necessary medical consent to the operation.
Many states prohibit implementation of the declaration if the
patient is pregnant. Others exclude certain types of care from those
that the patient may request to be withheld or withdrawn.
   In the past, powers of attorney were used for financial matters.
The person giving the power (the principal) designates someone else
(the attorney in fact or agent) to make business and financial
decisions for him or her _ sell real estate, invest money, sign a
business contract.
   Traditionally, the principal had to be competent; the power of
attorney terminated upon the principal's incapacity or death.
However, under current law a power of attorney can be ``durable''
and endure or continue in effect even if the principal is
incompetent. More important, states now recognize that the powers
conferred by a durable power of attorney may include the authority
to make health care decisions on behalf of the principal.
   A durable power of attorney for health-care decision-making is a
more versatile document than a living will declaration. It can be
used for all medical decisions, not just those about life-prolonging
treatment, and by all people, not just those who are terminally ill.
In the example given above, if the Alzheimer's patient, while
competent, had executed a durable power of attorney authorizing
someone to make health-care decisions, the person named in the
document would be able to consent to or refuse the cataract
operation.
   Durable powers of attorney can be used to request that
life-sustaining treatment be continued or to request that such
treatment, including food and water, be withheld or withdrawn. Most
important, they allow you to say who should be responsible for
making health-care decisions if you are not able to do so.
   While only some states have specific laws about medical durable
powers of attorney, all states recognize their use. Each state has
its own requirements about who may be named the agent to make the
medical decisions, who may witness the document, and the form the
document should take. States have similar requirements for living
wills.
   A durable power of attorney for health-care decision-making is a
necessary document to protect your right to make health-care
decisions even if you are incapacitated. Simply executing a will, or
signing a durable power of attorney directed to business and
financial matters will not ensure that this right continues past
your incapacity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
