<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Briefs Adv13   07-10 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Briefs, Adv 13,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dentists Should Watch For Abuse of Older Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dentists can help detect abuse or neglect in their
elderly patients because the signs include head, neck and facial
injuries.
   Dr. Thomas J. Bomberg, a professor at the University of Colorado
School of Dentistry, surveyed 3,000 randomly selected U.S. dentists.
Out of the 1,417 who replied, 3 percent had seen or treated an
elderly victim of abuse or neglect and 7.6 percent had suspicions of
such problems among older patients.
   ``In spite dramatic increases in the rate of utilization of
dental services by the aged in recent years,'' Bomberg said, ``The
role of the dentist in the detection, identification, treatment and
follow-up in cases of abuse in the elderly has been largely
ignored.''
   Thirty-eight percent of all abuse involves head, neck or facial
injuries, including broken teeth, facial and lip cuts and broken
jaws, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Hotline Helps Needy Older Americans Get Medical Eye Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People 65 and older can get medical care for
their eyes even if they can't afford it by dialing a nationwide
toll-free helpline at 1-800-222-EYES.
   The National Eye Care Project Helpline has referred nearly
150,000 elderly patients to eye doctors since it was set up three
years ago, according to the American Academy of Ophthalmology.
   To qualify, a patient must be at least 65 and no longer have
access to an eye doctor he or she saw in the past.
   The program pays only for office medical care, not for
eyeglasses, prescription drugs or treatment in hospitals. It was
established to detect and treat eye disease, which is common among
the elderly and can cause blindness.
   The Helpline operates from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. Pacific time, or 11
a.m. to 7 p.m. Eastern time.
   Qualified callers are matched with an eye doctors in their areas.
Doctors have agreed to provide treatment at no cost to the patients.
Patients without medical insurance are treated free of charge; for
those covered by Medicare or other insurance, the doctors will
accept that as payment in full.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Florida Establishes Panel Honoring Claude Pepper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new state commission named for the
late Rep. Claude Pepper will provide a ``road map to the 21st
century'' in dealing with issues of interest to older Floridians,
Gov. Bob Martinez says.
   Martinez signed legislation this month that creates the Claude
Pepper Commission on Aging, whose mandate is to not only protect the
state's 3 million residents over age 60 but also to find ways to
enrich their lives.
   Pepper, D-Fla., who died in May at 88, was the nation's leading
spokesman on issues of concern to older Americans.
   The 18-member panel, which will be controlled by the governor's
office, will serve as an advisory body to the governor and Cabinet,
the Legislature and the state Department of Health and
Rehabilitative Services.
   Six of the commissioners will be appointed by the governor, six
by the speaker of the House and six by the president of the Senate.
Six would have to be over age 60.
   The measure also sets standards for adult congregate living
facilities, creates intermediate facilities to bridge the gap
between congregate homes and nursing homes, bolsters the adult
protective services program to prevent abuse of the elderly and
apprehend abusers and offers housing assistance.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 13</NOTE>
