<SECOND>BC-British Stocks,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Higher at Midday in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher, but off their best
levels, at midday Monday, as an initial speculative run-up in early
trading evaporated when no follow-through buying emerged.
   Market watchers said trading got off to a good start on weekend
press coverage that the lower dollar and easier U.S. interest rates
would bode well for global economies. In addition, the press
comments mentioned a handful of potential bids, sparking a buying
spree in selected stocks.
   But buying later dried up, as players adopted a more cautious
stance amid a week chock full of economic indicators from both sides
of the Atlantic.
   At about 12:15 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share
index was 3.9 points, or 0.2 percent, higher at 2,193.0, slightly
above its early morning minimum of 2,192.4. At midmorning, the index
had risen as much as 8.4 points to 2,197.5.
   Volume came to a light 218.1 million shares by midday, compared
with 565.2 million shares at the same time Friday.
</TEXT>
