<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Iraq-Oil     07-10 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iraq-Oil,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Iraqi Pipeline To Start Soon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's $1.5 billion oil pipeline across
Saudi Arabia to the Red Sea will open on schedule in September,
significantly boosting its export capacity, the Middle East Economic
Survey reported Monday.
   However, Iraq said it would adhere to its Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries production quota of 2.783 million
barrels a day despite its increased capacity.
   The respected oil industry weekly quoted an unidentified senior
Iraqi oil source as saying that delays caused by a four-month strike
at South Korea's Hyundai Engineering and Construction Co., which was
producing units for an offshore terminal, ``have been absorbed.''
   The strike, which ended in April, had triggered speculation that
the opening of the 56-inch, 580-mile pipeline would be delayed until
the end of the year.
   The pipeline will link into another pipeline that runs from
Iraq's southern port of el-Zubair. It was built along with pipelines
through Turkey during the Iran-Iraq war, when Baghdad's vital oil
export routes through the Gulf were cut off.
   The offshore terminal in the Red Sea will be able to handle
tankers of up to 400,000 tons. At least one of three planned loading
berths will now be ready by September, the newsletter reported.
   The pipeline is being built by Italy's Saipem Co. for a
consortium that includes Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industries and
Mitsubish Corp, Italy's Snamprogetti and France's Spie Capag Co.
   IPSA-2, as the pipeline is called, will have an initial capacity
of around 800,000 barrels a day, with full capacity of 1.65 million
barrels a day early next year, MEES reported.
   With export capacity from the southern el-Bakr terminal on the
Persian Gulf expected to rise to 2 million barrels a day next year,
Iraq's production capacity should reach an estimated 4.5 million
barrels a day next year.
   Oil Minister Issam Abdul al-Chalabi sad last month that war
damage to the al-Bakr platform, a deep water terminal, has been
repaired.
   The weekly newsletter reported that Iraq's oil policy was based
on Iraq's desire to maximize revenue and stabilize prices ``rather
than a maximization of production and price competition.''
   Baghdad also prefers ``strategic flexibility to give the country
the necessary options after its experience in the Gulf War, when at
one point only the Turkish pipeline, with less than 1 million
barrels a day capacity, was in operation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
