<DOCNO> AP890710-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Toyota-SecondShift     07-10 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Toyota-Second Shift,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Trying to Meet Demand For Camrys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The extra 400 cars a day being produced by
a second shift at Toyota Motor Corp.'s main assembly plant may
double annual production and still not meet customer requests,
company officials said.
   ``We've had a problem meeting the market's demand for Camrys,''
said Alex Warren, senior vice president of administration for Toyota.
   The Camry is one of the top-selling cars in the United States.
Last year, more than 200,000 were sold here. This year, Toyota
expects sales of 250,000 to 260,000, Warren said.
   As of June, Toyota had only enough cars in inventory to sell for
23 days, said Debra Sanchez Fair, a spokeswoman for Toyota Motor
Sales U.S.A. in Torrence, Calif. The industry standard for normal
inventory is 60 days.
   ``The Camry is our No. 1 volume vehicle,'' she said. And June was
a record month, despite a slowdown in the auto industry.
   By year end, Toyota management expects the Georgetown plant to
make 800 cars a day _ 200,000 a year. This past week, the first
shift was producing 400 a day while the second shift was making 275.
   Warren said there is no specific timetable for the acceleration.
   ``We're not as worried about the numbers as we are the quality,''
he said.
   Hiring at the plant is complete, and the new employees trained
with the first shift through May and early June. Slowly, the hours
for the second shift were changed so the workers could spend some
time working on their own each day. In mid-June, the two shifts were
completely split.
   The first shift works from 6:15 a.m. to 3:15 p.m. The second
shift works from 5:15 p.m. to 2:15 a.m. Hiring for the second shift
began in January and ended two weeks ago.
   The plant now employs between 2,800 and 2,900, with about 1,250
workers on the line for each shift, Warren said.
   Hiring for the power-train plant _ where engines, axles and
steering components will be assembled _ will continue through the
end of 1990. By then, the two plants could employ as many as 3,500,
Warren said. The power-train plant is scheduled to be completed by
next summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
