<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-10 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Forecasts Pressure Crop Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, weighed down
by forecasts for increasing chances of rain in the Midwestern Corn
Belt as the week progresses.
   The corn market opened with unexpectedly sharp losses despite a
weekend of extremely hot, mostly dry weather in most growing areas.
   ``I think the main impact here is the chance of rain,'' said
William Biedermann, a vice president and director of research with
Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage based in Crystal Lake, Ill.
   The wheat market was modestly lower in response to
better-than-expected yields of winter wheat. Harvesting of the crop
is nearing completion in the Great Plains.
   The main event in the grain markets this week should be the
Agriculture Department's report on corn and soybean plantings, which
is scheduled for release after the close of trading on Wednesday.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $4.03 a bushel; corn was 4 cents to
4} cents lower with July at $2.69} a bushel; oats were 4} cents to
5{ cents lower with July at $1.53 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents
lower to 2{ cents higher with July at $7.69 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .27 cent lower with August at 69.60
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher
with August at 80.75 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .68
cent higher with July at 47.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .05 cent to .15 cent higher with July at 31 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
