<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CVN-QVCMerger     07-10 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CVN-QVC Merger,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>CVN Agrees To Be Acquired By QVC in Video Shopping Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CVN Companies Inc. has agreed to be
acquired by QVC Network Inc., a smaller competitor in the televised
home shopping business, for more than $400 million in cash and
stock, the companies said today.
   The deal would create a company that backers said could better
compete against the video retailing leader, Home Shopping Network
Inc., in an industry that generated an estimated $1.4 billion in
revenue last year.
   The agreement calls for QVC, of West Chester, Pa., to purchase
all CVN common stock for $19 a share in cash plus one-eighth of a
share in QVC common stock.
   CVN, which operates the Cable Value Network, the Fashion Channel
and America's Shopping Channel, had about 18.3 million shares of
stock outstanding, making that cash portion of the deal worth about
$350 million.
   The stock portion of the deal would add another $40 million to
the price of the transaction at recent prices. QVC closed at $17.88
a share in national over-ther-counter trading while CVN closed at
$18.75 a share.
   CVN also warrants and options outstanding that would add another
$25 million to the value of the deal, the companies indicated.
   The merger is subject to approval by shareholders of both
companies as well as securing federal regulatory approval. The
companies said they hoped the deal could be completed in September.
   QVC, which operates the QVC cable network, has arranged for a
financing commitment of $435 million from the Bank of New York. It
has also received a commitment from Comcast Corp. to buy $30 million
of convertible subordinated debentures.
   QVC had net sales of $213 million in the year ended May 31,
substantially smaller than CVN's $637.8 million in the same period.
However, QVC has an exclusive TV agreement to sell Sears, Roebuck
merchandise.
   CVN reported serving some 23.3 million cable subscribers to 14.1
million for QVC.
   ``The combination of QVC and CVN will allow for more effective
direct marketing efforts which will result in increased subscriber
acceptance and satisfaction,'' CVN Chairman Theodore Deikel said in
a statement. ``The combination will also enhance the opportunities
for long-term growth.''
   CVN said its board decided that the QVC offer would benefit
shareholders more than CVN's previously announced plan to issue a
special $10 a share dividend. If CVN shareholders approve the
merger, the dividend will be canceled.
   After the merger, QVC said it intends to continue both companies'
television shopping programs.
   QVC said it does not intend to make any substantial changes in
CVN operations before the end of the year to allow time for teams
from both companies to evaluate ways to enhance productivity.
   Joseph M. Segal, QVC's chairman, said his company would still
reach fewer homes with its CVN and QVC shopping programs than Home
Shopping Network does.
   But he said QVC would be able to compete more effectively and
``reach a sales level comparable to HSN's'' if the deal goes through
because the company would be abler to offer consumers more
diversified shopping programs and merchandise choices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f AM-TimesAppointments     07-10 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Times Appointments,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joseph Lelyveld Named Deputy Managing Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Lelyveld has been named deputy managing
editor of The New York Times and is expected to succeed Arthur Gelb
as managing editor, the newspaper announced.
   The Times announced that Lelyveld's promotion from foreign editor
was effective July 16.
   Gelb, 65, is expected to retire from the news department early
next year and move to a senior position in the Times Company.
   ``We are therefore temporarily reviving the job of deputy
managing editor so that Arthur and Joe can work side by side to
prepare an orderly transition,'' said Max Frankel, executive editor.
   The Times also announced that David R. Jones, editor of national
editions, will become an assistant managing editor. Bernard
Gwertzman, who has been Lelyveld's deputy, will become foreign
editor.
   Lelyveld, 52, who won the Pulitzer Prize in 1986 for his book
about South Africa, ``Move Your Shadow,'' has been a reporter in New
York and Washington and a correspondent in the Congo, India, Hong
Kong, Britain and South Africa.
   A graduate of Harvard and the Columbia Graduate School of
Journalism, Lelyveld has been a national correspondent for The Times
Magazine and deputy foreign editor from 1977 to 1980. He became
foreign editor in December 1986.
   Jones, 56, who has been at The Times since 1963, was assistant
news editor of the Washington bureau, assistant national editor and
national editor before being named editor of national editions in
1987.
   Gwertzman, 54, worked as a correspondent in Moscow and served as
chief diplomatic correspondent from 1972 until becoming deputy
foreign editor in 1987. He joined the Times' Washington bureau in
1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
