<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with closing prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on London's stock exchange ended
higher Monday, as the market continued to draw inspiration from
takeover speculation.
   However, trading volume was extremely low, reflecting the absence
of strong institutional buying interest, dealers said. A slim 417.6
million shares were traded, compared with the 774.8 million shares
which changed hands Friday.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 6.1
points, or 0.3 percent, at 2,195.2 at the close, above a late
afternoon low of 2,189.4, but below an early high of 2,197.5.
   ``There's still quite a lot of speculative interest bubbling in
the market,'' one trader said, noting that a shortage of stock among
market makers accentuated the rises in many stock prices.
   Traders said the market also was encouraged by a healthy
performance on Wall Street as London trading wound down.
   The Financial Times 30-share index rose 5.1 points to close at
1,820.1. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 1.44 points to
close at 1,247.56.
</TEXT>
