<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     07-10 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply In Europe, Gold Also Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell sharply Monday in European
trading on speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve will continue to
ease its grip on credit.
   Gold prices were also lower as the market continued to
consolidate gains from last week, dealers said.
   Last Friday's U.S. job figures for June, indicating a slowdown in
the economy, came on the heels of other reports that showed sluggish
growth. Dealers said this was likely to persuade the Federal Reserve
to ease monetary policy and lower interest rates.
   As U.S. interest rates fall, the dollar becomes a less attractive
investment.
   The dollar's decline also gained momentum in Europe because it
broke several key support points on technical charts, they said.
   ``We're still driven by technical factors,'' said a corporate
adviser at a U.S. bank in London.
   ``The market here was dominated by technical trading,'' said a
dealer at a large Frankfurt bank. ``We had executions of stop-loss
orders as the dollar fell, and this drove it even lower.'' A
stop-loss order is an order to sell to minimize losses in a
declining market.
   ``The dollar is bound to be weak until we find a bottom,'' added
one London dealer.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.37 yen to a closing 139.28 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a lower rate of 138.95 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6410 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6245 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Friday, included: 1.8575 West German marks, down from 1.8840; 1.5960
Swiss francs, down from 1.6200; 6.3005 French francs, down from
6.3915; 2.0988 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1272; 1,354.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,368.00; and 1.18835 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1907.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $381.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $385.25.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid of $383.45 an ounce
compared with $384.60 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 29 cents to close at a bid
$383.27 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid of $5.21 a troy ounce, compared with
Friday's $5.37.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
