<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     07-10 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0357</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market worked its way higher in quiet
trading today amid expectations of further easing of the Federal
Reserve's credit policy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 12.33 to 2,500.19 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 871 up, 498 down and
539 unchanged.
   Analysts said talk of a recent gradual turn by the Fed toward a
policy of easier credit has been reinforced by a decline in the
interest rate on federal funds, or overnight loans between banks.
   Rates on long-term government bonds, which crested well above 9
percent earlier this year, have lately dropped to the threshold of 8
percent.
   New York's Chase Manhattan Bank and a few smaller banks today
lowered their prime lending rates from 11 percent to 10.5 percent.
   Wall Street's optimists argue that the decline in the cost of
borrowed money will help cushion the business impact of slowing
economic growth, which has been evident for the past several months.
   Worries persist in the financial world, however, about the
prospective effects of a throttled-down economy on corporate profits.
   American Medical International led the active list, up 3 at 26[.
The company, which put itself on the block last month, agreed to be
acquired by an investor group for $26.50 a share in cash plus new
stock.
   Takeover rumors and speculation sparked buying in such issues as
UAL, up 4} at 170}, and Honeywell, up 2| at 80].
   Gainers among the blue chip and technology stocks included
General Motors, up \ at 40]; International Business Machines, up 2
at 114[; General Electric, up \ at 53], and Digital Equipment, up }
at 96{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.77 to 182.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .39 at 364.14.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 92.51 million shares with two
hours to go.
