<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Fall Sharply On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn, soybean and oat futures closed sharply lower
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade in anticipation of cooler,
wetter weather in the Midwest.
   Wheat futures finished moderately lower.
   Private meteorologists predicted rainfall of \ inch to 1{ inches
covering 30 percent to 60 percent of the Midwestern corn and soybean
fields by Wednesday.
   Expectations for a bearish mid-week crop report prompted further
selling of corn and soybean futures. The Agriculture Department is
set to release estimates of planted acreage for those crops after
the close of trading on Wednesday.
   Private analysts and traders expect the USDA report to show
modest increases in planted acreage since last year, but many have
lowered their expectations because of heavy rains that have made
planting impossible in parts of the eastern Corn Belt and the
Southeast.
   ``It's one thing to fight weather and another thing to fight
weather if these acreage reports are gong to be negative,'' said Pat
O'Connell, a grain-market analyst in Chicago with Refco Inc.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 5{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.99{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 13{ cents lower with July at $2.63 a bushel; oats were 10\ cents
to 11{ cents lower with July at $1.47 a bushel; and soybeans were
18{ cents to 32{ cents lower with July at $7.43{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
