<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices declined Monday in quiet
trading.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, slipped 39 cents to settle at $20.36 a barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange, after rising 45 cents on
Friday. Other contract months also fell.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
August contract for home heating oil closed at 48.79 cents a gallon,
down 0.98 cent. The contract lost 0.12 cent on Friday.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery declined 0.13
cent to settle at 56.46 cents a gallon, after rising 0.32 cent
Friday.
   Andrew Lebow, a trader with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said prices appeared to be moving within a broad trading range
amid light volume.
   ``The market's not going anywhere. It's kind of trading
sideways,'' he said. ``There's no real rhyme and reason.''
   Energy futures prices have fluctuated in recent days in response
to labor problems affecting North Sea oil operations, but Lebow said
it was unlikely a they would have a major impact on exports.
</TEXT>
