<DOCNO> AP890710-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-10 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Forecasts Knock Down Corn, Soybean Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn, soybean and oat futures prices fell Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade in anticipation of cooler, wetter weather in the
Midwestern Corn Belt.
   Wheat futures finished moderately lower.
   On other markets, gold and silver advanced, while energy,
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 5{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.99{ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents to 13} cents
lower with July at $2.63{ a bushel; oats were 10\ cents to 11{ cents
lower with July at $1.47 a bushel; soybeans were 18{ cents to 32{
cents lower with July at $7.43} a bushel.
   The declines in the corn, oat and soybean markets exceeded the
normal daily price limits in those markets, which are, respectively,
10 cents, 10 cents and 30 cents a bushel. The Board of Trade had
raised the limits by 50 percent following limit-up moves in all
three markets last Wednesday. The limits return to normal on Tuesday.
   Private meteorologists predicted rainfall of \ inch to 1{ inches
covering 30 percent to 60 percent of the Midwestern corn and soybean
fields by mid-week.
   Precipitation is badly needed in the western Corn Belt states of
Iowa, Missouri, Illinois and Minnesota, particularly with the corn
crop now in the pollination stage. Soybeans are several weeks away
from their most crucial phase.
   A National Weather Service six-to-10-day forecast issued after
the close predicted below-normal temperatures and above-normal
rainfall for most Midwestern crop areas during the early and middle
portions of next week.
   Expectations for a bearish Agriculture Department crop report on
Wednesday added to the sell-off of grain and soybean futures.
   Private analysts and traders expect the USDA report to show
modest increases in planted corn and soybean acres for the first
time since 1984.
   ``It's one thing to fight weather and another thing to fight
weather if these acreage reports are going to be negative,'' said
Pat O'Connell, a grain-market analyst in Chicago with Refco Inc.
   Gold and silver futures edged higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to a weak dollar and the third consecutive
decline in the Commodity Research Bureau's index of 21 commodity
prices.
   The CRB index's fall of 3.20 points to 229.25 was perceived as a
recessionary signal.
   Gold settled 90 cents higher across the board with August at
$383.60 a troy ounce; silver was 1.9 cents to 2 cents higher with
July at $5.229 a troy ounce.
   Most oil futures prices declined in quiet trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Andrew Lebow, a trader with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said prices appeared to be moving within a broad trading range
amid light volume.
   ``The market's not going anywhere. It's kind of trading
sideways,'' he said. ``There's no real rhyme and reason.''
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 39 cents lower to 6
cents higher with August at $20.36 a barrel; heating oil was .49
cent to .98 cent lower with August at 48.79 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .17 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August at 56.46
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
with support stemming from higher prices and pressure coming from
expectations for lower prices due to a slowdown in marketings.
   Pork futures were mostly higher on firmer cash prices.
   Live cattle settled .60 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August
at 69.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .20
cent higher with August at 80.97 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent
lower to .48 cent higher with July at 47.37 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .08 cent lower to .75 cent higher with July at
30.77 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
