<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 1836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Nike     07-10 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nike,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Athletic Shoe Maker Builds Future on Diversification, Segmenting
Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Nike Inc. went public in 1980, Business Week
magazine wondered whether the athletic shoe maker's move to the
stock market meant that the jogging craze had run its course.
   Now, at the other end of the decade, the company named for the
Greek goddess of victory is planning for future success around
people's continuing fascination with fitness.
   ``People said Nike has helped but also has taken a ride on the
running boom,'' said Nike co-founder Philip H. Knight. ``What we
used to call the running boom was really just the first shot of the
fitness revolution.''
   Knight, Nike's chairman and chief executive officer, said in an
interview that he believes this revolution has led to lifestyle
changes that will keep the momentum rolling for sales of athletic
shoes.
   Working out has become a habit for more people _ whether they
like it or not _ because they know it's good for them, said Knight.
``You might get bored with sleeping but you've still got to do it.''
   Knight was in New York on Monday to for a news conference, the
first in the Beaverton, Ore.-based company's history, to release
Nike's latest financial results.
   He also delivered his message to Wall Street securities analysts.
The analysts apparently weren't completely satisfied with what they
heard. In nationwide over-the-counter trading, Nike stock sank $1 to
close at $42.75 Monday.
   The company reported a 19.7 percent profit gain for the quarter
ended May 31. Income rose to $36.46 million, or 97 cents a share,
from $30.47 million, or 81 cents a share, in the same quarter a year
earlier. Sales totaled $413.42 million, a 16.6 percent increase over
$354.42 million in the 1988 quarter.
   In the 12 months ended May 31, Nike's earnings rose 64.3 percent
to $167.05 million, or $4.45 a share, from $101.7 million, or $2.70
a share. Sales for the year grew 42.5 percent to $1.71 billion from
$1.20 billion.
   Having had such a good year hasn't made Nike complacent,
particularly because the 1984-1988 period was trying for the
company. Sales, which had been growing steadily, sagged to $876.5
million in 1987 from $1.07 billion in 1986.
   During those years, rival shoe manufacturer Reebok International
Ltd. rode the crest of the aerobics wave to become a major force in
the athletic footwear business. And L.A. Gear carved out a slice of
the market for itself, becoming a brand sought after by girls and
young women.
   Meanwhile, Nike made a few missteps. It introduced entries in the
casual segment of the sports shoe market under the Nike brand name
but they didn't go anywhere. The verdict was that consumers couldn't
accept leisure footwear from a company better known for
high-performance athletic shoes.
   ``It was a little like Levis trying to sell suits,'' Knight
recalled.
   The company seems to have learned from that episode. It no longer
peddles shoes designed for casual wear using the Nike name. In 1988,
it boosted the base of its sport-casual division by debuting i.e., a
line of athletically inspired shoes targeted at women in the 25-35
age group. This year, Nike is bringing out Side 1, a line of sporty
and fashionable shoes for teen-age girls.
   In another move to branch out within the footwear field, Nike
acquired Cole-Haan, a Maine-based maker of high-end dress and casual
shoes, in June 1988.
   Knight said the recent diversification into other footwear
categories has been handled so the brands can develop on their own,
independent of Nike's flagship shoe lines.
   There is the chance of some overlap. For instance, Knight said
Nike's footwear researchers are studying the possibility of
incorporating advances in athletic footwear into street shoes.
   To help build sales growth in the athletic shoe business, Nike
has cultivated individual market segments and developed shoes
ntended for specific pursuits.
   Its running shoes have been joined over the years by footwear for
basketball, walking, hiking and windsurfing, for example. Nike
created a whole new category when it created its cross-training
shoe, aimed at people who follow varied exercise regimens.
   Apparel has become an important part of Nike's business and
Knight said the company is working with retailers to more closely
coordinate the marketing of clothing and shoes.
   ``We think we have a lot of room to grow in apparel,'' Knight
said.
</TEXT>
