<FIRST>u f AM-Time 1stld-Writethru f0119 07-10 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time, 1st ld - Writethru, f0119,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Head to Delaware for Showdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBs 7th graf pvs to UPDATE with closing stock prices.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The struggle for Time Inc. enters a key phase
Tuesday as the media giant and its hostile pursuer, Paramount
Communications Corp., enter a Delaware courtroom for what could be
the pivotal confrontation of their five-week-old takeover fight.
   Paramount, trying to force Time's board to seriously consider its
$12.2 billion hostile bid, will argue that Time put itself up for
sale when it agreed to a friendly stock-swap merger with Warner
Communications Inc. earlier this year and therefore must consider
competing offers.
   Time will argue that its board never contemplated selling the
company and that the agreement with Warner _ which has since been
changed to a $14 billion tender offer for Warner _ stemmed from the
ordinary conduct of Time's business.
   Tuesday's hearing before Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen in
Wilmingon has been anxiously awaited by the companies and their
employees and by Time stockholders, who could profit handsomely if
Paramount's $200 a share bid succeeds. Several major shareholders
also will be in court Tuesday, seeking to stop the Time-Warner
merger.
   Allen's decision could affect more than just these three
companies: if Time loses, the climate for friendly mergers in this
country could change radically. Many of the biggest U.S.
corporations are incorporated in Delaware and subject to its laws.
   Observers have said it is difficult to predict how Allen will
rule. But investors have grown pessimistic about Paramount's chances
of success, and Time's stock price _ which hit a high of $182.75
after Paramount announced its bid June 6 _ dropped back sharply as
some traders decided to take their profits before the battle went to
court.
   Time stock rose $1.12{ to $152.62{ a share Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange. Warner stock rose 25 cents to $62 a share and
Paramount dipped 25 cents to $56.75 a share.
   The issue in Tuesday's hearing, according to Duke University Law
School professor James D. Cox, is whether entering into negotiations
with Warner ``triggers the auctioneer role for the (Time) directors,
or can their conduct merely be judged by the business judgment
rule.''
   The business judgment rule, a widely-followed legal concept,
allows decisions made by directors in the normal course of business
to stand. Courts generally are reluctant to disturb such decisions.
   Time's lawyers might argue that the Time-Warner merger deal was
the result of two years of on-again, off-again negotiations. Time
chairman J. Richard Munro hinted the company was considering a
merger when he told securities analysts last November that Time
intended to be among the growing ranks of global media conglomerates.
   But Paramount might contend _ as the company stated in the
prospectus for its offer _ that its chairman, Martin S. Davis,
raised the possibility of a merger between Paramount and Time ``on
several occasions during the past several years.''
   That raises the question of whether Time entered into the merger
agreement as a defensive step. If that were the case, Time _ which
has rejected the Paramount bid as inadequate and highly conditional
_ would be forced to consider buyout offers.
   Michael Bradley, a law professor at the University of Michigan,
said the planned merger did not appear to meet the criteria under
which a company must be considered up for sale.
   ``If Time were thinking of restructuring or some other drastic
move, like a leveraged buyout, that would cross that threshhold,''
Bradley said. ``It's not clear that the negotiations put them into
that posture.''
   Bernard Black, a professor at the Columbia University School of
Law, said, ``I would be very surprised if the Delaware court stops
Time from buying Warner, partly because it's a pre-existing
transaction.''
   But other observers say the issue revolves around the unequal
stock positions between Time and Warner in their original merger
proposal. Under that agreement, the current Warner shareholders
would have 60 percent of the stock in Time Warner Inc. while the
current Time shareholders would have 40 percent.
   Melvin A. Eisenberg, who teaches law at the University of
California at Berkeley, said, ``It's ridiculous to say Time is
buying if Warner is getting 60 percent of the equity.''
   Under the original merger proposal, Time stockholders would have
received a share in the new company for each share they owned while
Warner shareholders would have received 0.465 of a share of the new
Time-Warner for each of their Warner shares.
   There are other issues for Allen to consider, including whether
Time's shareholders should be allowed to decide the future of the
company.
   Allen's ruling, expected later this week, will not settle the
matter because the losing side is expected to appeal to the Delaware
Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
