<FIRST>u f AM-Time-Paramount     07-10 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Paramount,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Offers to Add Interest to Bid for Time if Delays Develop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Time Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of an important court hearing,
Paramount Communications Inc. said Monday it would add interest to
its hostile $12.2 billion offer for Time Inc. if certain delays
prevent it from closing the deal.
   Paramount said it had amended its offer of $200 per share in cash
for all of Time's stock to give shareholders an additional interest
payment of 9 percent annually if it is delayed beyond 60 days in
getting needed regulatory approvals for transfer of cable licenses
needed to complete the deal.
   The interest would begin accruing 60 days after Time either
agrees or is ordered to refrain from interfering with Paramount's
efforts to obtain FCC and state and local cable regulatory
approvals, Paramount said.
   That would add about $1.50 a share to the bid each month.
   Donald Oresman, general counsel of Paramount, said ``our
willingness to pay interest if the company cannot close its deal
within 60 days ``underscores our confidence that regulatory
approvals can be obtained within that period if Time's
obstructionist tactics are stopped.''
   Time offered no comment on the new terms of Paramount's offer,
but previously rejected Paramount's bid as inadequate and too
conditional, saying among other things that it would likely take a
year or more for Paramount to obtain the necessary approvals for
cable license transfers.
   But a source close to Time said Paramount's addition of interest
to its ``reprsents a belated admission that it will take Paramount a
substantial period of time to obtain the necessary regulatory
approvals.''
   Paramount has contended it could win the necessary approvals
within a few months if it were given the chance, but has complained
that Time has been drumming up opposition among local cable
regulators to Paramount's efforts.
   Paramount stepped into the battle for Time in June as Time neared
a shareholder vote on its proposed merger with Warner Communications
Inc. in a deal that would create the world's largest media and
entertainment company.
   Time subsequently amended its merger plan and now is offering $14
billion in cash and securities for Warner's stock. In making that
bid, Time said it would sweeten its offer at a rate of 9 percent a
year if it were unable to complete the offer within 60 days.
   Paramount's decision to add interest to its tender offer for Time
was announced on the eve of a hearing set for Tuesday in Delaware
Chancery Court over a suit that could determine who will win control
of Time.
   Paramount and some Time shareholders want the court to block
Time's acquisition of Warner. They are expected to argue that Time
put itself up for sale when it agreed to merger with Warner and that
Time has not fairly considered Paramount's bid.
   In a separate filing Monday with the Federal Communications
Commission, Paramount said it already has filed transfer
applications representing the majority of subscribers to cable
systems operated by Time's 82 percent-owned American Television and
Communications Corp. where such approvals are required.
</TEXT>
