<FIRST>u f AM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru f0255 07-10 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0255,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Marks Start Of Memorial Period</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 2nd graf to UPDATE with violence in Matewan;
picks up 3rd graf, `Gunfire also ...' INSERTS 5 grafs after 16th graf,
``Everyone might...' to UPDATE with Westmoreland not being able to fill
orders, judge in Viginia jailing three miners for blocking convoy; picks
up 17th graf pvs, `In New...'. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cooling-off period called by the
United Mine Workers was shattered almost as soon as it began Monday
by gunfire at a non-union mine and an explosion that damaged a coal
company trailer.
   The owner of a security agency working at the non-union mine in
Boomer said about 150 people, some in masks and camouflage paint,
ambushed his employees around dawn, overturning two trucks and a car
and injuring several guards.
   In Matewan, union supporters confronted a convoy of 15 to 18
non-union coal trucks shortly before Gov. Gaston Caperton was to
promote an area tourism program, said Bennett Hatfield, whose Rawl
Sales and Processing Co. owns the trucks.
   State police said four trucks were disabled, with some flat tires
and some damage.
   One non-union driver was slightly injured, said a state police
who refused to give her name.
   Caperton arrived after the incident and proceeded with his
schedule.
   Gunfire also was reported at a Mingo County mine.
   UMW President Richard Trumka called the three-day ``memorial
period,'' a work stoppage permitted under the union's national
contract, in what he said was an effort to restore calm to the
Appalachian and Midwestern coal fields.
   More than 30,000 UMW members have been engaged in a wildcat
strike throughout Appalachia and the Midwest in support of 1,900
union members on strike since April against Pittston in Virginia,
West Virginia and Kentucky.
   The wildcat strikers have ignored repeated back-to-work orders
from federal judges.
   In Virginia, an explosion early Monday damaged an office trailer
owned by Clinchfield Coal Co., Pittston's main subsidiary in
Virginia.
   The explosion, believed caused by a bomb, occurred shortly after
midnight along a road near Nora, said State Police Sgt. Mike Frank.
   In West Virginia, Cliff Nuckols, head of a security agency at
Appalachian Mining Inc., said scores of people converged on the mine
entrance in Boomer. Shots rang out, and several guards who scuffled
with the attackers suffered minor injuries, he said.
   ``They sneaked through the weeds. You can't see them. They come
through the weeds and the woods and all of a sudden you're just
looking at them. They're there,'' Nuckols said. ``It was pitch
black. The whole thing happened within 30-40 seconds.''
   State Police are investigating, said Sgt. J.L. Miller. He said
the attackers ``stormed the landing, escorted two guards down the
hill and told them to hit the road.''
   In West Virginia's Mingo County, Sid Young, a driver for
non-union Hampden Coal Co., said the mine was hit by gunfire early
Monday. No injuries were reported.
   The national coal contract allots 10 ``memorial days'' on which
miners do not have to report to work. Such days usually are used to
air labor grievances.
   Westmoreland Coal Co. miners were not included in Trumka's
three-day holiday because its miners in Virginia have used their
allotment.
   But company spokesman Steve Anderson said the miners remained off
the job Monday, their first scheduled day back after their annual
two-week summer vacation.
   ``Everyone might have been too optimistic that we might see
people return to work when the vacations over. It's not happening,''
he said.
   In Philadelphia, Westmoreland announced that it has advised seven
overseas customers, whose shipments represented 308,176 tons, that
it can't ship the coal because of production shortages resulting
from the wildcat strike.
   The company said if production doesn't resume by the end of this
week, it will be unable to fill additional export orders for 165,865
tons.
   Also Monday, a federal judge in Big Stone Gap, Va., sentenced
three striking miners to jail terms ranging from three days to three
months for driving in slow-moving convoys to block coal trucks.
   U.S. District Judge Glen Williams, who complained last week that
huge fines were doing nothing to stop the convoys, tried another
approach, finding the men guilty of contempt of court, the Wise
County clerk said.
   A fourth miner was found innocent.
   In New York, Trumka joined Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., and
Gary White, head of the West Virginia Coal Operators Association, in
assuring Japanese steel officials that the supply of Appalachian
coal is reliable despite the Pittston strike.
   ``We cannot afford to allow the Pittston strike to jeopardize
West Virginia's high standing in international coal markets,''
Rockefeller said in a statement.
   Japan bought 13 million tons of U.S. coal last year, about half
of it from West Virginia and an increase of 3 million tons over 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890710-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GreekBankSuit     07-10 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greek Bank Suit,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Bank Sued for $1.5 Billion By Depositors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney representing about 300 depositors in a
Greek bank filed a lawsuit Monday seeking $1.5 billion in damages
and restitution for the depositors, who claim their funds were
removed from the country and frozen.
   Attorney Constantine Kangles said the class-action lawsuit filed
in U.S. District Court would seek treble damages for U.S. depositors
in the National Mortgage Bank of Greece.
   Kangles maintained that the bank used its U.S. offices to prey on
immigrant Greeks by promising them high interest rates on deposits
and that the earnings would be tax-free.
   Last month, federal authorities raided U.S. offices of the bank,
seized documents and arrested 14 of its officers on racketeering
charges.
   A bank spokesman Monday denied the charges in the lawsuit.
   ``Not one bank account in Greece has been frozen,'' said the
spokesman, Dimitris Klitorakis, speaking in Athens.
   ``The reports are incorrect, not to say downright false,''
Klitorakis said. He said the deposits have been transferred to the
Bank of Greece, the nation's central bank, ``and can be requested in
the form of checks or remittances for any destination.''
   The only deposits that had been frozen were those made at the
time of the U.S. authorities' raid, he said.
   He added that the number of people who had requested their money
back was ``negligible.''
   Barry Slotnick, a New York attorney representing the bank, said
all U.S. representative offices of the bank were being staffed and
that American depositors would have access to their funds next week.
   The civil lawsuit against the bank and 14 of its officers came
after federal authorities announced an investigation of the bank and
the officers for racketeering. On June 21, authorities raided seven
branches in Illinois, Massachusetts, New York and Pennsylvania,
seizing documents and arresting the officers.
   The bank is charged with illegally accepting more than $700
million in deposits from customers in the United States and sending
the money overseas so the depositors could avoid U.S. taxes,
according to a complaint filed in U.S. District Court in New York.
   The National Mortgage Bank of Greece is a separate entity from
the state-owned National Bank of Greece, which also operates in the
United States. The National Bank of Greece owns about 47 percent of
the mortgage bank, according to federal authorities.
   In ads placed in Greek language newspapers, bank officers
promised customers interest rates as high as 18 percent that would
be paid in Greek drachmas and would not be disclosed to U.S.
authorities, Kangles said.
   He said about 300 people are behind the lawsuit, but their ranks
could swell to as many as 3,000. The $1.5 billion represents treble
damages based on an estimated $500 million in deposits involved, he
said.
   The mortgage bank's branches were not even legally authorized to
accept money from customers in the United States, authorities say.
Rather, the U.S. branches were opened with the ostensible purpose of
encouraging investment in Greece.
   Mortgage Bank says deposits in the United States were made at
Bankers' Trust and Atlantic Bank branches, not at Mortgage Bank.
Both those banks, as well as Mortgage Bank, are controlled by the
National Bank of Greece.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
